{"title_page": "Vanderveer Projects", "text_new": "'''Vendeever Projects''' now known as \"Flatbush Gardens\", is a large low-income federal housing project located in [[East Flatbush, Brooklyn]]. Consisting of 59 six-story buildings on 30 acres, it contains 2,496 units housing about 13,000 residents. Until October 2005 Flatbush Gardens was, called Vanderveer Estates and was one of the most disreputable federally financed projects in the country. Handed off among about seven owners during 20 years, Vanderveer became a poster child for federally financed failures in moderate-income housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/13/nyregion/a-long-troubled-complex-hopes-to-flourish-again.html|title=A Long-Troubled Complex Hopes to Flourish Again|first1=Andy|last1=Newman|first2=Michael|last2=Brick|date=January 13, 2004|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Vanderveer.jpg|thumb]] -->\n\n==History==\nThe project was built in 1949 and 1950 on the site of the old Flatbush Water Works as a haven for working families. The complex held about 13,000 people with 2,496 units. During the early years some building lobbies had chandeliers and potted plants, but over the years the buildings slowly decayed. \nIn 1981, the owners did $23 million in renovations but botched the job so completely that the city, which helped finance the work, ended up suing the managers. In 1987 Foster Apartments bought the project and renamed it New Vanderveer Estates and made $8 million in repairs, started a free summer camp and got the vacancy rate down to 2 percent but two years later, the complex had begun to deteriorate once again. With a high vacancy rate, the project began to decline with crime being a main problem.\nIn 1979 A 35-year-old woman was shot to death by a policeman in her apartment after she slashed a sergeant in the upper left arm with a knife while resisting an attempt to evict her. Police officials said a single shot fired by another officer had killed the woman. She fell near the entrance of her sparsely furnished studio apartment at 1413 New York Avenue. Three officers and a city marshal were apparently present when the shooting occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/08/30/archives/brooklyn-woman-35-slain-after-slashing-an-officer-death-follows.html|title=Brooklyn Woman, 35, Slain After Slashing an Officer|first=Joseph P.|last=Fried|date=August 30, 1979|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\nProblems worsened in the 1980s during the [[Crack epidemic]] After drug dealers set up shop in the apartments. It became notorious for shootings due to the open drug market in the buildings. Tenants stated drug dealers operated openly from basements, and gangs recruit members by force.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn-flatbush-gardens-promoted-safe-haven-residents-complex-hellhole-article-1.188661|title=Brooklyn's Flatbush Gardens promoted as safe haven, but residents say complex is hellhole|first=Kerry Burke, JONATHAN|last=LEMIRE|website=nydailynews.com}}</ref>\nVanderveer residents nicknamed the intersection of Foster and Nostrand avenues \"the Front Page\" because the murders there often ended up on the front pages of local papers. The area to the south they called \"the Back Page\" because its many murders went unnoticed. NYPD stated, 40% of the crime in the 67th Precinct was attributable to Vanderveer. Aggressive policing by [[NYPD]] and other enforcement agencies dismantled \"entrenched and highly organized drug-distribution organizations\" at Vanderveer, making it an NYPD success story. In 2006 crime in Flatbush Gardens was limited to one felonious assault and 20 burglaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nysun.com/real-estate/once-troubled-housing-complex-seeks-change/50520/|title=A Once-Troubled Housing Complex Seeks Change|website=The New York Sun}}</ref>\nIn 1999 Two undercover police officers shot and killed a 26-year-old man in Vanderveer, after he became angry that they were buying crack cocaine from someone else and shot one of them in the foot, the police said. The man was declared dead at the scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/09/19/nyregion/police-kill-man-during-drug-operation.html|title=Police Kill Man During Drug Operation|first=Kit R.|last=Roane|date=September 19, 1999|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Clipper Equity purchased the project and was able to make massive renovations renaming it Flatbush Gardens. With $8 million in capital improvements Clipper Equity renovated all 59 elevators, installing security cameras, repairing intercoms, starting the replacement of 18,000 windows, and constructing a community room. Currently the rent in Flatbush Gardens go for $1,000 a month for a one-bedroom unit, $1,200 for two bedrooms, and $1,375 for three bed room.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2009/09/16/established-tenants-fear-tides-of-change-at-flatbush-gardens/|title=Established tenants fear tides of change at Flatbush Gardens|first=Helen|last=Klein|date=September 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Residential buildings in Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "'''Vendeever Projects''' now known as \"Flatbush Gardens\", is a large low-income federal housing project located in [[East Flatbush, Brooklyn]]. Consisting of 59 six-story buildings on 30 acres, it contains 2,496 units housing about 13,000 residents. Until October 2005 Flatbush Gardens was, called Vanderveer Estates and was one of the most disreputable federally financed projects in the country. Handed off among about seven owners during 20 years, Vanderveer became a poster child for federally financed failures in moderate-income housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/13/nyregion/a-long-troubled-complex-hopes-to-flourish-again.html|title=A Long-Troubled Complex Hopes to Flourish Again|first1=Andy|last1=Newman|first2=Michael|last2=Brick|date=January 13, 2004|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Vanderveer.jpg|thumb]] -->\n\n==History==\nThe project was built in 1949 and 1950 on the site of the old Flatbush Water Works as a haven for working families. The complex held about 13,000 people with 2,496 units. During the early years some building lobbies had chandeliers and potted plants, but over the years the buildings slowly decayed. \nIn 1981, the owners did $23 million in renovations but botched the job so completely that the city, which helped finance the work, ended up suing the managers. In 1987 Foster Apartments bought the project and renamed it New Vanderveer Estates and made $8 million in repairs, started a free summer camp and got the vacancy rate down to 2 percent but two years later, the complex had begun to deteriorate once again. With a high vacancy rate, the project began to decline with crime being a main problem.\nIn 1979 A 35-year-old woman was shot to death by a policeman in her apartment after she slashed a sergeant in the upper left arm with a knife while resisting an attempt to evict her. Police officials said a single shot fired by another officer had killed the woman. She fell near the entrance of her sparsely furnished studio apartment at 1413 New York Avenue. Three officers and a city marshal were apparently present when the shooting occurred.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/08/30/archives/brooklyn-woman-35-slain-after-slashing-an-officer-death-follows.html|title=Brooklyn Woman, 35, Slain After Slashing an Officer|first=Joseph P.|last=Fried|date=August 30, 1979|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\nProblems worsened in the 1980s during the [[Crack epidemic]] After drug dealers set up shop in the apartments. It became notorious for shootings due to the open drug market in the buildings. Tenants stated drug dealers operated openly from basements, and gangs recruit members by force.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn-flatbush-gardens-promoted-safe-haven-residents-complex-hellhole-article-1.188661|title=Brooklyn's Flatbush Gardens promoted as safe haven, but residents say complex is hellhole|first=Kerry Burke, JONATHAN|last=LEMIRE|website=nydailynews.com}}</ref>\nVanderveer residents nicknamed the intersection of Foster and Nostrand avenues \"the Front Page\" because the murders there often ended up on the front pages of local papers. The area to the south they called \"the Back Page\" because its many murders went unnoticed. NYPD stated, 40% of the crime in the 67th Precinct was attributable to Vanderveer. Aggressive policing by [[NYPD]] and other enforcement agencies dismantled \"entrenched and highly organized drug-distribution organizations\" at Vanderveer, making it an NYPD success story. In 2006 crime in Flatbush Gardens was limited to one felonious assault and 20 burglaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nysun.com/real-estate/once-troubled-housing-complex-seeks-change/50520/|title=A Once-Troubled Housing Complex Seeks Change|website=The New York Sun}}</ref>\nIn 1999 Two undercover police officers shot and killed a 26-year-old man in Vanderveer, after he became angry that they were buying crack cocaine from someone else and shot one of them in the foot, the police said. The man was declared dead at the scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/09/19/nyregion/police-kill-man-during-drug-operation.html|title=Police Kill Man During Drug Operation|first=Kit R.|last=Roane|date=September 19, 1999|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Clipper Equity purchased the project and was able to make massive renovations renaming it Flatbush Gardens. With $8 million in capital improvements Clipper Equity renovated all 59 elevators, installing security cameras, repairing intercoms, starting the replacement of 18,000 windows, and constructing a community room. Currently the rent in Flatbush Gardens go for $1,000 a month for a one-bedroom unit, $1,200 for two bedrooms, and $1,375 for three bed room.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2009/09/16/established-tenants-fear-tides-of-change-at-flatbush-gardens/|title=Established tenants fear tides of change at Flatbush Gardens|first=Helen|last=Klein|date=September 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n[[Category:Residential buildings in Brooklyn]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vanderveer_Projects"}
{"title_page": "Handover of Hong Kong", "text_new": "{{short description|Transfer of sovereignty of Hong Kong to China}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name              = <!--Uses page name if omitted-->\n|native_name       = \n|native_name_lang  = \n|logo              = \n|logo_alt          = \n|logo_caption      = \n|logo_size         = \n|image             = \n|image_size        = \n|alt               = \n|caption           = On the afternoon of 30 June 1997, [[PATTEN]] on the eve of [[Hong Kong Governor]], [[Hong Kong Governor's Office|Government House]] received [[attendant officer|adjutant]] [[Hong Kong Governor#emblem|Governor's flag]].\n|status            = <!-- e.g. defunct, active, inactive ... -->\n|genre             = <!-- e.g. natural phenomena, fairs, festivals, conferences, exhibitions ... -->\n|date              = 1 July 1997\n|begins            = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|mm|dd}} -->\n|ends              = <!-- {{end date|YYYY|mm|dd}} -->\n|frequency         = <!-- Weekly, Monthly, Quarterly, Semi-annually, Annually, Bi-annually, 2nd Tuesday of November, etc. -->\n|venue             = \n|location          = Hong Kong\n|coordinates       = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display=inline,title}} --> \n|country           = \n|years_active      = <!-- {{age|YYYY|mm|dd}} Date of the first occurrence -->\n|first             = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|mm|dd}} \"founded=\" and \"established=\" also work -->\n|founder_name      = <!-- or | founders = -->\n|last              = <!-- Date of most recent event; if the event will not be held again, use {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n|prev              = \n|next              = \n|participants      = [[People's Republic of China]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland]]\n|attendance        = \n|capacity          = \n|area              = \n|budget            = \n|activity          = \n|leader_name       = \n|patron            = \n|organised         = <!-- \"organized=\" also works -->\n|filing            = \n|people            = \n|member            = \n|sponsor           = <!-- | or sponsors = -->\n|website           = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n|current           = \n|footnotes         = \n}}\n{{History of Hong Kong}}\n\nThe '''transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong''',<ref>\"This law took effect on 1 July 1997, upon the '''transfer of sovereignty''' from the United Kingdom to China\" [https://www.yearbook.gov.hk/1997/ch3/e3m.htm Hong Kong Year Book] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025223258/https://www.yearbook.gov.hk/1997/ch3/e3m.htm |date=25 October 2018 }}</ref><ref>\"...existing system in order to preserve continuity in the administration of the public service after the '''transfer of sovereignty'''\" [http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr04-05/english/panels/se/papers/se0815cb2-2431-2e.pdf Legislative Council of Hong Kong record] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006075237/http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr04-05/english/panels/se/papers/se0815cb2-2431-2e.pdf |date=6 October 2018 }}</ref><ref>Parliament of Australia [https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Joint/Completed_Inquiries/jfadt/hongkong/reportinx|Completed Inquiry: Hong Kong: The Transfer of Sovereignty]</ref> commonly known as the '''handover of Hong Kong''' (or simply '''the Handover''', also '''the Return''' in mainland China and Hong Kong), occurred at midnight at the start of 1 July 1997, when the [[United Kingdom]] ended administration for the [[British Hong Kong|colony of Hong Kong]] and returned control of the territory to [[China]]. [[Hong Kong]] became a [[Special administrative regions of China|special administrative region]] and continues to maintain governing and economic systems separate from those of [[mainland China]].\n\nThis event ended 156 years of British colonial rule in Hong Kong. The territory was Britain's last substantial overseas possession. With a population of about 6.5 million in 1997, Hong Kong constituted 97% of the total population of all [[British Overseas Territories|British Dependent Territories]] at the time. The retrocession is considered by some to definitively mark the end of the [[British Empire]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Acquisition of Hong Kong.svg|thumb|250px|Britain acquired [[Hong Kong Island]] in 1842, the [[Kowloon Peninsula]] in 1860, and the lease of the [[New Territories]] in 1898.]]\n\nBy the 1820s and 1830s, the British had conquered parts of India and had intentions of growing cotton in these lands to offset the amount of cotton they were buying from America. When this endeavour failed, the British realised they could grow poppies at an incredible rate. These poppies could then be turned into opium, which the Chinese highly desired, but their laws prohibited. So the British plan was grow poppies in India, convert it into opium, smuggle the opium in China and trade it for tea, and sell the tea back in Britain. The illegal opium trade was highly successful, and the drug was very profitably smuggled into China in extremely large volumes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Chinese Opium Wars|last=Beeching|first=Jack|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|year=1975|isbn=|location=New York|pages=74}}</ref>\n\nThe United Kingdom obtained control over portions of Hong Kong's territory through three treaties concluded with [[Qing dynasty|Qing China]] after the [[Opium Wars]]:\n\n* 1842 [[Treaty of Nanking]]: [[Hong Kong Island]] ceded in perpetuity\n* 1860 [[Convention of Peking]]: [[Kowloon Peninsula]] and [[Stonecutter's Island]] additionally ceded\n* 1898 [[Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory]]: the [[New Territories]] and [[Outlying Islands, Hong Kong|outlying islands]] leased for 99 years until 1997\n\nDespite the finite nature of the New Territories lease, this portion of the colony was developed just as rapidly as, and became highly integrated with, the rest of Hong Kong. As the end of the lease approached, and by the time of serious negotiations over the future status of Hong Kong in the 1980s, it was thought impractical to separate the ceded territories and return only the New Territories to China. In addition, with the scarcity of land and natural resources in Hong Kong Island and Kowloon, large-scale [[infrastructures|infrastructure]] investments had been made in the New Territories, with break-evens lying well past 30 June 1997.<ref name=\"Akers-Jones\" />\n\nWhen the People's Republic of China obtained its seat in the United Nations as a result of the [[UN General Assembly Resolution 2758]] in 1971, it began to act diplomatically on its previously lost sovereignty over both Hong Kong and [[Macau]]. In March 1972, the Chinese UN representative, [[Huang Hua (politician)|Huang Hua]], wrote to the United Nations Decolonization Committee to state the position of the Chinese government:\n\n:\"The questions of Hong Kong and Macau belong to the category of questions resulting from the series of unequal treaties which the imperialists imposed on China. Hong Kong and Macau are part of Chinese territory occupied by the British and Portuguese authorities. The settlement of the questions of Hong Kong and Macau is entirely within China's sovereign right and do not at all fall under the ordinary category of colonial territories. Consequently they should not be included in the list of colonial territories covered by the declaration on the granting of independence to colonial territories and people. With regard to the questions of Hong Kong and Macau, the Chinese government has consistently held that they should be settled in an appropriate way when conditions are ripe.\"<ref name=\"Passage\">{{cite book|author1=Ming K. Chan|author2=Gerard A. Postiglione|title=The Hong Kong Reader: Passage to Chinese Sovereignty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BZQcw-SJhI8C&pg=PA45|year=1996|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-1-56324-870-2|page=45}}</ref>\n\nThe same year, on 8 November, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] passed the resolution on removing Hong Kong and Macau from the official list of colonies.<ref name=\"Passage\" />\n\nIn March 1979 the [[Governor of Hong Kong]], [[Murray MacLehose, Baron MacLehose of Beoch|Murray MacLehose]], paid his first official visit to the People's Republic of China (PRC), taking the initiative to raise the question of Hong Kong's sovereignty with [[Deng Xiaoping]].<ref name=\"Pepper\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=upDNEYtw4uYC&pg=PA229 Elections, Political Change and Basic Law Government: Hong Kong in Search of a Political Form], [[Suzanne Pepper]] in ''Elections and Democracy in Greater China'', Larry Diamond, Ramon H. Myers, OUP Oxford, 2001, page 55</ref> Without clarifying and establishing the official position of the PRC government, the arranging of real estate leases and loans agreements in Hong Kong within the next 18 years would become difficult.<ref name=\"Akers-Jones\">{{cite book|author=David Akers-Jones|title=Feeling the Stones: Reminiscences by David Akers-Jones|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PnQAsA0oIPoC&pg=PA109|year=2004|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-962-209-655-4|page=109}}</ref>\n\nIn response to concerns over land leases in the New Territories, MacLehose proposed that British administration of the whole of Hong Kong, as opposed to sovereignty, be allowed to continue after 1997.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/jun/02/guardianobituaries1 Lord MacLehose] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123134724/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/jun/02/guardianobituaries1 |date=23 November 2016 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 2 June 2000</ref> He also proposed that contracts include the phrase \"for so long as the Crown administers the territory\".<ref>{{cite book|author=M. Taylor Fravel|title=Strong Borders, Secure Nation: Cooperation and Conflict in China's Territorial Disputes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=02Hjr6RUckwC&pg=PA224|year=2008|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=1-4008-2887-2|page=224}}</ref>\n\nIn fact, as early as the mid-1970s, Hong Kong had faced additional risks raising loans for large-scale infrastructure projects such as its [[Mass Transit Railway]] (MTR) system and a new airport. Caught unprepared, Deng asserted the necessity of Hong Kong's return to China, upon which Hong Kong would be given special status by the PRC government.\n\nMacLehose's visit to the PRC raised the curtain on the issue of Hong Kong's sovereignty: Britain was made aware of the PRC's intent to resume sovereignty over Hong Kong, and began to make arrangements accordingly to ensure the sustenance of her interests within the territory, as well as initiating the creation of a withdrawal plan in case of emergency.\n\nThree years later, Deng received the former [[British Prime Minister]] [[Edward Heath]], who had been dispatched as the special envoy of Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] to establish an understanding of the PRC's plans with regards to the retrocession of Hong Kong; during their meeting, Deng outlined his plans to make the territory a special economic zone, which would retain its capitalist system under Chinese sovereignty.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wei-Bin Zhang|title=Hong Kong: The Pearl Made of British Mastery and Chinese Docile-diligence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hwPUGWBTsX4C&pg=PA68|year=2006|publisher=Nova Publishers|isbn=978-1-59454-600-6|page=68}}</ref>\n\nIn the same year, [[Edward Youde]], who succeeded MacLehose as the 26th Governor of Hong Kong, led a [[delegation]] of five [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Councillor]]s to London, including [[Chung Sze-yuen]], [[Lydia Dunn]], and [[Roger Lobo]].<ref name=\"Chung\">[https://archive.org/details/hongkongsjourney00chun/page/123 <!-- quote=chung sze-yuen lydia dunn and roger lobo delegation to london. --> ''Hong Kong's Journey to Reunification: Memoirs of Sze-yuen Chung''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104047/https://books.google.com/books?id=0ZxGHy-4X30C&lpg=PA352&ots=78T_VKsnfe&dq=chung%20sze-yuen%20lydia%20dunn%20and%20roger%20lobo%20delegation%20to%20london&pg=PA123#v=onepage&q=chung%20sze-yuen%20lydia%20dunn%20and%20roger%20lobo%20delegation%20to%20london&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Sze Yuen Chung, Chinese University Press, 2001, page 123</ref> Chung presented their position on the sovereignty of Hong Kong to Thatcher, encouraging her to take into consideration the interests of the native Hong Kong population in her upcoming visit to China.<ref name=\"Chung\" />\n\nIn light of the increasing openness of the PRC government and economic reforms on the mainland, the then British Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] sought the PRC's agreement to a continued British presence in the territory.<ref name=\"Cottrell\" />\n\nHowever, the PRC took a contrary position: not only did the PRC wish for the New Territories, on lease until 1997, to be placed under the PRC's jurisdiction, it also refused to recognise the onerous \"[[Unequal treaty|unfair and unequal treaties]]\" under which Hong Kong Island and Kowloon had been ceded to Britain in perpetuity after the [[Opium Wars]].<ref name=\"Yahuda\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=b9gGzWigqpMC&q=kowloon#v=onepage&q=kowloon&f=true ''Hong Kong: China's Challenge''], Michael B. Yahuda, Routledge, 1996, page 45</ref> Consequently, the PRC recognised only the British administration in Hong Kong, but not British sovereignty.<ref name=\"Yahuda\" />\n\n==Talks==\n{{quote box\n|title=Major events, 1979\u20131997\n|align=right\n|width=30%\n|quote=<nowiki></nowiki>\n* 24 March 1979: Hong Kong Governor Sir [[Murray MacLehose]] was invited to visit Guangzhou and Beijing to find out the attitude of the Chinese government on the issue of Hong Kong.\n* 29 March 1979: Sir Murray MacLehose met paramount leader [[Deng Xiaoping]] and raised the issue of Hong Kong for the first time. Deng remarked that the investors could set their minds at peace.\n* 4 April 1979: The Kowloon\u2013Canton through-train routes were restored after 30 years of non-service.\n* 3 May 1979: The [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] won the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|U.K. election]].\n* 29 October 1979: Premier [[Hua Guofeng]] visited Britain and had a meeting with British prime minister [[Margaret Thatcher]]. Both of them expressed their concern to maintain the stability and prosperity of Hong Kong.\n* 12 May 1980: [[Table (verb)#Commencing discussion|Table]]d by the Conservative Party in the British government, a new status \"[[British Overseas Territories citizen]]\" was introduced. This status proposal was widely opposed by Hong Kong people.\n* 3 April 1981: Foreign Secretary [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Lord Carrington]] met Deng Xiaoping in his visit to Beijing.\n* 30 September 1981: Chairman of the [[National People's Congress|NPC]] [[Ye Jianying]] issued nine guiding principles concerning a peaceful reunification of Taiwan and mainland China.\n* 30 October 1981: The House of Commons passed the new British Nationality Act.\n* November 1981: The Beijing government invited some Hong Kong citizens to help organising a united front in the handling of the Hong Kong issue.\n* 6 January 1982: Chinese Premier [[Zhao Ziyang]] received Lord Privy Seal [[Humphrey Atkins]]. Zhao insisted that the PRC would uphold its sovereignty over Hong Kong.\n* 10 March 1982: Vice Premier [[Gu Mu]] received Sir [[John Bremridge]], promising to maintain Hong Kong's stability and prosperity.\n* 6 April 1982: Deng Xiaoping revealed his wish to have official contact with the British government.\n* 8 May 1982: Sir [[Edward Youde]] arrived as the 26th Governor of Hong Kong.\n* May 1982: Deng Xiaoping and Zhao Ziyang collected advice from Hong Kong notables such as [[Li Ka-shing]] and [[T. K. Ann|Ann Tse-kei]].\n* 15 June 1982: Deng Xiaoping officially announced the position of the Chinese government in the context of the Hong Kong 97 Issue, marking the first public statement on part of the PRC with regards to the issue.}}\n\n===Before the negotiations===\nIn the wake of Governor MacLehose's visit, Britain and the PRC established initial diplomatic contact for further discussions of the Hong Kong question, paving the way for Thatcher's first visit to the PRC in September 1982.<ref name=\"Roger\">{{cite book|author1=Roger Buckley|author2=Buckley Roger|title=Hong Kong: The Road to 1997|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cxxGJ7c10noC&pg=PA109|year=1997|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-46979-1|page=109}}</ref>\n\nMargaret Thatcher, in discussion with Deng Xiaoping, reiterated the validity of an extension of the lease of Hong Kong territory, particularly in light of binding treaties, including the Treaty of Nanking in 1842, the [[Convention of Peking]] in 1856, and the Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory signed in 1890.\n\nIn response, Deng Xiaoping cited clearly the lack of room for compromise on the question of sovereignty over Hong Kong; the PRC, as the successor of [[Qing dynasty]] and the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] on [[Mainland China|the mainland]], would recover the entirety of the New Territories, Kowloon and Hong Kong Island. China considered treaties about Hong Kong as unequal and ultimately refused to accept any outcome that would indicate permanent loss of sovereignty over Hong Kong's area, whatever wording the former treaties had.<ref>Ezra F. Vogel: Deng Xiaoping and the Transformation of China. Library of Congress Cataloging-in-Publication Data 2011. Pages 496\u20137.</ref>\n\nDuring talks with Thatcher, China planned to invade and seize Hong Kong if the negotiations set off unrest in the colony. Thatcher later said that Deng told her bluntly that China could easily take Hong Kong by force, stating that \"I could walk in and take the whole lot this afternoon\", to which she replied that \"there is nothing I could do to stop you, but the eyes of the world would now know what China is like\".<ref>[http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/world_news/article67028.ece China plotted Hong Kong invasion] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408004455/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/world_news/article67028.ece |date=8 April 2016 }}, Michael Sheridan, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', 25 June 2007</ref>\n\nAfter her visit with Deng in Beijing, Thatcher was received in Hong Kong as the first British Prime Minister to set foot on the territory whilst in office. At a press conference, Thatcher re-emphasised the validity of the three treaties, asserting the need for countries to respect treaties on universal terms: \"There are three treaties in existence; we stick by our treaties unless we decide on something else. At the moment, we stick by our treaties.\"<ref name=\"Cottrell\" />\n\nAt the same time, at the 5th session of the 5th [[National People's Congress]], the constitution was amended to include a new Article 31 which stated that the country might establish [[Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China|Special Administrative Regions]] (SARs) when necessary.<ref>[http://english.gov.cn/archive/laws_regulations/2014/08/23/content_281474982987458.htm Constitution of the People's Republic of China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416110047/http://english.gov.cn/archive/laws_regulations/2014/08/23/content_281474982987458.htm |date=16 April 2016 }}, State Council of the People's Republic of China</ref>\n\nThe additional Article would hold tremendous significance in settling the question of Hong Kong and later [[Macau]], putting into social consciousness the concept of \"[[One country, two systems]]\". The concept would prove useful to deploy until the territories were secured and conditions were ripe for its gradual revision.\n\n===Negotiations begin===\nA few months after Thatcher's visit to Beijing, the PRC government had yet to open negotiations with the British government regarding the sovereignty of Hong Kong.\n\nShortly before the initiation of sovereignty talks, Governor Youde declared his intention to represent the population of Hong Kong at the negotiations. This statement sparked a strong response from the PRC, prompting Deng Xiaoping to denounce talk of \"the so-called 'three-legged stool'\", which implied that Hong Kong was a party to talks on its future, alongside Beijing and London.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/article/453465/benefits-three-legged-stool Benefits of a three-legged stool] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427121205/http://www.scmp.com/article/453465/benefits-three-legged-stool |date=27 April 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 26 April 2004</ref>\n\nAt the preliminary stage of the talks, the British government proposed an exchange of sovereignty for administration and the implementation of a British administration post-handover.<ref name=\"Cottrell\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090809225312/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/how-mrs-thatcher-lost-hong-kong-ten-years-ago-fired-up-by-her-triumph-in-the-falklands-war-margaret-thatcher-flew-to-peking-for-a-lastditch-attempt-to-keep-hong-kong-under-british-rule--only-to-meet-her-match-in-deng-xiaoping-two-years-later-she-signed-the-agreement-handing-the-territory-to-china-1543375.html How Mrs Thatcher lost Hong Kong], ''[[The Independent]]'', Robert Cottrell, 30 August 1992</ref>\n\nThe PRC government refused, contending that the notions of sovereignty and administration were inseparable, and although it recognised [[Macau]] as a \"Chinese territory under Portuguese administration\", this was only temporary.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ySvxAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA175 ''China Perspectives''], Issues 21\u201326, C.E.F.C., 1999, page 13</ref>\n\nIn fact, during informal exchanges between 1979 and 1981, the PRC had proposed a \"Macau solution\" in Hong Kong, under which it would remain under British administration at China's discretion.<ref name=\"Pepper\" />\n\nHowever, this had previously been rejected following the [[Hong Kong 1967 Leftist riots|1967 Leftist riots]], with the then Governor, [[David Trench]], claiming the leftists' aim was to leave the UK without effective control, or \"to Macau us\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Gary Ka-wai Cheung|title=Hong Kong's Watershed: The 1967 Riots|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0uStp3CUaqUC&pg=PA36|year=2009|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-962-209-089-7|page=37}}</ref>\n\nThe conflict that arose at that point of the negotiations ended the possibility of further negotiation. During the reception of former British Prime Minister Edward Heath during his sixth visit to the PRC, Deng Xiaoping commented quite clearly on the impossibility of exchanging sovereignty for administration, declaring an ultimatum: the British government must modify or give up its position or the PRC will announce its resolution of the issue of Hong Kong sovereignty unilaterally.<ref name=\"fmprc\">[http://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/ziliao_665539/3602_665543/3604_665547/t18032.shtml The Chinese government resumed exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401135704/http://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/ziliao_665539/3602_665543/3604_665547/t18032.shtml |date=1 April 2016 }}, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]], People's Republic of China</ref>\n\nIn 1983, [[Typhoon Ellen (1983)|Typhoon Ellen]] ravaged Hong Kong, causing great amounts of damage to both life and property.<ref name=\"SHT\">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ReUbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gGgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1278,6865410&dq=typhoon+ellen&hl=en Typhoon Ellen Batters Hong Kong, killing 6] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222095911/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ReUbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gGgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1278,6865410&dq=typhoon+ellen&hl=en |date=22 February 2017 }}, [[United Press International]], ''[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]'', 10 September 1983</ref> The Hong Kong dollar plummeted on [[Black Saturday (1983)|Black Saturday]], and the [[Financial Secretary of Hong Kong|Financial Secretary]] [[John Bremridge]] publicly associated the economic uncertainty with the instability of the political climate.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/1983/1004/100426.html Hong Kong business world shaken by political uncertainties] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411040625/http://www.csmonitor.com/1983/1004/100426.html |date=11 April 2016 }}, ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', 4 October 1983</ref> In response, the PRC government condemned Britain through the press for \"playing the economic card\" in order to achieve their ends: to intimidate the PRC into conceding to British demands.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1988/jan/20/hong-kong Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414154546/http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1988/jan/20/hong-kong |date=14 April 2016 }} ''[[Hansard]]'', HC Deb 20 January 1988 vol 125 cc971-1018</ref>\n\n===British concession===\nGovernor Youde with nine members of the Hong Kong Executive Council travelled to London to discuss with Prime Minister Thatcher the crisis of confidence\u2014the problem with morale among the people of Hong Kong arising from the ruination of the Sino-British talks. The session concluded with Thatcher's writing of a letter addressed to the PRC Premier [[Zhao Ziyang]].\n\nIn the letter, she expressed Britain's willingness to explore arrangements optimising the future prospects of Hong Kong while utilising the PRC's proposals as a foundation. Furthermore, and perhaps most significantly, she expressed Britain's concession on its position of a continued British presence in the form of an administration post-handover.\n\nTwo rounds of negotiations were held in October and November. On the sixth round of talks in November, Britain formally conceded its intentions of either maintaining a British administration in Hong Kong or seeking some form of co-administration with the PRC, and showed its sincerity in discussing PRC's proposal on the 1997 issue. Obstacles were cleared.\n\n[[Simon Keswick]], chairman of [[Jardine Matheson]] & Co., said they were not pulling out of Hong Kong, but a new [[holding company]] would be established in [[Bermuda]] instead.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=N0_VAAAAMAAJ ''Summary of World Broadcasts: Far East''], Part 3, BBC Monitoring Service, 1984</ref> The PRC took this as yet another plot by the British. The Hong Kong government explained that it had been informed about the move only a few days before the announcement. The government would not and could not stop the company from making a business decision.\n\nJust as the atmosphere of the talks was becoming cordial, members of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] felt impatient at the long-running secrecy over the progress of Sino-British talks on the Hong Kong issue. A motion, [[Table (verb)#Commencing discussion|table]]d by legislator [[Roger Lobo]], declared \"This Council deems it essential that any proposals for the future of Hong Kong should be debated in this Council before agreement is reached\", was passed unanimously.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ian Scott|title=Political Change and the Crisis of Legitimacy in Hong Kong|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w7NuSICc0lYC&pg=PA210|year=1989|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-1269-0|page=210}}</ref>\n\nThe PRC attacked the motion furiously, referring to it as \"somebody's attempt to play the three-legged stool trick again\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=B9ksAAAAMAAJ ''Daily Report: People's Republic of China''], Issues 38\u201345, United States. Foreign Broadcast Information Service, National Technical Information Service, 1993, page 79</ref> At length, the PRC and Britain initiated the Joint Declaration on the question of Hong Kong's future in Beijing. [[Zhou Nan]], the then PRC Deputy Foreign Minister and leader of the negotiation team, and Sir [[Richard Evans (British diplomat)|Richard Evans]], British Ambassador to Beijing and leader of the team, signed respectively on behalf of the two governments.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/26/newsid_2538000/2538843.stm ON THIS DAY: 26 September 1984: UK and China agree Hong Kong handover] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103002517/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/26/newsid_2538000/2538843.stm |date=3 January 2008 }}, [[BBC News]]</ref>\n\n==Sino-British Joint Declaration==\n{{Main|Sino-British Joint Declaration}}\nThe Sino-British Joint Declaration was signed by the Prime Ministers of the People's Republic of China and the United Kingdom governments on 19 December 1984 in Beijing. The Declaration entered into force with the exchange of instruments of ratification on 27 May 1985 and was registered by the People's Republic of China and United Kingdom governments at the United Nations on 12 June 1985.\n\nIn the Joint Declaration, the People's Republic of China Government stated that it had decided to resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong (including [[Hong Kong Island]], Kowloon, and the New Territories) with effect from 1 July 1997 and the United Kingdom Government declared that it would restore Hong Kong to the PRC with effect from 1 July 1997. In the document, the People's Republic of China Government also declared its basic policies regarding Hong Kong.\n\nIn accordance with the \"[[One country, two systems]]\" principle agreed between the United Kingdom and the People's Republic of China, the socialist system of the People's Republic of China would not be practised in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), and Hong Kong's previous capitalist system and its way of life would remain unchanged for a period of 50 years. This would have left Hong Kong unchanged until 2047.\n\nThe Joint Declaration provided that these basic policies should be stipulated in the [[Hong Kong Basic Law]]. The ceremony of the signing of the Sino-British Joint Declaration took place at 18:00, 19 December 1984 at the Western Main Chamber of the [[Great Hall of the People]]. The [[Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office]] at first proposed a list of 60\u201380 Hong Kong people to attend the ceremony. The number was finally extended to 101.\n\nThe list included Hong Kong government officials, members of the Legislative and Executive Councils, chairmen of the [[Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation]] and [[Standard Chartered Bank]], prominent businessmen such as [[Li Ka-shing]], [[Pao Yue-kong]] and [[Fok Ying-tung]], and also [[Martin Lee]] Chu-ming and [[Szeto Wah]].\n\n===Universal suffrage===\n\nThe Hong Kong Basic Law ensured, among other things, that Hong Kong will retain its [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|legislative system]], and people's rights and freedom for fifty years, as a [[Special administrative regions of China|special administrative region (SAR) of China]]. The [[Government of China|central government in Beijing]] maintains control over Hong Kong's foreign affairs as well as the legal interpretation of the Basic Law. The latter has led democracy advocates and some Hong Kong residents to argue, after the fact,  that the territory has yet to achieve [[universal suffrage]] as promised by the [[Hong Kong Basic Law|Basic Law]], leading to [[Umbrella Revolution|mass demonstrations in 2014]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> In 2019, demonstrations that started as a protest [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|against an extradition law]] also led to massive demonstrations (1.7 million on 11 and 18 August 2019), again demanding universal suffrage, but also the resignation of Carrie Lam (the current Chief Executive).<ref name=\"BBC19aug2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49340717|title=Hong Kong: Timeline of extradition protests |quote=What started as demonstrations against an extradition bill have since taken on a much wider scope and are now demanding full democratic rights for Hong Kongers.|work=[[BBC News]] |date=4 September 2019 |access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Drafting of Basic Law==\n{{Main|Basic Law of Hong Kong}}\n\nThe [[Basic Law of Hong Kong|Basic Law]] was drafted by a [[Hong Kong Basic Law Drafting Committee|Drafting Committee]] composed of members from both Hong Kong and [[China|Mainland China]]. A [[Hong Kong Basic Law Consultative Committee|Basic Law Consultative Committee]] formed purely by Hong Kong people was established in 1985 to canvas views in Hong Kong on the drafts.\n\nThe first draft was published in April 1988, followed by a five-month public consultation exercise. The second draft was published in February 1989, and the subsequent consultation period ended in October 1989.\n\nThe Basic Law was formally promulgated on 4 April 1990 by the [[National People's Congress|NPC]], together with the designs for the flag and emblem of the HKSAR. Some members of the Basic Law drafting committee were ousted by Beijing following [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests|4 June 1989 Tiananmen Square protests]], after voicing views supporting the student protesters.\n\nThe Basic Law was said to be a mini-[[constitution]] drafted with the participation of Hong Kong people. The political system had been the most controversial issue in the drafting of the Basic Law. The special issue sub-group adopted the political model put forward by [[Louis Cha]]. This \"mainstream\" proposal was criticised for being too conservative.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\nAccording to Clauses 158 and 159 of the Basic Law, powers of interpretation and amendment of the Basic Law are vested in the [[Standing Committee of the National People's Congress]] and the National People's Congress, respectively. Hong Kong's people have limited influence.\n\n==Tide of migration==\nAfter the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]], the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Councillors]] and the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Councillors]] of Hong Kong unexpectedly held an urgent meeting, in which they agreed unanimously that the British Government should give the people of Hong Kong the [[Right of abode (United Kingdom)|right of abode]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>[http://www.taiwantoday.tw/ct.asp?xItem=103048&ctNode=2198&mp=9 A Rough Road ahead] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424062259/http://www.taiwantoday.tw/ct.asp?xItem=103048&ctNode=2198&mp=9 |date=24 April 2016 }}, ''[[Taiwan Review]]'', 1 March 1990</ref>\n\nMore than 10,000 Hong Kong residents rushed to [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]] in order to get an application form for residency in the United Kingdom. On the eve of the deadline, over 100,000 lined up overnight for a [[British National (Overseas)]] application form. While mass migration began well before 1989, the event led to the peak migration year in 1992 with 66,000 leaving.<ref>{{cite book|author=Melanie MANION|title=Corruption by Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zyMeydaAu1kC&pg=PA80|year=2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-04051-9|page=80}}</ref>\n\nMany citizens were pessimistic towards the future of Hong Kong and the transfer of the region's sovereignty. A tide of emigration, which was to last for no less than five years, broke out. At its peak, [[citizenship]] of small countries, such as [[Tonga]], was also in great demand.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/07/magazine/in-the-court-of-the-king-of-tonga.html?pagewanted=all In the Court of the King of Tonga] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160803/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/07/magazine/in-the-court-of-the-king-of-tonga.html?pagewanted=all |date=24 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times Company]]'', 1992</ref>\n\n[[Singapore]], which also had a [[Chinese Singaporeans|predominantly Chinese]] population, was another popular destination, with the country's Commission (now Consulate-General) being besieged by anxious Hong Kong residents.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-12/news/8902160755_1_singapore-commission-hong-kong-singapore-government Singapore Lure Stirs Crowds In Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002085238/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-12/news/8902160755_1_singapore-commission-hong-kong-singapore-government |date=2 October 2015 }}, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', 12 July 1989</ref> By September 1989, 6000 applications for residency in Singapore had been approved by the Commission.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/newpaper19890921-1.2.3.7.aspx 6,000 from HK given residency here] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420031256/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/newpaper19890921-1.2.3.7.aspx |date=20 April 2016 }}, ''[[The New Paper]]'', 21 September 1989, page 2</ref>\n\nSome [[consul (representative)|consul]] staff were suspended or arrested for their [[political corruption|corrupt behaviour]] in granting immigration visas. In April 1997, the acting [[Immigration and Naturalization Service|immigration officer]] at the [[Consulate General of the United States, Hong Kong and Macau|US Consulate-General]], James DeBates, was suspended after his wife was arrested for smuggling of Chinese migrants into the United States.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/06/world/us-immigration-officer-in-hong-kong-investigated-for-corruption.html U.S. Immigration Officer in Hong Kong Investigated for Corruption] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160810/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/06/world/us-immigration-officer-in-hong-kong-investigated-for-corruption.html |date=24 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 6 April 1997</ref> The previous year, his predecessor, Jerry Stuchiner, had been arrested for smuggling forged [[Honduran passport]]s into the territory before being sentenced to 40 months in prison.<ref>[http://europe.newsweek.com/smuggling-people-170802 Smuggling People], ''[[Newsweek]]'', 17 March 1997</ref>\n\nCanada ([[Greater Vancouver|Vancouver]] and [[Greater Toronto|Toronto]]), the United Kingdom (London, [[Glasgow]], and [[Manchester]]), Australia ([[Perth]], [[Greater Sydney|Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]]), and the United States ([[San Francisco Bay Area|San Francisco]] and [[New York metropolitan area|New York]]) were, and by large, the most popular destinations. The United Kingdom devised the [[British Nationality Selection Scheme]], granting 50,000 families British citizenship under the [[British nationality law and Hong Kong|British Nationality Act (Hong Kong) 1990]].<ref>{{UK-LEG|path=ukpga/1990/34/contents|title=British Nationality Act (Hong Kong) 1990}}</ref>\n\n[[Chinese Canadians in Greater Vancouver|Vancouver]] was among the most popular destinations, earning the nickname of  \"Hongcouver\".<ref>[http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/story.html?id=011b7438-172c-4126-ba42-2c85828bd6ce Chinese Vancouver: A decade of change] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116072007/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/story.html?id=011b7438-172c-4126-ba42-2c85828bd6ce |date=16 November 2014 }}, ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', 30 June 2007</ref> [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]], a suburb of Vancouver, was nicknamed \"Little Hong Kong\".<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/a-tale-of-two-solitudes-written-anew/article1034293/ A tale of two solitudes written anew] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418034355/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/a-tale-of-two-solitudes-written-anew/article1034293/ |date=18 April 2016 }}, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 26 October 2001</ref> All in all, from the start of the settlement of the negotiation in 1984 to 1997, nearly 1 million people emigrated; consequently, Hong Kong suffered serious loss of human and financial capital.<ref>Fosh, Patricia. Chan, Andy. Chow, Wilson WS. Snape, Ed. Westwood, Robert. [2000] (2000) Hong Kong Management and Labour. United Kingdom: Routledge. {{ISBN|0-415-22269-9}}.</ref>\n\n==Last governor==\n{{main|1994 Hong Kong electoral reform}}\n[[Chris Patten]] became the last governor of Hong Kong. This was regarded as a turning point in Hong Kong's history. Unlike his predecessors, Patten was not a diplomat, but a career politician and former Member of Parliament. He introduced democratic reforms which pushed PRC\u2013British relations to a standstill and affected the negotiations for a smooth handover.\n\nPatten introduced a package of electoral reforms in the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]]. These reforms proposed to enlarge the electorate, thus making voting in the Legislative Council more democratic. This move posed significant changes because Hong Kong citizens would have the power to make decisions regarding their future.\n\n==Handover ceremony==\n{{Main|Hong Kong handover ceremony}}\nThe handover ceremony was held at the new wing of the [[Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre]] in [[Wan Chai]] on the night of 30 June 1997.\n\nThe principal British guest was [[Prince Charles]], who read a farewell speech on behalf of the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]]. The newly elected [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Prime Minister, [[Tony Blair]], the [[Foreign Secretary of the United Kingdom|Foreign Secretary]] [[Robin Cook]], the departing [[Governor of Hong Kong|Governor]] [[Chris Patten]] and [[Charles Guthrie, Baron Guthrie of Craigiebank|General Sir Charles Guthrie]], [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]], also attended.\n\nRepresenting the People's Republic of China were the President, [[Jiang Zemin]], the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]], [[Li Peng]], and the first chief executive [[Tung Chee-hwa]]. The event was broadcast around the world.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mike Chinoy|title=China Live: People Power and the Television Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YeiaOWcc17MC&pg=PA395|year=1999|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-8476-9318-4|page=395}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/bbc_parliament/6241974.stm Hong Kong Night \u2013 Sunday 1 July] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819202535/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/bbc_parliament/6241974.stm |date=19 August 2007 }}, [[BBC News]], 27 June 2007</ref>\n\n==Additional effects==\n\n===Before and after handover===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"clear:both; width:100%;\"\n! width=50% | Unchanged after 30 June 1997\n! width=50% | Changed after 30 June 1997\n|-valign=top\n|\n#English continued as an official language and is still taught in all schools. However, many schools teach in [[Cantonese]] in parallel with [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]] and English.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GbF8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA198 Education and colonial transition in Singapore and Hong Kong: Comparisons and contrasts], Jason Tan in '' Changing Educational Contexts, Issues and Identities: 40 Years of Comparative Education'', Michael Crossley, Patricia Broadfoot, Michele Schweisfurth, Routledge, 2007, page 198</ref>\n#The border with the mainland, while now known as the boundary, continued to be patrolled as before, with separate immigration and customs controls.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200301/08/0108224.htm Lok Ma Chau Control Point to provide 24-hour passenger clearance services] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051045/http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200301/08/0108224.htm |date=4 March 2016 }}, [[Government of Hong Kong|Government Information Centre]], 8 January 2003</ref>\n#Hong Kong citizens were still required to apply for a [[Mainland Travel Permit for Hong Kong and Macao Residents|Mainland Travel Permit]], in order to visit mainland China.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201202/15/P201202150334.htm LCQ1: Immigration clearance and entry visas to the Mainland for non-Chinese Hong Kong permanent residents with foreign passports] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109234739/http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201202/15/P201202150334.htm |date=9 January 2015 }}, [[Government of Hong Kong|Government Information Centre]], 15 February 2012</ref> \n#Citizens of mainland China still did not have the [[right of abode]] in Hong Kong.<ref>[http://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/services/roa/geninfor.html General Information on the Right of Abode in Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325022735/http://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/services/roa/geninfor.html |date=25 March 2016 }}, [[Hong Kong Immigration Department|Immigration Department]]</ref> Instead, they had to apply for a permit to [[Two-way Permit|visit]] or [[One-way Permit|settle]] in Hong Kong from the PRC government.<ref>[http://www.fmcoprc.gov.hk/eng/fwxx/wgrqz/t1055657.htm Exit and Entry Administration Law of the People's Republic of China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331061809/http://www.fmcoprc.gov.hk/eng/fwxx/wgrqz/t1055657.htm |date=31 March 2016 }}, [[Office of the Commissioner of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region]]</ref> \n#Hong Kong remained a [[common law jurisdiction]], with a separate legal system from that [[Law of the People's Republic of China|used in the mainland]], with previous laws remaining in force provided that they did not conflict with the [[Basic Law of Hong Kong|Basic Law]].<ref>{{cite book|title=China Briefing's Business Guide to the Greater Pearl River Delta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PknF6cR7lQMC&pg=PA245|year=2004|publisher=China Briefing Media, Ltd.|isbn=978-988-98673-1-7|page=245}}</ref>\n#The [[Hong Kong dollar]] continued to be used as its sole currency, and the responsibility of the [[Hong Kong Monetary Authority]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hkma.gov.hk/eng/index.shtml |title=Hong Kong Monetary Authority |access-date=30 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329231845/http://www.hkma.gov.hk/eng/index.shtml |archive-date=29 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The [[Bank of China (Hong Kong)|Bank of China]] had already started issuing banknotes in 1994.<ref>[http://www.boc.cn/en/aboutboc/ab7/200809/t20080926_1601846.html Bank of China Authorized to Issue HKD and MOP (1987\u20131992)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411141108/http://www.boc.cn/en/aboutboc/ab7/200809/t20080926_1601846.html |date=11 April 2016 }}, [[Bank of China]]</ref>\n#Hong Kong continued to operate as a separate customs territory from mainland China under Article 116 of the Basic Law.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200009/30/0929290.htm Hong Kong operates as a separate Customs territory] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040908113214/http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200009/30/0929290.htm |date=8 September 2004 }}, [[Government of Hong Kong|Government Information Centre]], 30 September 2000</ref>\n#Hong Kong remained an individual member of various international organisations, such as the [[World Trade Organization]] and [[APEC]].<ref>[https://www.wto.org/english/news_e/spmm_e/spmm03_e.htm Address Via Video-Conference \u2013 A challenge to APEC business] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912164957/http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/spmm_e/spmm03_e.htm |date=12 September 2014 }}, Address given by Rt Hon Mike Moore, Director-General, World Trade Organization, 12 September 1999</ref>\n#Hong Kong, which remained an individual member of the [[International Olympic Committee]], continued to send its own team to international sporting events such as the Olympics.<ref name=\"Olympic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.olympic.org/hong-kong-china |title=Sports Federation and Olympic Committee of Hong Kong China |access-date=27 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316171825/http://www.olympic.org/hong-kong-china |archive-date=16 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#Hong Kong maintained [[Hong Kong Economic and Trade Office]]s overseas, as well as in the Greater China Region. These include the offices in London, Washington D.C., [[Brussels]] and [[Geneva]], previously known as Hong Kong Government Offices.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr82-83/english/lc_sitg/hansard/h821111.pdf |title=Official report of proceedings, 11 November 1982, Legislative Council |access-date=27 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220507/http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr82-83/english/lc_sitg/hansard/h821111.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#Many countries' [[Consular missions in Hong Kong|consulates-general]] in Hong Kong remained outside the jurisdiction of their embassies in Beijing, such as the United States [[Consulate General of the United States, Hong Kong|Consulate General]], which reports directly to the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ait.org.tw/en/pressrelease-pr1224.html |title=Christopher J. Marut Appointed as Director of the Taipei Office of the American Institute in Taiwan |access-date=24 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002648/http://www.ait.org.tw/en/pressrelease-pr1224.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#The Chung Hwa Travel Service, which functioned as [[Taiwan]]'s [[de facto embassy|''de facto'' mission]] in Hong Kong, continued to function as before, issuing visas to visitors from Hong Kong, mainland China and other countries.<ref>{{cite book|author=Yue-man Yeung|title=The First Decade: The Hong Kong SAR in Retrospective and Introspective Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9X9QXYXGdJwC&pg=PA87|year=2007|publisher=Chinese University Press|isbn=978-962-996-357-6|page=87}}</ref> In 2011 it was renamed the [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Hong Kong]].<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2011/07/17/2003508415 Is name change a game changer?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222005/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2011/07/17/2003508415 |date=3 March 2016 }}, ''[[Taipei Times]]'', 17 July 2011</ref>     \n#Hong Kong continued to negotiate and maintain its own aviation bilateral treaties with foreign countries and territories.<ref>[http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/laws/table1ti.html List of Air Services Agreements and Air Services Transit Agreements] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411054743/http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/laws/table1ti.html |date=11 April 2016 }}, [[Department of Justice (Hong Kong)|Department of Justice]]</ref> Agreements with [[Taiwan]] signed in 1996 remained in force after the change of sovereignty, and were replaced by \"the air transportation agreement between Taiwan and Hong Kong\", which retained international regulations, such as regulations on customs.<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2002/07/01/0000146568 New air accord a result of compromise, analysts say] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409020634/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2002/07/01/0000146568 |date=9 April 2016 }}, ''[[Taipei Times]]'', 1 July 2002</ref> \n#Signs (and fonts), labels, and roadway construction standards on Hong Kong roads and expressways continue to follow the [[Transport in the European Union|European Union roadway standards]], particularly those of the UK.<ref>[http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/car-news/89974/celebrating-50-years-of-uk-road-signs Celebrating 50 years of UK road signs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706041738/http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/car-news/89974/celebrating-50-years-of-uk-road-signs |date=6 July 2016 }}, ''[[Auto Express]]'', 8 January 2015</ref>\n#Hong Kong continued to [[Left- and right-hand traffic|drive on the left]], unlike Mainland China, which drives on the right.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Andrew Stone|author2=Chung Wah Chow|author3=Reggie Ho|title=\u9999\u6e2f L\u0306\u0111\u95e8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PgJTSYeEnNkC&pg=PA279|year=2008|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-665-6|page=278}}</ref> [[Vehicle registration plates of Hong Kong|Vehicle registration plates]] continued to be modelled on [[Vehicle registration plates of the United Kingdom|those of the United Kingdom]], white on the front and yellow on the back, with the vehicle registration mark in a similar font.<ref>[http://hub.hku.hk/bitstream/10722/46157/1/50044.pdf?accept=1 Recognition of vehicle registration mark on moving vehicles in an outdoor environment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412233817/http://hub.hku.hk/bitstream/10722/46157/1/50044.pdf?accept=1 |date=12 April 2016 }}, N. H. C. Yung*, K. H. Au & A. H. S. Lai, Laboratory for Intelligent Transportation Systems Research, [[University of Hong Kong]], IEEE Conference on Intelligent Transportation Systems, Proceedings, Itsc, 1999, p. 418-422</ref>\n#Hong Kong-registered vehicles still required special [[Vehicle registration plates of China#Cross-border with Hong Kong and Macau|cross-border]] plates to travel to and from mainland China, similar to those of [[Guangdong]].<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/article/1105206/cross-border-licence-plates-go-1-million-yuan-black-market Cross-border licence plates go for a million yuan on black market] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503102917/http://www.scmp.com/article/1105206/cross-border-licence-plates-go-1-million-yuan-black-market |date=3 May 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 14 December 2012</ref> Vehicles registered in the mainland can enter Hong Kong under the [[Hong Kong mainland China driving scheme]].<ref name=\"scmp1\">[http://topics.scmp.com/news/hk-news-watch/article/New-entry-plan-for-mainland-cars New entry plan for mainland cars] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223095104/http://topics.scmp.com/news/hk-news-watch/article/New-entry-plan-for-mainland-cars |date=23 February 2012 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 9 February 2012.</ref>\n#Hong Kong citizens continued to have easier access to many countries, including those in Europe and North America, with Hong Kong SAR passport holders having visa-free access to 154 other countries and territories.<ref>[http://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/service/travel_document/visa_free_access.html  Visa-free access for HKSAR Passport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331011103/http://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/service/travel_document/visa_free_access.html |date=31 March 2016 }}, [[Hong Kong Immigration Department]]</ref> \n#Many former colonial citizens could still use [[British National (Overseas)]] and [[British citizen]] passports after 1997. (''Main article: [[British nationality law and Hong Kong]]'')\n#It continued to have more political freedoms than [[mainland China]], with the holding of demonstrations and the [[Memorials for the Tiananmen Square protests of 1989#Hong Kong|annual memorial]] to commemorate the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]] continuing to be held in [[Victoria Park, Hong Kong|Victoria Park]].<ref>[http://time.com/3908678/tiananmen-massacre-26th-anniversary-hong-kong-china-vigil-victoria-park/ Tens of Thousands Gather in Hong Kong to Remember the 1989 Tiananmen Massacre] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419102504/http://time.com/3908678/tiananmen-massacre-26th-anniversary-hong-kong-china-vigil-victoria-park/ |date=19 April 2016 }}, ''[[Time Magazine]]'', 4 June 2015</ref>   \n#It continued to have a [[List of political parties in Hong Kong|multi-party]] political system.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ngok Ma|title=Political Development in Hong Kong: State, Political Society, and Civil Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=af_IAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA135|year=2007|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-962-209-809-1|page=135}}</ref> This is separate from the [[Chinese Communist Party|Communist]]-led [[United Front (People's Republic of China)|United Front]] on the mainland.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1864432/united-front-chief-sun-chunlan-tells-young-hongkongers-love United Front chief Sun Chunlan tells young Hongkongers to love their country and make the most of close ties with China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624035646/http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1864432/united-front-chief-sun-chunlan-tells-young-hongkongers-love |date=24 June 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 6 October 2015</ref> \n#It continued to have more [[freedom of the press]] than mainland China, under Article 27 of the Basic Law, despite the growing influence of Beijing.<ref>[https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2015/hong-kong Hong Kong * | Country report | Freedom of the Press | 2015] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328194946/https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2015/hong-kong |date=28 March 2016 }}, [[Freedom House]]</ref>\n#It also continued to have more religious freedoms, with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Hong Kong]] remaining under the jurisdiction of the [[Holy See]], instead of the [[Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association]] on the mainland.<ref>[http://en.radiovaticana.va/news/2016/01/16/pope_appoints_hong_kong_bishop_to_macau_%E2%80%8E/1201599 Pope appoints Hong Kong bishop to Macau] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420112918/http://en.radiovaticana.va/news/2016/01/16/pope_appoints_hong_kong_bishop_to_macau_%E2%80%8E/1201599 |date=20 April 2016 }}, ''[[Vatican Radio]]'', 16 January 2016</ref> The [[Falun Gong]] spiritual practice also remained legal in Hong Kong, despite encountering opposition from the SAR government.<ref name=dangerous>{{Cite book |first=Mickey |last=Spiegel |url=https://archive.org/details/fromhouseholdtof00huma |title=Dangerous Meditation: China's Campaign Against Falungong |publisher=Human Rights Watch |year=2002 |accessdate=28 September 2007 |isbn=1-56432-269-6 }}</ref>\n#Many other technical standards from the United Kingdom, such as [[Electrical wiring in Hong Kong|electrical plugs]] ([[BS 1363]]) are still used in Hong Kong.<ref>[http://www.frommers.com/destinations/china/702082 Fast Facts in China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409031813/http://www.frommers.com/destinations/china/702082 |date=9 April 2016 }}, ''[[Frommer's]]''</ref> However, telephone companies changed from installing [[British Standard|UK-style]] [[BS 6312]] telephone sockets to installing [[Registered jack|US-style]] [[Modular connector#6P2C|RJ11]] ones.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120211132642/http://www.ofta.gov.hk/en/consumer_interest/rj_system/index.html The RJ System of telephone plugs and sockets is gradually replacing the BT System in Hong Kong], [[Office of the Telecommunications Authority]] (OFTA), Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government</ref> Hong Kong also adopted the [[Digital Terrestrial Multimedia Broadcast|digital TV standard]] devised in mainland China for [[Television in Hong Kong|TV transmissions]], instead of [[DVB-T]], to replace [[PAL]]-I.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wrth|title=World Radio Tv Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-KY9AQAAIAAJ|year=2008|publisher=WRTH Publications Ltd|isbn=978-0-9555481-1-6|page=642}}</ref> (''Main article: [[Technical standards in colonial Hong Kong]]'')\n#Hong Kong retained a separate [[country calling code|international dialling code]] (852) and [[Hong Kong telephone numbering plan|telephone numbering plan]] from that of the [[China telephone numbering plan|mainland]].<ref>[https://www.itu.int/oth/T0202000060/en Hong Kong, China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304064001/http://www.itu.int/oth/T0202000060/en |date=4 March 2016 }}, [[International Telecommunication Union]], 19 February 2013</ref> Calls between Hong Kong and the mainland still required international dialling.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GpqzAAAAIAAJ ''China International Business: The Monthly Publication of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, P.R.C''], Issues 7\u201312, Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, 2002</ref> \n#Hong Kong retained a separate [[ISO 3166]] code, [[ISO 3166-2:HK|HK]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:HK |title=ISO Online Browsing Platform: HK |access-date=29 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617031837/https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:HK |archive-date=17 June 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> It also retained a [[Country code top-level domain|top-level domain]], [[.hk]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hkirc.hk/ |title=Hong Kong Internet Registration Corporation |access-date=29 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321090104/https://www.hkirc.hk/ |archive-date=21 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, the [[ISO 3166-2:CN|Chinese code]] CN-91 was also used.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:CN |title=ISO Online Browsing Platform: CN |access-date=29 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617031837/https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:CN |archive-date=17 June 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#Hong Kong retained its own separate [[postal service]]s, with [[Hongkong Post]] operating separately from [[China Post]]. Hong Kong was not made part of the [[List of postal codes in China|Chinese postcode system]], nor did it introduce a postcode system of its own.<ref>[http://www.upu.int/fileadmin/documentsFiles/activities/addressingUnit/hkgEn.pdf Hongkong, China], [[Universal Postal Union]]</ref>\n#The Hong Kong government continued to make a subvention to the [[English Schools Foundation]], responsible for English-medium schools, which would not be phased out until 2016.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/families/article/1359426/esfs-new-chief-executive-belinda-greer-looks-boost-efficiency ESF's new chief executive Belinda Greer looks to boost efficiency], ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 19 November 2013</ref>  \n#The former British military drill, marching and words of command in English continued in all disciplinary services including all civil organisations.<ref>[http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/11_useful_info/aux_police/training.html Training] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316201245/http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/11_useful_info/aux_police/training.html |date=16 March 2016 }}, Hong Kong Police Force</ref> The [[People's Liberation Army|PLA]] soldiers of the [[People's Liberation Army Hong Kong Garrison|Chinese Garrison in Hong Kong]] have their own drills and Mandarin words of command.\n#Statues of British monarchs remained. [[Queen Victoria]]'s statue remains in [[Victoria Park, Hong Kong|Victoria Park]].<ref>[http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/vp/index.html Victoria Park] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321182929/http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/vp/index.html |date=21 March 2016 }}, [[Leisure and Cultural Services Department]]</ref> [[King George VI]]'s statue similarly remained in [[Hong Kong Zoological and Botanical Gardens]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/hkzbg/ |title=Hong Kong Zoological and Botanical Gardens |access-date=31 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330204811/http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/hkzbg/ |archive-date=30 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#British-inspired road names remain unchanged.<ref name=\"SCMP1994\" />\n||\n#From 2012, secondary education moved away from the English model of five years secondary schooling plus two years of university matriculation to the Chinese model of three years of junior secondary plus another three years of senior secondary, while university education was extended from three years to four.<ref>[https://universitydesign.asu.edu/db/hong-kong-undergraduate-education-reform-under-201c3-3-4201d Hong Kong Undergraduate Education Reform Under \"3+3+4\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408045313/https://universitydesign.asu.edu/db/hong-kong-undergraduate-education-reform-under-201c3-3-4201d |date=8 April 2016 }}, University Design Consortium, [[Arizona State University]]</ref>\n#The [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|chief executive]] became the [[head of government]], [[Elections in Hong Kong|elected]] by a [[Selection Committee]], whose members were mainly elected from among professional sectors and business leaders.<ref>[http://www.basiclaw.gov.hk/en/basiclawtext/annex_1.html Annex I : Method for the Selection of the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408201047/http://www.basiclaw.gov.hk/en/basiclawtext/annex_1.html |date=8 April 2016 }}, [[Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]]</ref> The [[Governor of Hong Kong|Governor]] was appointed by the United Kingdom.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/politics97/hk/patten.shtml Chris Patten \u2013 Governor of Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402130913/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/politics97/hk/patten.shtml |date=2 April 2018 }}, [[BBC]], Politics 97</ref>\n#The [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]], [[1995 Hong Kong legislative election|elected in 1995]], was dissolved and replaced by a [[Provisional Legislative Council]], before elections were held to a new Council, in which only 20 out of 60 seats were directly elected.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elections.gov.hk/elections/legco1998/524-e.htm#gc524-e |title=Results of the 1998 Legislative Council Election |access-date=15 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231311/http://www.elections.gov.hk/elections/legco1998/524-e.htm#gc524-e |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The decision to dissolve the Legislative Council and replace it with a Provisional Legislative Council was criticised by representatives of the UK government.<ref>An interview with the former British Prime Minister Thatcher just before Britain's handover of Hong Kong back to China on 1 July 1997; Reporter/Producer: Susan Yu; Published on 1 July 1997 and viewable on YouTube.</ref>\n#Foreign nationals were not allowed to stand for directly elected seats in the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]], only for [[Functional constituency (Hong Kong)|indirectly elected]] seats.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/lau-in-passport-battle-1289087.html Lau in passport battle] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427221230/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/lau-in-passport-battle-1289087.html |date=27 April 2016 }}, ''[[The Independent]]'', 16 December 1997</ref>  \n#All public office buildings now flew the flags of the [[Flag of the People's Republic of China|PRC]] and the [[flag of Hong Kong|Hong Kong SAR]]. The [[Union Flag]] now flew only outside the [[British Consulate-General, Hong Kong|British Consulate-General]] and other British premises.\n#The British national anthem ''[[God Save the Queen]]'', was no longer played after closedown on [[Television in Hong Kong|television stations]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cV3QdfNOewk God Save the Queen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316195259/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cV3QdfNOewk |date=16 March 2014 }}, [[TVB Pearl]], 1987</ref> The Chinese national anthem, ''[[March of the Volunteers]]'' was now played instead.<ref>Vickers, Edward. [https://books.google.com/books?id=QwXgYeQRVHsC&pg=PA94 \"Learning to Love the Motherland: 'National Education' in Post-Retrocession Hong Kong\" in ''Designing History in East Asian Textbooks: Identity Politics and Transnational Aspirations'', p.&nbsp;94]. Routledge (Abingdon), 2011. {{ISBN|9780415602525}}.</ref> \n#At international sporting events such as the Olympics, Hong Kong was now known as [[Hong Kong at the Olympics|Hong Kong, China]].<ref name=\"Olympic\" /> Hong Kong athletes and teams compete under the Hong Kong SAR flag instead of the British flag of Hong Kong, and gold medallists were honoured with the Chinese national anthem, instead of the British national anthem.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-34918397 Fifa investigates Hong Kong over China match booing] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216001611/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-34918397 |date=16 February 2018 }}, [[BBC News]], 25 November 2015</ref>\n#The [[Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal|Court of Final Appeal]] replaced the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] as the highest court of appeal.<ref>[http://www.hkcfa.hk/en/about/overview/index.html A Brief Overview of the Court of Final Appeal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230185237/http://www.hkcfa.hk/en/about/overview/index.html |date=30 December 2015 }}, [[Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal]]</ref>\n#The [[Supreme Court (Hong Kong)|Supreme Court]] was replaced by the [[High Court (Hong Kong)|High Court]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Simon N. M. Young|author2=Yash Ghai|title=Hong Kong's Court of Final Appeal: The Development of the Law in China's Hong Kong|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4LAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA227|year=2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-01121-2|page=227}}</ref>\n#The [[Secretary for Justice (Hong Kong)#Attorneys General before 1997|Attorney General]] was replaced by the [[Secretary for Justice (Hong Kong)|Secretary for Justice]].<ref>[http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/about/soj.html Secretary for Justice, Mr Rimsky Yuen, SC, JP] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412145253/http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/about/soj.html |date=12 April 2016 }}, [[Department of Justice (Hong Kong)|Department of Justice]]</ref>\n#The [[Central People's Government]] was now formally represented in Hong Kong by a [[Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region|Liaison Office]], dealing with domestic matters.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/20/world/in-watching-hong-kong-china-loses-the-shades.html In Watching Hong Kong, China Loses The Shades] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160817/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/20/world/in-watching-hong-kong-china-loses-the-shades.html |date=24 July 2016 }}, ''[[New York Times]]'', 20 February 2000</ref> This had been established under British rule as the [[Xinhua News Agency#Xinhua in Hong Kong|Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch]], before it adopted its present name in 2000.<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/insight/archives/2000/01/21/0000020843 Renamed Xinhua becomes a new force in Hong Kong's politics] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819145347/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/insight/archives/2000/01/21/0000020843 |date=19 August 2017 }}, ''[[Taipei Times]]'', 21 January 2000</ref> \n#The Hong Kong SAR Government was now formally represented in Beijing by the [[Office of the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region in Beijing|Office of the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bjo.gov.hk/en/home/index.html |title=Welcome Message Office of the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) of the People's Republic of China in Beijing |access-date=1 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416173624/http://www.bjo.gov.hk/en/home/index.html |archive-date=16 April 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China]] was represented in Hong Kong by a [[Office of the Commissioner of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region|Commissioner]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070821153208/http://big5.fmprc.gov.cn/gate/big5/www.fmcoprc.gov.hk/eng/ Office of the Commissioner of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region]</ref>\n#The [[People's Liberation Army]] established a [[People's Liberation Army Hong Kong Garrison|Garrison]], taking over responsibility for defence from [[British Forces Overseas Hong Kong]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/hong-kong-forces-withdrawal-outlined-1485942.html Hong Kong forces withdrawal outlined] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410065018/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/hong-kong-forces-withdrawal-outlined-1485942.html |date=10 April 2016 }}, ''[[The Independent]]'', 19 July 1993</ref> The Prince of Wales Building was renamed the [[Chinese People's Liberation Army Forces Hong Kong Building]], while the Prince of Wales Barracks was similarly renamed the Central Barracks, with effect from January 2002.<ref>[http://en.people.cn/200112/30/eng20011230_87779.shtml PLA Hong Kong Garrison Head Office to Use New Name] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030627/http://en.people.cn/200112/30/eng20011230_87779.shtml |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''[[People's Daily]]'', 31 December 2001</ref>\n#Flags were no longer flown at the [[The Cenotaph (Hong Kong)|Cenotaph]] to remember the war dead; previously British troops raised flags representing the [[British Army]], [[Royal Navy]] and [[Royal Air Force]] every morning, lowering them again before sunset.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/article/204622/confusion-over-flags-leaves-cenotaph-bare Confusion over flags leaves Cenotaph bare], ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 21 July 1997</ref> \n#[[Government House, Hong Kong|Government House]] was not used as the residence of the first chief executive, [[Tung Chee-hwa]].<ref name=\"Slow but Sure\" /> However, his successor, [[Donald Tsang]], moved into the compound in 2006.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200601/12/P200601110210.htm CE moves into Government House today] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200906/http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200601/12/P200601110210.htm |date=3 March 2016 }}, [[Government of Hong Kong]], 12 January 2006</ref>   \n#[[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]]'s portrait was removed from public offices.<ref name=\"Battle Royal\" /> Coins issued since 1993 no longer had the Queen's head, instead having the [[Bauhinia \u00d7 blakeana#Usage as an emblem|Bauhinia]].<ref>[http://www.hkma.gov.hk/eng/publications-and-research/reference-materials/viewpoint/19991118.shtml Viewpoint: Bauhinia Coins] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031116/http://www.hkma.gov.hk/eng/publications-and-research/reference-materials/viewpoint/19991118.shtml |date=4 March 2016 }}, [[Hong Kong Monetary Authority]], 18 November 1999</ref>\n#Postage stamps now displayed the words \"Hong Kong, China\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Hong Kong|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QCAfAQAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Government Press|page=354}}</ref> A set of definitive stamps, bearing the words \"Hong Kong\" with no connotation of sovereignty, was introduced in January 1997.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hongkong Post|title=Hongkong Post Annual Report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8gNEAQAAIAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Government Press|page=30}}</ref> \n#The \"[[Royal Charter|Royal]]\" title was dropped from almost all [[Royal Charter#Hong Kong|organisations that had been granted it]], with the exception of the [[Royal Hong Kong Yacht Club]].<ref name=\"Battle Royal\">[http://www.csmonitor.com/1996/0610/061096.intl.intl.2.html A Battle Royal Rocks Imperial Yacht Club] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408180839/http://www.csmonitor.com/1996/0610/061096.intl.intl.2.html |date=8 April 2016 }}, ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', 10 June 1996</ref>\n#The [[St Edward's Crown|Crown]] was removed from the crest of the [[Hong Kong Police Force]], and replaced by the [[Bauhinia \u00d7 blakeana#Usage as an emblem|Bauhinia]].<ref name=\"Battle Royal\" />\n#Legal references to the \"[[The Crown|Crown]]\" were replaced by references to the \"State\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5ZtTFZBUG_oC&pg=PA39 Continuity and Change in the Legal System], ''The Other Hong Kong Report 1998'', edited by Larry Chuen-ho Chow, Yiu-Kwan Fan, Chinese University Press, 1998, page 39</ref> [[Barrister]]s who had been appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] would now be known as [[Senior Counsel]].<ref>[http://hkba.org/the-bar/aboutus/index.html About Us], [[Hong Kong Bar Association]]</ref>\n#The [[British honours system]] was replaced by a local system, in which the [[Grand Bauhinia Medal]] was the highest award.<ref>{{cite book|title=Summary of World Broadcasts: Asia, Pacific|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jfpWAAAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n#[[Public holidays in Hong Kong|Public holidays]] changed, with British-inspired occasions, such as the [[Queen's Birthday|Queen's Official Birthday]], [[Victory over Japan Day#Hong Kong|Liberation Day]], and [[Remembrance Day]] being replaced by [[PRC National Day]] and [[Hong Kong SAR Establishment Day]].<ref name=\"SCMP1994\">[http://www.scmp.com/article/88137/17-holidays-stay-after-1997 17 holidays to stay after 1997] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503213839/http://www.scmp.com/article/88137/17-holidays-stay-after-1997 |date=3 May 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 12 September 1994</ref> [[Double Ten Day]], commemorating the establishment of the [[Republic of China (1912-49)|Republic of China]], was abolished as a public holiday in 1950.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4lJOAQAAIAAJ ''Far Eastern Economic Review''], 1968, page 450</ref>\n#Many of the red [[Royal Mail]] [[pillar box]]es were removed from the streets of Hong Kong and replaced by green [[Hongkong Post]] boxes.<ref name=\"Slow but Sure\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/09/world/change-in-hong-kong-is-slow-but-sure.html?pagewanted=all Change in Hong Kong Is Slow but Sure] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160822/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/09/world/change-in-hong-kong-is-slow-but-sure.html?pagewanted=all |date=24 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 9 October 1997</ref> All others were re-painted.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/07/hong-kong-to-cover-british-insignia-on-postboxes-to-avoid-confusion Hong Kong to cover British insignia on postboxes to 'avoid confusion'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215070035/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/07/hong-kong-to-cover-british-insignia-on-postboxes-to-avoid-confusion |date=15 December 2016 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 7 October 2015</ref>\n#British citizens (without right of abode in Hong Kong) were no longer able to work in Hong Kong without a visa; the policy was changed on 1 April 1997.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160826184845/http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/97/0411/nat3.html Warning: Deadline Ahead], ''[[Asiaweek]]'', 11 April 1997</ref><ref name=\"Offshore Investment\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20161221002053/http://www.offshoreinvestment.com/media/uploads/Hong%20Kong%20after%20the%20change%20of%20sovereignty.pdf Hong Kong after the change of sovereignty], Jane McNair and Professor Peter Willoughby,\nDeacons Graham & James, Hong Kong SAR, ''Offshore Investment'', January 1999, issue 92</ref>\n#The United Kingdom was now represented by the [[British Consulate-General, Hong Kong|British Consulate-General]], which reports directly to the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmfaff/649/64907.htm The UK's relations with Hong Kong: 30 years after the Joint Declaration] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525090559/https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmfaff/649/64907.htm |date=25 May 2017 }}, Tenth Report of Session 2014\u201315, [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]], [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], 6 March 2015, page 16 [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmfaff/649/649.pdf PDF] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719113821/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmfaff/649/649.pdf |date=19 July 2018 }}</ref> This has responsibility for British citizens, instead of the [[Hong Kong Immigration Department]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Yash Ghai|title=Hong Kong's New Constitutional Order: The Resumption of Chinese Sovereignty and the Basic Law|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=veEZBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA167|year=1997|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-962-209-463-5|page=167}}</ref> Previously, the country's commercial interests were represented by a British Trade Commission.<ref>{{cite book|author=Claudia Cragg|title=Hunting with the Tigers: Doing Business with Hong Kong, Indonesia, South Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Taiwan, Thailand, and Vietnam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QhVWl7-NcY8C&pg=PA417|year=1993|publisher=Pfeiffer & Company|isbn=978-0-89384-204-8|page=417}}</ref> It was headed by a Senior Trade Commissioner, who became the first Consul-General.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/isd/news/oct97/1022pm.htm Chief Executive holds 'useful, cordial' talks with British Prime Minister] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613122434/http://www.info.gov.hk/isd/news/oct97/1022pm.htm |date=13 June 2018 }}, Government of Hong Kong, 22 October 1997</ref>\n#Hong Kong was no longer linked to the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] and no longer participated in related [[Commonwealth Family|organisations or events]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecgf.com/countries/intro.asp?loc=HKG# |title=Commonwealth Games Federation \u2013 Hong Kong |access-date=24 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819125702/http://www.thecgf.com/countries/intro.asp?loc=HKG |archive-date=19 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Consular missions in Hong Kong|Consular missions]] of Commonwealth member states in Hong Kong were no longer known as Commissions, but as Consulates-General.<ref>[http://www.mfa.gov.sg/content/mfa/overseasmission/hong_kong/about_the_consulate_general.html About the Consulate-General] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029161528/http://www.mfa.gov.sg/content/mfa/overseasmission/hong_kong/about_the_consulate_general.html |date=29 October 2015 }}, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Singapore)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]], Singapore</ref>\n#Countries which did not have diplomatic relations with the United Kingdom, but had diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of China, such as [[North Korea]] and [[Iran]], were allowed to establish or re-open Consulates-General.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ralf Horlemann|title=Hong Kong's Transition to Chinese Rule: The Limits of Autonomy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QtHHi3B0peYC&pg=PA79|year=2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-43411-4|page=78}}</ref> \n#Consulates of countries which maintained diplomatic relations with [[Taiwan]] were closed.<ref name=\"SCMP Liberia\">[http://www.scmp.com/article/214706/liberian-consulate-forced-close Liberian consulate forced to close] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426075314/http://www.scmp.com/article/214706/liberian-consulate-forced-close |date=26 April 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 10 October 1997</ref> Only South Africa, which was to establish relations with the People's Republic of China from 1998, was allowed to keep its Consulate General open for an interim period.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140109234316/http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/1997/06130x66197.htm Statement on Future South Africa/Hong Kong Relations by the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs, Mr Aziz Pahad, 12 June 1997]</ref>   \n#Hong Kong's [[Aircraft registration#List of countries/regions and their registration prefixes and patterns|aircraft registration prefix]] changed from '''VR''' to '''B''', bringing it into line with mainland China and Taiwan.<ref>[http://www.yearbook.gov.hk/1997/ch15/e15v.htm Hong Kong&nbsp;\u2013 A New Era \u2013 Civil Aviation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060225/http://www.yearbook.gov.hk/1997/ch15/e15v.htm |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''Hong Kong Yearbook 1997'', [[Government of Hong Kong|Hong Kong SAR Government]]</ref>\n#Newspapers, such as the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', changed to heading their pages with \"National\", rather than \"Local\" and 'China', and began including Chinese names in Chinese characters. However, the online edition still uses \"China\" and only displays Chinese names in Roman script.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/news/china China News] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327135325/http://www.scmp.com/news/china |date=27 March 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]''</ref>  \n#A giant golden statue of a ''[[Bauhinia blakeana]]'' was erected in a public space outside the [[Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre]], named [[Golden Bauhinia Square]], along with a [[Monument in Commemoration of the Return of Hong Kong to China|Reunification Monument]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_RRXAAAAMAAJ ''Summary of World Broadcasts: Asia, Pacific''], Issues 3986\u20133998, page G-8</ref> \n|-\n|}\n\n===Rose Garden Project===\n{{Main|Port and Airport Development Strategy}}\n\nAfter the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]], the Hong Kong government proposed a grand \"Rose Garden Project\" to restore faith and solidarity among the residents.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas Y. T. Luk|author2=James P. Rice|title=Before and After Suzie: Hong Kong in Western Film and Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TDkZAQAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=New Asia College, The Chinese University of Hong Kong|isbn=978-962-8072-09-5|page=88}}</ref> As the construction of the new [[Hong Kong International Airport]] would extend well after the handover, Governor Wilson met PRC Premier [[Li Peng]] in Beijing to ease the mind of the PRC government.<ref>{{cite book|author=John M. Carroll|title=A Concise History of Hong Kong|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fQofAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA195|year=2007|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-0-7425-7469-4|page=195}}</ref>\n\nThe communist press published stories that the project was an evil plan to bleed Hong Kong dry before the handover, leaving the territory in serious debt.<ref>{{cite book|author=Denis Bray|title=Hong Kong Metamorphosis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v6ZszKvUkjAC|year=2001|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-962-209-550-2|page=232}}</ref> After three years of negotiations, Britain and the PRC finally reached an agreement over the construction of the new airport, and signed a Memorandum of Understanding.<ref>{{cite book|author=Steve Yui-Sang Tsang|title=A Modern History of Hong Kong|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h7LtAAAAMAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-86064-184-8|page=253}}</ref> Removing hills and reclaiming land, it took only a few years to construct the new airport.\n\n===Views of the Kowloon Walled City===\n{{Main|Kowloon Walled City}}\n\nThe Walled City was originally a single fort built in the mid-19th century on the site of an earlier 17th century watch post on the [[Kowloon Peninsula]] of Hong Kong.<ref>Lim, Patricia. [2002] (2002). Discovering Hong Hong's Cultural Heritage. Central, Hong Kong: Oxford University Press. ISBN Volume One 0-19-592723-0</ref> After the ceding of [[Hong Kong Island]] to Britain in 1842 ([[Treaty of Nanjing]]), [[Manchu]] [[Qing]] Dynasty authorities of China felt it necessary for them to establish a military and administrative post to rule the area and to check further British influence in the area.\n\nThe 1898 Convention which handed additional parts of Hong Kong (the [[New Territories]]) to Britain for 99 years excluded the Walled City, with a population of roughly 700. It stated that China could continue to keep troops there, so long as they did not interfere with Britain's temporary rule.\n\nBritain quickly went back on this unofficial part of the agreement, attacking Kowloon Walled City in 1899, only to find it deserted. They did nothing with it, or the outpost, and thus posed the question of Kowloon Walled City's ownership squarely up in the air. The outpost consisted of a [[yamen]], as well as buildings which grew into low-lying, densely packed neighbourhoods from the 1890s to 1940s.\n\nThe [[enclave]] remained part of Chinese territory despite the turbulent events of the early 20th century that saw the fall of the Qing government, the establishment of the [[Republic of China (1912\u201349)|Republic of China]] and later, a [[People's Republic of China|Communist Chinese government]] (PRC).\n\nSquatters began to occupy the Walled City, resisting several attempts by Britain in 1948 to drive them out. The Walled City became a haven for criminals and drug addicts, as the [[Hong Kong Police]] had no right to enter the City and China refused maintainability. The 1949 foundation of the People's Republic of China added thousands of refugees to the population, many from [[Guangdong]]; by this time, Britain had had enough, and simply adopted a \"hands-off\" policy.\n\nA murder that occurred in Kowloon Walled City in 1959 set off a small diplomatic crisis, as the two nations each tried to get the other to accept responsibility for a vast tract of land now virtually ruled by anti-[[Qing dynasty|Manchurian]] [[Triad society|Triads]].\n\nAfter the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration|Joint Declaration in 1984]], the PRC allowed British authorities to demolish the City and resettle its inhabitants. The mutual decision to tear down the walled city was made in 1987.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9NYyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kO8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1193%2C4443534 Hong Kong's infamous Walled City to be converted into park area], Michael Browning, [[Knight Ridder]], ''Ottawa Citizen'', 29 January 1987, page c9</ref> The government spent up to [[HKD|HK$]] 3&nbsp;billion to resettle the residents and shops.\n\nSome residents were not satisfied with the compensation, and some even obstructed the demolition in every possible way.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YsExAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3YwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6688%2C969556 Riot police evict Hong Kong residents from Walled City] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630155905/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YsExAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3YwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6688%2C969556 |date=30 June 2016 }}, [[Associated Press]], ''[[Boca Raton News|The News]]'', 3 July 1992</ref> Ultimately, everything was settled, and the Walled City became a park.<ref>[http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/kwcp/index.html Kowloon Walled City Park \u2013 History/Background] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323040215/http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/kwcp/index.html |date=23 March 2016 }}, [[Leisure and Cultural Services Department]]</ref>\n\n==International reaction==\nThe [[Republic of China on Taiwan]] promulgated the ''Laws and Regulations Regarding Hong Kong & Macao Affairs'' on 2 April 1997 by [[President of the Republic of China|Presidential]] Order, and the [[Executive Yuan]] on 19 June 1997 ordered the provisions pertaining to Hong Kong to take effect on 1 July 1997.<ref>[[Ministry of Justice (Republic of China)]]: [http://law.moj.gov.tw/Eng/LawClass/LawHistory.aspx?PCode=Q0010003 Laws and Regulations Regarding Hong Kong & Macao Affairs: Legislative History]</ref>\n\nThe [[United States\u2013Hong Kong Policy Act]] or more commonly known as the Hong Kong Policy Act ([[Public law|PL]] no. 102-383m 106 Stat. 1448) is a 1992 act enacted by the [[United States Congress]].  It allows the United States to continue to treat Hong Kong separately from China for matters concerning trade export and economics control after the handover.<ref name=\"HKrev\">Hong Kong's reversion to China: effective monitoring critical to assess U.S. DIANE Publishing. {{ISBN|1-4289-7837-2}}</ref>\n\nThe United States was represented by then Secretary of State [[Madeleine Albright]] at the [[Hong Kong handover ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Albright To Attend Hong Kong Transfer Ceremony |url=http://edition.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1997/04/16/albright.hongkong/ |publisher=CNN |date=16 April 1997 |accessdate=27 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128152038/http://edition.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1997/04/16/albright.hongkong/ |archive-date=28 January 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, she partially boycotted it in protest of China's dissolution of the democratically elected Hong Kong legislature.<ref>{{cite news |title=Smooth Hong Kong handover lifts China's image |url=http://articles.cnn.com/1997-07-15/world/9707_15_hongkong_1_handover-beijings-china-policy?_s=PM:WORLD |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119115910/http://articles.cnn.com/1997-07-15/world/9707_15_hongkong_1_handover-beijings-china-policy?_s=PM:WORLD |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 January 2013 |publisher=CNN |date=15 July 1997 |accessdate=27 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==End of the British Empire==\n{{Seealso|Decolonization|List of countries that have gained independence from the United Kingdom}}\n[[File:HK 71 Match BHKG1.jpg|thumb|Hong Kong 1 July march with [[Flag of Hong Kong (1959\u20131997)|British Hong Kong flag]]]]\nThe handover marked the end of British rule in Hong Kong, which was Britain's last substantial overseas territory.  Although in statute law set down by [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], British Hong Kong had no status of pre-eminence vis-a-vis the other [[British Dependent Territories]] (as they were then classified before the term British Overseas Territory was [[British Overseas Territories Act 2002|introduced in 2002]]), Hong Kong was by far the most populous and economically potent.  In 1997 the colony had a population of approximately 6.5 million, which represented roughly 97% of the population of the British Dependent Territories as a whole at that time (the next largest, [[Bermuda]], having a 1997 population of approximately only 62,000).  With a [[gross domestic product]] of approximately US$180 billion in the last year of British rule,<ref>{{cite web |title=Hong Kong SAR, China  |url=https://data.worldbank.org/country/hong-kong-sar-china?view=chart |website=World Bank |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> Hong Kong's economy was roughly 11% the size of Britain's.<ref>{{cite web |title=United Kingdom |url=https://data.worldbank.org/country/united-kingdom |website=World Bank |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>  Therefore, although the economies of the [[Economy of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] and [[Economy of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] were measured separately, the Handover did mean the British economy in its very broadest sense became substantially smaller (by comparison, the acquisition of Hong Kong boosted the size of the [[Economy of the People's Republic of China|Chinese economy]], which was then smaller than the United Kingdom's, by 18.4%).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bland and Pong |first1=Ben and Jane |title=Hong Kong since the handover in charts |url=https://www.ft.com/content/7e2422b8-5bb1-11e7-9bc8-8055f264aa8b |accessdate=21 September 2018 |work=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> As a comparator to Hong Kong, in 2017 Bermuda (as with population, the economically largest of Britain's remaining territories) had a GDP of only US$4.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gross Domestic Product \u2013 2017 highlights |url=https://www.gov.bm/sites/default/files/GDP%202017%20annual%20publication.pdf |publisher=Government of Bermuda, Department of Statistics |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe cession of Hong Kong meant that Britain's remaining territories (excepting the United Kingdom itself) henceforth consisted either of uninhabited lands (for instance the [[British Antarctic Territory]]), small islands or micro land masses (such as [[Montserrat]]), territories used as military bases (for example [[Akrotiri and Dhekelia]] on the island of [[Cyprus]], itself a former [[crown colony]] granted independence in 1960), or a combination of the latter two (like [[Gibraltar]]). And while many of Britain's remaining territories are significant to the global economy by virtue of being [[offshore financial centre]]s (Bermuda, the [[British Virgin Islands]], and the [[Cayman Islands]] being the most prominent of these), their economies are insubstantial.  Demographically, they are also tiny compared to Britain, with a collective population of less than 0.4% of Britain's 2017 population of 66 millions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Population estimates |url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/populationestimates |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> As of 2018 the combined population of Britain's remaining fourteen Overseas Territories is only approximately 250,000, which is less than all but three [[districts of Hong Kong]], and roughly equal to that of the [[City of Westminster]]\n\nConsequently, because ceding Hong Kong came at the end of half a century of decolonisation, and because the handover meant that the United Kingdom became without significant overseas territories, [[dominions]], or [[colonies]] for the first time in its history ([[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]], having been bequeathed the incipient domains of its later empire by inheriting the [[English overseas possessions|colonial possessions]] of the [[Kingdom of England]] upon the passing of the [[Acts of Union 1707]], always having been an imperial power, [[ab initio]]) the handover of Hong Kong to China is regarded by some as marking the conclusion of the [[British Empire]], with 1 July 1997 being its end date and the handover ceremony being its last diplomatic act.\n\n==In popular culture==\nScholars have begun to study the complexities of the transfer as shown in the popular media, such as films, television and video and online games.  For example, Hong Kong director [[Fruit Chan]] made a sci-fi thriller ''[[The Midnight After]]'' (2014) that stressed the sense of loss and alienation represented by survivors in an apocalyptic Hong Kong. Chan infuses a political agenda in the film by playing on Hong Kongers' collective anxiety towards communist China.<ref>Chia-rong Wu, \"Hong Kong Identity in Question: Fruit Chan's Uncanny Narrative and (Post-)97 Complex.\" ''American Journal of Chinese Studies'' (April 2017), Vol. 24 Issue 1, pp 43\u201356.</ref>  Yiman Wang has argued that America has viewed China through the prisms of films from Shanghai and Hong Kong, with a recent emphasis on futuristic disaster films set in Hong Kong after the transfer goes awry.<ref>Yiman Wang, ''Remaking Chinese Cinema: Through the Prism of Shanghai, Hong Kong, and Hollywood'' (2014) pp 114, 131</ref> \n*The handover is central to the plot of the 1998 action film ''[[Rush Hour (1998 film)|Rush Hour]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Chris Berry|author2=Mary Ann Farquhar|title=China on Screen: Cinema and Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YOWdAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA2|year=2006|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-13706-5|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\"Singh 2016\">{{cite web|first1=Harminder|last1=Singh|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education-community/article/1983718/everything-you-need-know-about-hong-kongs-return|title=Everything you need to know about Hong Kong's return to Chinese sovereignty|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|publisher=[[Alibaba Group]]|date=1 July 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018010140/http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education-community/article/1983718/everything-you-need-know-about-hong-kongs-return|archive-date=18 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*It is also mentioned in another 1998 film\u2014''[[Knock Off (film)|Knock Off]]''.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Knock-Off-Rob-Schneider/dp/B000I9YUY0 ''Knock Off'' 1998] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508072910/http://www.amazon.com/Knock-Off-Rob-Schneider/dp/B000I9YUY0 |date=8 May 2016 }}, [[Amazon.com]]</ref>\n*The handover is the backdrop for \"A Death in Hong Kong\", the first episode the [[Murder, She Wrote (season 10)|tenth series]] of ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007h8j3 A Death in Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312123725/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007h8j3 |date=12 March 2017 }}, [[BBC Two]], 27 February 2009</ref><ref name=\"Singh 2016\" />\n*Hong Kong Cantopop artist [[Samuel Hui|Sam Hui]] has made numerous references to 1997 including the song \"Could Not Care Less About 1997\" (\u8a71\u77e5\u4f6097).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MLT4fstT_Tc |title=Sam Hui \u8a31\u51a0\u5091 \u2013 \u8a71\u77e5\u4f6097 (\u96fb\u5f71\u300e\u65b0\u534a\u65a4\u516b\u4e24\u300f\u4e3b\u984c\u66f2) |access-date=1 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423031249/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MLT4fstT_Tc |archive-date=23 April 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n*Chinese American rapper [[Jin Auyeung]] has a song called \"1997\" in his Cantonese album ''ABC'', which he makes references to the handover, ten years since Hong Kong's return to China.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hqfSgxw--38 |title=Artist : Jin Title : 1997 Album : ABC Track No : 9  |access-date=1 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170416150844/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hqfSgxw--38 |archive-date=16 April 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n*''[[Zero Minus Ten]]'', a [[James Bond]] novel by [[Raymond Benson]], is set largely in Hong Kong during the days leading up to the Handover.<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Zero-Minus-Ten-James-Bond/dp/0340684496 ''Zero Minus Ten'' (James Bond 007)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414143231/http://www.amazon.co.uk/Zero-Minus-Ten-James-Bond/dp/0340684496 |date=14 April 2016 }}, [[Amazon.com]]</ref><ref name=\"Singh 2016\" />\n*The 2012 James Bond film ''[[Skyfall]]'' features [[Raoul Silva|a villain]] who had been an [[MI6]] agent in Hong Kong until the Handover, when he was handed over to the Chinese for his unauthorised [[Hacker (computer security)|hacking]] of their security networks.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/business/article/1080685/will-james-bond-bow-beijings-censorship Will James Bond bow to Beijing's censorship?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503213927/http://www.scmp.com/business/article/1080685/will-james-bond-bow-beijings-censorship |date=3 May 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 12 November 2012</ref>\n* The ''[[Doctor Who Unbound]]'' audio drama ''[[Sympathy for the Devil (audio drama)|Sympathy for the Devil]]'' by [[Jonathan Clements]] is set on the eve of the Handover and involves an attempted defection by a war criminal, only hours before China takes control.<ref name=\"Singh 2016\" />\n*''[[Hong Kong 97 (film)|Hong Kong 97]]'', a 1994 [[American films|American]] movie starring [[Robert Patrick]], is set in Hong Kong during the 24 hours before the end of British rule.<ref>[https://ew.com/article/1994/11/04/video-review-hong-kong-97 Hong Kong '97] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120080102/http://www.ew.com/article/1994/11/04/video-review-hong-kong-97 |date=20 November 2015 }}, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', 4 November 1994</ref>\n*''[[Hong Kong 97 (video game)|Hong Kong 97]]'', a 1995 Japanese [[homebrew (video games)|homebrew]] [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]] game, is set in Hong Kong around the time of the transition. The player controls Chin ([[Jackie Chan]]), who was called by the Hong Kong government to kill the invading Chinese, including [[Tong Shau Ping]]. The game gained a [[cult following]] due to its [[kuso|very poor quality]] and absurd plot.<ref>[http://kotaku.com/5936454/racism-violence--madness-make-this-awful-hong-kong-game-one-to-remember Racism, Violence & Madness Make This Awful Hong Kong Game One to Remember] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416131853/http://kotaku.com/5936454/racism-violence--madness-make-this-awful-hong-kong-game-one-to-remember |date=16 April 2016 }}, [[Kotaku]], 21 August 2012</ref>\n*The handover of Hong Kong is referenced multiple times and witnessed in the 1997 film ''[[Chinese Box]]'', starring [[Jeremy Irons]] and [[Gong Li]].  The film itself was filmed leading up to and during the handover.<ref name=NYT>[https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A02E7D8143CF934A25757C0A96E958260 Chinese Box (1997) FILM REVIEW; A Meditation on the Meaning of Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160827/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A02E7D8143CF934A25757C0A96E958260 |date=24 July 2016 }}, Stephen Holden, ''[[The New York Times]]'' 17 April 1998</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Hong Kong}}\n*[[History of Chinese immigration to Canada#Heading into the new millennium|History of Chinese immigration to Canada]]\n*[[Hong Kong people in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Monument in Commemoration of the Return of Hong Kong to China]]\n*[[Transfer of sovereignty over Macau]]\n*[[Hong Kong 1 July marches]]\n*[[Hong Kong\u2013Mainland conflict]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |year=2008 |title=''[[Dicey Morris & Collins|Dicey, Morris and Collins on the Conflict of Laws]]'' |isbn=978-0-421-88360-4 |edition=14th |publisher=Sweet & Maxwell |first1=Lawrence |last1=Collins |author1-link=Lawrence Collins, Baron Collins of Mapesbury |first2=C.G.J. |last2=Morse |first3=David |last3=McClean |first4=Adrian |last4=Briggs |first5=Jonathan |last5=Harris |first6=Campbell |last6=McLachlan |first7=Jonathan |last7=Hill}}\n* {{cite book |year=2008 |first1=J.J. |last1=Fawcett |first2=J.M. |last2=Carruthers |first3=Peter |last3=North |title=Cheshire, North & Fawcett: Private International Law |isbn=978-0-19-928438-2}}\n* Flowerdew, John. ''The final years of British Hong Kong: The discourse of colonial withdrawal'' (Springer, 1998).\n* Lane, Kevin. ''Sovereignty and the status quo: the historical roots of China's Hong Kong policy'' (Westview Press, 1990).\n* Mark, Chi-kwan. \"To \u2018educate\u2019 Deng Xiaoping in capitalism: Thatcher's visit to China and the future of Hong Kong in 1982.\" ''Cold War History'' (2015): 1\u201320.\n* Tang, James TH. \"From empire defence to imperial retreat: Britain's postwar China policy and the decolonization of Hong Kong.\" ''Modern Asian Studies'' 28.02 (1994): 317\u2013337.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://gohongkong.about.com/od/travelplanner/a/hongkongcountry.htm|title=What Country Is Hong Kong in? China or Not?|first=Rory|last=Boland|work=About.com Travel}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/big/0630.html|title=China Resumes Control of Hong Kong, Concluding 156 Years of British Rule|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"auto2\">\"1898 and all that\u2014a Brief History of Hong Kong.\" ''The Economist'', 28 June 1997</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970616070035/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/hongkong/index.htm|date=16 June 1997|title=The Hong Kong handover}} \u2013 [[BBC World Service]]\n* [http://www.hksar20.gov.hk/ Hong Kong SAR's 20th Anniversary]{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} \n{{HKafter1997}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Transfer Of Sovereignty Of Hong Kong}}\n[[Category:History of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:British Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:1997 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:1997 in China]]\n[[Category:1997 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1997 in international relations]]\n[[Category:1990s in Hong Kong]]<!--for lead up in decade--->\n[[Category:China\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Sovereignty]]\n[[Category:July 1997 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Decolonisation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Transfer of sovereignty of Hong Kong to China}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name              = <!--Uses page name if omitted-->\n|native_name       = \n|native_name_lang  = \n|logo              = \n|logo_alt          = \n|logo_caption      = \n|logo_size         = \n|image             = \n|image_size        = \n|alt               = \n|caption           = On the afternoon of June 30, 1997, [[PATTEN]] on the eve of [[Hong Kong Governor]], [[Hong Kong Governor's Office|Government House]] received [[attendant officer|adjutant]] [[Hong Kong Governor#emblem|Governor's flag]].\n|status            = <!-- e.g. defunct, active, inactive ... -->\n|genre             = <!-- e.g. natural phenomena, fairs, festivals, conferences, exhibitions ... -->\n|date              = 1 July 1997\n|begins            = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|mm|dd}} -->\n|ends              = <!-- {{end date|YYYY|mm|dd}} -->\n|frequency         = <!-- Weekly, Monthly, Quarterly, Semi-annually, Annually, Bi-annually, 2nd Tuesday of November, etc. -->\n|venue             = \n|location          = Hong Kong\n|coordinates       = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display=inline,title}} --> \n|country           = \n|years_active      = <!-- {{age|YYYY|mm|dd}} Date of the first occurrence -->\n|first             = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|mm|dd}} \"founded=\" and \"established=\" also work -->\n|founder_name      = <!-- or | founders = -->\n|last              = <!-- Date of most recent event; if the event will not be held again, use {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n|prev              = \n|next              = \n|participants      = [[People's Republic of China]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland]]\n|attendance        = \n|capacity          = \n|area              = \n|budget            = \n|activity          = \n|leader_name       = \n|patron            = \n|organised         = <!-- \"organized=\" also works -->\n|filing            = \n|people            = \n|member            = \n|sponsor           = <!-- | or sponsors = -->\n|website           = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n|current           = \n|footnotes         = \n}}\n{{History of Hong Kong}}\n\nThe '''transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong''',<ref>\"This law took effect on 1 July 1997, upon the '''transfer of sovereignty''' from the United Kingdom to China\" [https://www.yearbook.gov.hk/1997/ch3/e3m.htm Hong Kong Year Book] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025223258/https://www.yearbook.gov.hk/1997/ch3/e3m.htm |date=25 October 2018 }}</ref><ref>\"...existing system in order to preserve continuity in the administration of the public service after the '''transfer of sovereignty'''\" [http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr04-05/english/panels/se/papers/se0815cb2-2431-2e.pdf Legislative Council of Hong Kong record] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006075237/http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr04-05/english/panels/se/papers/se0815cb2-2431-2e.pdf |date=6 October 2018 }}</ref><ref>Parliament of Australia [https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Joint/Completed_Inquiries/jfadt/hongkong/reportinx|Completed Inquiry: Hong Kong: The Transfer of Sovereignty]</ref> commonly known as the '''handover of Hong Kong''' (or simply '''the Handover''', also '''the Return''' in mainland China and Hong Kong), occurred at midnight at the start of 1 July 1997, when the [[United Kingdom]] ended administration for the [[British Hong Kong|colony of Hong Kong]] and returned control of the territory to [[China]]. [[Hong Kong]] became a [[Special administrative regions of China|special administrative region]] and continues to maintain governing and economic systems separate from those of [[mainland China]].\n\nThis event ended 156 years of British colonial rule in Hong Kong. The territory was Britain's last substantial overseas possession. With a population of about 6.5 million in 1997, Hong Kong constituted 97% of the total population of all [[British Overseas Territories|British Dependent Territories]] at the time. The retrocession is considered by some to definitively mark the end of the [[British Empire]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Acquisition of Hong Kong.svg|thumb|250px|Britain acquired [[Hong Kong Island]] in 1842, the [[Kowloon Peninsula]] in 1860, and the lease of the [[New Territories]] in 1898.]]\n\nBy the 1820s and 1830s, the British had conquered parts of India and had intentions of growing cotton in these lands to offset the amount of cotton they were buying from America. When this endeavour failed, the British realised they could grow poppies at an incredible rate. These poppies could then be turned into opium, which the Chinese highly desired, but their laws prohibited. So the British plan was grow poppies in India, convert it into opium, smuggle the opium in China and trade it for tea, and sell the tea back in Britain. The illegal opium trade was highly successful, and the drug was very profitably smuggled into China in extremely large volumes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Chinese Opium Wars|last=Beeching|first=Jack|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|year=1975|isbn=|location=New York|pages=74}}</ref>\n\nThe United Kingdom obtained control over portions of Hong Kong's territory through three treaties concluded with [[Qing dynasty|Qing China]] after the [[Opium Wars]]:\n\n* 1842 [[Treaty of Nanking]]: [[Hong Kong Island]] ceded in perpetuity\n* 1860 [[Convention of Peking]]: [[Kowloon Peninsula]] and [[Stonecutter's Island]] additionally ceded\n* 1898 [[Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory]]: the [[New Territories]] and [[Outlying Islands, Hong Kong|outlying islands]] leased for 99 years until 1997\n\nDespite the finite nature of the New Territories lease, this portion of the colony was developed just as rapidly as, and became highly integrated with, the rest of Hong Kong. As the end of the lease approached, and by the time of serious negotiations over the future status of Hong Kong in the 1980s, it was thought impractical to separate the ceded territories and return only the New Territories to China. In addition, with the scarcity of land and natural resources in Hong Kong Island and Kowloon, large-scale [[infrastructures|infrastructure]] investments had been made in the New Territories, with break-evens lying well past 30 June 1997.<ref name=\"Akers-Jones\" />\n\nWhen the People's Republic of China obtained its seat in the United Nations as a result of the [[UN General Assembly Resolution 2758]] in 1971, it began to act diplomatically on its previously lost sovereignty over both Hong Kong and [[Macau]]. In March 1972, the Chinese UN representative, [[Huang Hua (politician)|Huang Hua]], wrote to the United Nations Decolonization Committee to state the position of the Chinese government:\n\n:\"The questions of Hong Kong and Macau belong to the category of questions resulting from the series of unequal treaties which the imperialists imposed on China. Hong Kong and Macau are part of Chinese territory occupied by the British and Portuguese authorities. The settlement of the questions of Hong Kong and Macau is entirely within China's sovereign right and do not at all fall under the ordinary category of colonial territories. Consequently they should not be included in the list of colonial territories covered by the declaration on the granting of independence to colonial territories and people. With regard to the questions of Hong Kong and Macau, the Chinese government has consistently held that they should be settled in an appropriate way when conditions are ripe.\"<ref name=\"Passage\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=BZQcw-SJhI8C&lpg=PA45&ots=8mGxHzO1cv&dq=Huang%20Hua%20Hong%20Kong%20Macau&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q=Huang%20Hua%20Hong%20Kong%20Macau&f=false ''The Hong Kong Reader: Passage to Chinese Sovereignty''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104421/https://books.google.com/books?id=BZQcw-SJhI8C&lpg=PA45&ots=8mGxHzO1cv&dq=Huang%20Hua%20Hong%20Kong%20Macau&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q=Huang%20Hua%20Hong%20Kong%20Macau&f=false |date=22 February 2017 }}, Ming K. Chan, Gerard A. Postiglione, \nM.E. Sharpe, 1996, page 45</ref>\n\nThe same year, on 8 November, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] passed the resolution on removing Hong Kong and Macau from the official list of colonies.<ref name=\"Passage\" />\n\nIn March 1979 the [[Governor of Hong Kong]], [[Murray MacLehose, Baron MacLehose of Beoch|Murray MacLehose]], paid his first official visit to the People's Republic of China (PRC), taking the initiative to raise the question of Hong Kong's sovereignty with [[Deng Xiaoping]].<ref name=\"Pepper\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=upDNEYtw4uYC&lpg=PA229&ots=9X2jk49fP9&dq=murray%20maclehose%20deng%20xiaoping%20march%201979&pg=PA229#v=onepage&q=murray%20maclehose%20deng%20xiaoping%20march%201979&f=true Elections, Political Change and Basic Law Government: Hong Kong in Search of a Political Form] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222085643/https://books.google.com/books?id=upDNEYtw4uYC&lpg=PA229&ots=9X2jk49fP9&dq=murray%20maclehose%20deng%20xiaoping%20march%201979&pg=PA229#v=onepage&q=murray%20maclehose%20deng%20xiaoping%20march%201979&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, [[Suzanne Pepper]] in ''Elections and Democracy in Greater China'', Larry Diamond, Ramon H. Myers, OUP Oxford, 2001, page 55</ref> Without clarifying and establishing the official position of the PRC government, the arranging of real estate leases and loans agreements in Hong Kong within the next 18 years would become difficult.<ref name=\"Akers-Jones\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=PnQAsA0oIPoC&lpg=PA110&ots=hba5L3TnmJ&dq=edward%20heath%20deng%20xiaoping%20hong%20kong&pg=PA109#v=onepage&q=edward%20heath%20deng%20xiaoping%20hong%20kong&f=true ''Feeling the Stones: Reminiscences by David Akers-Jones''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222102306/https://books.google.com/books?id=PnQAsA0oIPoC&lpg=PA110&ots=hba5L3TnmJ&dq=edward%20heath%20deng%20xiaoping%20hong%20kong&pg=PA109#v=onepage&q=edward%20heath%20deng%20xiaoping%20hong%20kong&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, David Akers-Jones, Hong Kong University Press, 2004, page 109</ref>\n\nIn response to concerns over land leases in the New Territories, MacLehose proposed that British administration of the whole of Hong Kong, as opposed to sovereignty, be allowed to continue after 1997.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/jun/02/guardianobituaries1 Lord MacLehose] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123134724/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/jun/02/guardianobituaries1 |date=23 November 2016 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 2 June 2000</ref> He also proposed that contracts include the phrase \"for so long as the Crown administers the territory\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=02Hjr6RUckwC&lpg=PA224&ots=sLeL8zIEld&dq=Murray%20MacLehose%20British%20administer%20hong%20kong%201997&pg=PA224#v=onepage&q&f=true ''Strong Borders, Secure Nation: Cooperation and Conflict in China's Territorial Disputes''], M. Taylor Fravel, Princeton University Press, 2008, page 224</ref>\n\nIn fact, as early as the mid-1970s, Hong Kong had faced additional risks raising loans for large-scale infrastructure projects such as its [[Mass Transit Railway]] (MTR) system and a new airport. Caught unprepared, Deng asserted the necessity of Hong Kong's return to China, upon which Hong Kong would be given special status by the PRC government.\n\nMacLehose's visit to the PRC raised the curtain on the issue of Hong Kong's sovereignty: Britain was made aware of the PRC's intent to resume sovereignty over Hong Kong, and began to make arrangements accordingly to ensure the sustenance of her interests within the territory, as well as initiating the creation of a withdrawal plan in case of emergency.\n\nThree years later, Deng received the former [[British Prime Minister]] [[Edward Heath]], who had been dispatched as the special envoy of Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] to establish an understanding of the PRC's plans with regards to the retrocession of Hong Kong; during their meeting, Deng outlined his plans to make the territory a special economic zone, which would retain its capitalist system under Chinese sovereignty.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hwPUGWBTsX4C&lpg=PA68&ots=0SItBhYsyi&dq=edward%20heath%20deng%20xiaoping%20hong%20kong&pg=PA68#v=onepage&q=edward%20heath%20deng%20xiaoping%20hong%20kong&f=false ''Hong Kong: The Pearl Made of British Mastery and Chinese Docile-diligence''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222125654/https://books.google.com/books?id=hwPUGWBTsX4C&lpg=PA68&ots=0SItBhYsyi&dq=edward%20heath%20deng%20xiaoping%20hong%20kong&pg=PA68#v=onepage&q=edward%20heath%20deng%20xiaoping%20hong%20kong&f=false |date=22 December 2016 }}, Wei-Bin Zhang, Nova Publishers, 2006, page 68</ref>\n\nIn the same year, [[Edward Youde]], who succeeded MacLehose as the 26th Governor of Hong Kong, led a [[delegation]] of five [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Councillor]]s to London, including [[Chung Sze-yuen]], [[Lydia Dunn]], and [[Roger Lobo]].<ref name=\"Chung\">[https://archive.org/details/hongkongsjourney00chun/page/123 <!-- quote=chung sze-yuen lydia dunn and roger lobo delegation to london. --> ''Hong Kong's Journey to Reunification: Memoirs of Sze-yuen Chung''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104047/https://books.google.com/books?id=0ZxGHy-4X30C&lpg=PA352&ots=78T_VKsnfe&dq=chung%20sze-yuen%20lydia%20dunn%20and%20roger%20lobo%20delegation%20to%20london&pg=PA123#v=onepage&q=chung%20sze-yuen%20lydia%20dunn%20and%20roger%20lobo%20delegation%20to%20london&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Sze Yuen Chung, Chinese University Press, 2001, page 123</ref> Chung presented their position on the sovereignty of Hong Kong to Thatcher, encouraging her to take into consideration the interests of the native Hong Kong population in her upcoming visit to China.<ref name=\"Chung\" />\n\nIn light of the increasing openness of the PRC government and economic reforms on the mainland, the then British Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] sought the PRC's agreement to a continued British presence in the territory.<ref name=\"Cottrell\" />\n\nHowever, the PRC took a contrary position: not only did the PRC wish for the New Territories, on lease until 1997, to be placed under the PRC's jurisdiction, it also refused to recognise the onerous \"[[Unequal treaty|unfair and unequal treaties]]\" under which Hong Kong Island and Kowloon had been ceded to Britain in perpetuity after the [[Opium Wars]].<ref name=\"Yahuda\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=b9gGzWigqpMC&q=kowloon#v=onepage&q=kowloon&f=true ''Hong Kong: China's Challenge''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222102800/https://books.google.com/books?id=b9gGzWigqpMC&q=kowloon#v=onepage&q=kowloon&f=true |date=22 December 2016 }}, Michael B. Yahuda, Routledge, 1996, page 45</ref> Consequently, the PRC recognised only the British administration in Hong Kong, but not British sovereignty.<ref name=\"Yahuda\" />\n\n==Talks==\n{{quote box\n|title=Major events, 1979\u20131997\n|align=right\n|width=30%\n|quote=<nowiki></nowiki>\n* 24 March 1979: Hong Kong Governor Sir [[Murray MacLehose]] was invited to visit Guangzhou and Beijing to find out the attitude of the Chinese government on the issue of Hong Kong.\n* 29 March 1979: Sir Murray MacLehose met paramount leader [[Deng Xiaoping]] and raised the issue of Hong Kong for the first time. Deng remarked that the investors could set their minds at peace.\n* 4 April 1979: The Kowloon\u2013Canton through-train routes were restored after 30 years of non-service.\n* 3 May 1979: The [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] won the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|U.K. election]].\n* 29 October 1979: Premier [[Hua Guofeng]] visited Britain and had a meeting with British prime minister [[Margaret Thatcher]]. Both of them expressed their concern to maintain the stability and prosperity of Hong Kong.\n* 12 May 1980: [[Table (verb)#Commencing discussion|Table]]d by the Conservative Party in the British government, a new status \"[[British Overseas Territories citizen]]\" was introduced. This status proposal was widely opposed by Hong Kong people.\n* 3 April 1981: Foreign Secretary [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Lord Carrington]] met Deng Xiaoping in his visit to Beijing.\n* 30 September 1981: Chairman of the [[National People's Congress|NPC]] [[Ye Jianying]] issued nine guiding principles concerning a peaceful reunification of Taiwan and mainland China.\n* 30 October 1981: The House of Commons passed the new British Nationality Act.\n* November 1981: The Beijing government invited some Hong Kong citizens to help organising a united front in the handling of the Hong Kong issue.\n* 6 January 1982: Chinese Premier [[Zhao Ziyang]] received Lord Privy Seal [[Humphrey Atkins]]. Zhao insisted that the PRC would uphold its sovereignty over Hong Kong.\n* 10 March 1982: Vice Premier [[Gu Mu]] received Sir [[John Bremridge]], promising to maintain Hong Kong's stability and prosperity.\n* 6 April 1982: Deng Xiaoping revealed his wish to have official contact with the British government.\n* 8 May 1982: Sir [[Edward Youde]] arrived as the 26th Governor of Hong Kong.\n* May 1982: Deng Xiaoping and Zhao Ziyang collected advice from Hong Kong notables such as [[Li Ka-shing]] and [[T. K. Ann|Ann Tse-kei]].\n* 15 June 1982: Deng Xiaoping officially announced the position of the Chinese government in the context of the Hong Kong 97 Issue, marking the first public statement on part of the PRC with regards to the issue.}}\n\n===Before the negotiations===\nIn the wake of Governor MacLehose's visit, Britain and the PRC established initial diplomatic contact for further discussions of the Hong Kong question, paving the way for Thatcher's first visit to the PRC in September 1982.<ref name=\"Roger\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=cxxGJ7c10noC&lpg=PA111&vq=Thatcher&pg=PA109#v=onepage&q=Thatcher&f=true ''Hong Kong: The Road to 1997''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222170811/https://books.google.com/books?id=cxxGJ7c10noC&lpg=PA111&vq=Thatcher&pg=PA109#v=onepage&q=Thatcher&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Roger Buckley, Cambridge University Press, 1997, page 109</ref>\n\nMargaret Thatcher, in discussion with Deng Xiaoping, reiterated the validity of an extension of the lease of Hong Kong territory, particularly in light of binding treaties, including the Treaty of Nanking in 1842, the [[Convention of Peking]] in 1856, and the Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory signed in 1890.\n\nIn response, Deng Xiaoping cited clearly the lack of room for compromise on the question of sovereignty over Hong Kong; the PRC, as the successor of [[Qing dynasty]] and the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] on [[Mainland China|the mainland]], would recover the entirety of the New Territories, Kowloon and Hong Kong Island. China considered treaties about Hong Kong as unequal and ultimately refused to accept any outcome that would indicate permanent loss of sovereignty over Hong Kong's area, whatever wording the former treaties had.<ref>Ezra F. Vogel: Deng Xiaoping and the Transformation of China. Library of Congress Cataloging-in-Publication Data 2011. Pages 496\u20137.</ref>\n\nDuring talks with Thatcher, China planned to invade and seize Hong Kong if the negotiations set off unrest in the colony. Thatcher later said that Deng told her bluntly that China could easily take Hong Kong by force, stating that \"I could walk in and take the whole lot this afternoon\", to which she replied that \"there is nothing I could do to stop you, but the eyes of the world would now know what China is like\".<ref>[http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/world_news/article67028.ece China plotted Hong Kong invasion] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408004455/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/world_news/article67028.ece |date=8 April 2016 }}, Michael Sheridan, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', 25 June 2007</ref>\n\nAfter her visit with Deng in Beijing, Thatcher was received in Hong Kong as the first British Prime Minister to set foot on the territory whilst in office. At a press conference, Thatcher re-emphasised the validity of the three treaties, asserting the need for countries to respect treaties on universal terms: \"There are three treaties in existence; we stick by our treaties unless we decide on something else. At the moment, we stick by our treaties.\"<ref name=\"Cottrell\" />\n\nAt the same time, at the 5th session of the 5th [[National People's Congress]], the constitution was amended to include a new Article 31 which stated that the country might establish [[Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China|Special Administrative Regions]] (SARs) when necessary.<ref>[http://english.gov.cn/archive/laws_regulations/2014/08/23/content_281474982987458.htm Constitution of the People's Republic of China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416110047/http://english.gov.cn/archive/laws_regulations/2014/08/23/content_281474982987458.htm |date=16 April 2016 }}, State Council of the People's Republic of China</ref>\n\nThe additional Article would hold tremendous significance in settling the question of Hong Kong and later [[Macau]], putting into social consciousness the concept of \"[[One country, two systems]]\". The concept would prove useful to deploy until the territories were secured and conditions were ripe for its gradual revision.\n\n===Negotiations begin===\nA few months after Thatcher's visit to Beijing, the PRC government had yet to open negotiations with the British government regarding the sovereignty of Hong Kong.\n\nShortly before the initiation of sovereignty talks, Governor Youde declared his intention to represent the population of Hong Kong at the negotiations. This statement sparked a strong response from the PRC, prompting Deng Xiaoping to denounce talk of \"the so-called 'three-legged stool'\", which implied that Hong Kong was a party to talks on its future, alongside Beijing and London.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/article/453465/benefits-three-legged-stool Benefits of a three-legged stool] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427121205/http://www.scmp.com/article/453465/benefits-three-legged-stool |date=27 April 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 26 April 2004</ref>\n\nAt the preliminary stage of the talks, the British government proposed an exchange of sovereignty for administration and the implementation of a British administration post-handover.<ref name=\"Cottrell\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090809225312/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/how-mrs-thatcher-lost-hong-kong-ten-years-ago-fired-up-by-her-triumph-in-the-falklands-war-margaret-thatcher-flew-to-peking-for-a-lastditch-attempt-to-keep-hong-kong-under-british-rule--only-to-meet-her-match-in-deng-xiaoping-two-years-later-she-signed-the-agreement-handing-the-territory-to-china-1543375.html How Mrs Thatcher lost Hong Kong], ''[[The Independent]]'', Robert Cottrell, 30 August 1992</ref>\n\nThe PRC government refused, contending that the notions of sovereignty and administration were inseparable, and although it recognised [[Macau]] as a \"Chinese territory under Portuguese administration\", this was only temporary.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ySvxAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA175&ots=RFhVibuCgz&dq=%22a%20Chinese%20territory%20under%20Portuguese%20administration%22&pg=PA175#v=onepage&q=%22a%20Chinese%20territory%20under%20Portuguese%20administration%22&f=true ''China Perspectives''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222105810/https://books.google.com/books?id=ySvxAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA175&ots=RFhVibuCgz&dq=%22a%20Chinese%20territory%20under%20Portuguese%20administration%22&pg=PA175#v=onepage&q=%22a%20Chinese%20territory%20under%20Portuguese%20administration%22&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Issues 21\u201326, C.E.F.C., 1999, page 13</ref>\n\nIn fact, during informal exchanges between 1979 and 1981, the PRC had proposed a \"Macau solution\" in Hong Kong, under which it would remain under British administration at China's discretion.<ref name=\"Pepper\" />\n\nHowever, this had previously been rejected following the [[Hong Kong 1967 Leftist riots|1967 Leftist riots]], with the then Governor, [[David Trench]], claiming the leftists' aim was to leave the UK without effective control, or \"to Macau us\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0uStp3CUaqUC&lpg=PA36&ots=PJ5gTkk6V5&dq=hong%20kong%20%22macau%20solution%22&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q=hong%20kong%20%22macau%20solution%22&f=true ''Hong Kong's Watershed: The 1967 Riots''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104333/https://books.google.com/books?id=0uStp3CUaqUC&lpg=PA36&ots=PJ5gTkk6V5&dq=hong%20kong%20%22macau%20solution%22&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q=hong%20kong%20%22macau%20solution%22&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Gary Ka-wai Cheung, Hong Kong University Press, 2009, page 37</ref>\n\nThe conflict that arose at that point of the negotiations ended the possibility of further negotiation. During the reception of former British Prime Minister Edward Heath during his sixth visit to the PRC, Deng Xiaoping commented quite clearly on the impossibility of exchanging sovereignty for administration, declaring an ultimatum: the British government must modify or give up its position or the PRC will announce its resolution of the issue of Hong Kong sovereignty unilaterally.<ref name=\"fmprc\">[http://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/ziliao_665539/3602_665543/3604_665547/t18032.shtml The Chinese government resumed exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401135704/http://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/ziliao_665539/3602_665543/3604_665547/t18032.shtml |date=1 April 2016 }}, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]], People's Republic of China</ref>\n\nIn 1983, [[Typhoon Ellen (1983)|Typhoon Ellen]] ravaged Hong Kong, causing great amounts of damage to both life and property.<ref name=\"SHT\">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ReUbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gGgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1278,6865410&dq=typhoon+ellen&hl=en Typhoon Ellen Batters Hong Kong, killing 6] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222095911/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ReUbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gGgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1278,6865410&dq=typhoon+ellen&hl=en |date=22 February 2017 }}, [[United Press International]], ''[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]'', 10 September 1983</ref> The Hong Kong dollar plummeted on [[Black Saturday (1983)|Black Saturday]], and the [[Financial Secretary of Hong Kong|Financial Secretary]] [[John Bremridge]] publicly associated the economic uncertainty with the instability of the political climate.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/1983/1004/100426.html Hong Kong business world shaken by political uncertainties] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411040625/http://www.csmonitor.com/1983/1004/100426.html |date=11 April 2016 }}, ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', 4 October 1983</ref> In response, the PRC government condemned Britain through the press for \"playing the economic card\" in order to achieve their ends: to intimidate the PRC into conceding to British demands.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1988/jan/20/hong-kong Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414154546/http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1988/jan/20/hong-kong |date=14 April 2016 }} ''[[Hansard]]'', HC Deb 20 January 1988 vol 125 cc971-1018</ref>\n\n===British concession===\nGovernor Youde with nine members of the Hong Kong Executive Council travelled to London to discuss with Prime Minister Thatcher the crisis of confidence\u2014the problem with morale among the people of Hong Kong arising from the ruination of the Sino-British talks. The session concluded with Thatcher's writing of a letter addressed to the PRC Premier [[Zhao Ziyang]].\n\nIn the letter, she expressed Britain's willingness to explore arrangements optimising the future prospects of Hong Kong while utilising the PRC's proposals as a foundation. Furthermore, and perhaps most significantly, she expressed Britain's concession on its position of a continued British presence in the form of an administration post-handover.\n\nTwo rounds of negotiations were held in October and November. On the sixth round of talks in November, Britain formally conceded its intentions of either maintaining a British administration in Hong Kong or seeking some form of co-administration with the PRC, and showed its sincerity in discussing PRC's proposal on the 1997 issue. Obstacles were cleared.\n\n[[Simon Keswick]], chairman of [[Jardine Matheson]] & Co., said they were not pulling out of Hong Kong, but a new [[holding company]] would be established in [[Bermuda]] instead.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=N0_VAAAAMAAJ&q=Simon+Keswick++Jardine+Matheson+%26+Co++bermuda&dq=Simon+Keswick++Jardine+Matheson+%26+Co++bermuda&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwil1eyGvODLAhUDNhoKHdhPCO8Q6AEIVjAK ''Summary of World Broadcasts: Far East''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104517/https://books.google.com/books?id=N0_VAAAAMAAJ&q=Simon+Keswick++Jardine+Matheson+%26+Co++bermuda&dq=Simon+Keswick++Jardine+Matheson+%26+Co++bermuda&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwil1eyGvODLAhUDNhoKHdhPCO8Q6AEIVjAK |date=22 February 2017 }}, Part 3, BBC Monitoring Service, 1984</ref> The PRC took this as yet another plot by the British. The Hong Kong government explained that it had been informed about the move only a few days before the announcement. The government would not and could not stop the company from making a business decision.\n\nJust as the atmosphere of the talks was becoming cordial, members of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] felt impatient at the long-running secrecy over the progress of Sino-British talks on the Hong Kong issue. A motion, [[Table (verb)#Commencing discussion|table]]d by legislator [[Roger Lobo]], declared \"This Council deems it essential that any proposals for the future of Hong Kong should be debated in this Council before agreement is reached\", was passed unanimously.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w7NuSICc0lYC&lpg=PA210&ots=dgIKZeY1rf&dq=This%20Council%20deems%20it%20essential%20that%20any%20proposals%20for%20the%20future%20of%20Hong%20Kong%20should%20be%20debated%20in%20this%20Council%20before%20agreement%20is%20reached&pg=PA210#v=onepage&q=This%20Council%20deems%20it%20essential%20that%20any%20proposals%20for%20the%20future%20of%20Hong%20Kong%20should%20be%20debated%20in%20this%20Council%20before%20agreement%20is%20reached&f=true ''Political Change and the Crisis of Legitimacy in Hong Kong''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222105938/https://books.google.com/books?id=w7NuSICc0lYC&lpg=PA210&ots=dgIKZeY1rf&dq=This%20Council%20deems%20it%20essential%20that%20any%20proposals%20for%20the%20future%20of%20Hong%20Kong%20should%20be%20debated%20in%20this%20Council%20before%20agreement%20is%20reached&pg=PA210#v=onepage&q=This%20Council%20deems%20it%20essential%20that%20any%20proposals%20for%20the%20future%20of%20Hong%20Kong%20should%20be%20debated%20in%20this%20Council%20before%20agreement%20is%20reached&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Ian Scott, Ian Scott\nUniversity of Hawaii Press, 1989, page 210</ref>\n\nThe PRC attacked the motion furiously, referring to it as \"somebody's attempt to play the three-legged stool trick again\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?ei=QtDeUdbPDu-20QW5k4CgCg&id=B9ksAAAAMAAJ&dq=three-legged+stool+trick+hong+kong&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22trick+once+again%22 ''Daily Report: People's Republic of China''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222165041/https://books.google.com/books?ei=QtDeUdbPDu-20QW5k4CgCg&id=B9ksAAAAMAAJ&dq=three-legged+stool+trick+hong+kong&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22trick+once+again%22 |date=22 February 2017 }}, Issues 38\u201345, United States. Foreign Broadcast Information Service, National Technical Information Service, 1993, page 79</ref> At length, the PRC and Britain initiated the Joint Declaration on the question of Hong Kong's future in Beijing. [[Zhou Nan]], the then PRC Deputy Foreign Minister and leader of the negotiation team, and Sir [[Richard Evans (British diplomat)|Richard Evans]], British Ambassador to Beijing and leader of the team, signed respectively on behalf of the two governments.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/26/newsid_2538000/2538843.stm ON THIS DAY: 26 September 1984: UK and China agree Hong Kong handover] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103002517/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/26/newsid_2538000/2538843.stm |date=3 January 2008 }}, [[BBC News]]</ref>\n\n==Sino-British Joint Declaration==\n{{Main|Sino-British Joint Declaration}}\nThe Sino-British Joint Declaration was signed by the Prime Ministers of the People's Republic of China and the United Kingdom governments on 19 December 1984 in Beijing. The Declaration entered into force with the exchange of instruments of ratification on 27 May 1985 and was registered by the People's Republic of China and United Kingdom governments at the United Nations on 12 June 1985.\n\nIn the Joint Declaration, the People's Republic of China Government stated that it had decided to resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong (including [[Hong Kong Island]], Kowloon, and the New Territories) with effect from 1 July 1997 and the United Kingdom Government declared that it would restore Hong Kong to the PRC with effect from 1 July 1997. In the document, the People's Republic of China Government also declared its basic policies regarding Hong Kong.\n\nIn accordance with the \"[[One country, two systems]]\" principle agreed between the United Kingdom and the People's Republic of China, the socialist system of the People's Republic of China would not be practised in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), and Hong Kong's previous capitalist system and its way of life would remain unchanged for a period of 50 years. This would have left Hong Kong unchanged until 2047.\n\nThe Joint Declaration provided that these basic policies should be stipulated in the [[Hong Kong Basic Law]]. The ceremony of the signing of the Sino-British Joint Declaration took place at 18:00, 19 December 1984 at the Western Main Chamber of the [[Great Hall of the People]]. The [[Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office]] at first proposed a list of 60\u201380 Hong Kong people to attend the ceremony. The number was finally extended to 101.\n\nThe list included Hong Kong government officials, members of the Legislative and Executive Councils, chairmen of the [[Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation]] and [[Standard Chartered Bank]], prominent businessmen such as [[Li Ka-shing]], [[Pao Yue-kong]] and [[Fok Ying-tung]], and also [[Martin Lee]] Chu-ming and [[Szeto Wah]].\n\n===Universal suffrage===\n\nThe Hong Kong Basic Law ensured, among other things, that Hong Kong will retain its [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|legislative system]], and people's rights and freedom for fifty years, as a [[Special administrative regions of China|special administrative region (SAR) of China]]. The [[Government of China|central government in Beijing]] maintains control over Hong Kong's foreign affairs as well as the legal interpretation of the Basic Law. The latter has led democracy advocates and some Hong Kong residents to argue, after the fact,  that the territory has yet to achieve [[universal suffrage]] as promised by the [[Hong Kong Basic Law|Basic Law]], leading to [[Umbrella Revolution|mass demonstrations in 2014]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> In 2019, demonstrations that started as a protest [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|against an extradition law]] also led to massive demonstrations (1.7 million on 11 August and 18 August 2019), again demanding universal suffrage, but also the resignation of Carrie Lam (the current Chief Executive).<ref name=\"BBC19aug2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49340717|title=Hong Kong: Timeline of extradition protests |quote=What started as demonstrations against an extradition bill have since taken on a much wider scope and are now demanding full democratic rights for Hong Kongers.|work=[[BBC News]] |date=4 September 2019 |access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Drafting of Basic Law==\n{{Main|Basic Law of Hong Kong}}\n\nThe [[Basic Law of Hong Kong|Basic Law]] was drafted by a [[Hong Kong Basic Law Drafting Committee|Drafting Committee]] composed of members from both Hong Kong and [[China|Mainland China]]. A [[Hong Kong Basic Law Consultative Committee|Basic Law Consultative Committee]] formed purely by Hong Kong people was established in 1985 to canvas views in Hong Kong on the drafts.\n\nThe first draft was published in April 1988, followed by a five-month public consultation exercise. The second draft was published in February 1989, and the subsequent consultation period ended in October 1989.\n\nThe Basic Law was formally promulgated on 4 April 1990 by the [[National People's Congress|NPC]], together with the designs for the flag and emblem of the HKSAR. Some members of the Basic Law drafting committee were ousted by Beijing following [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests|4 June 1989 Tiananmen Square protests]], after voicing views supporting the student protesters.\n\nThe Basic Law was said to be a mini-[[constitution]] drafted with the participation of Hong Kong people. The political system had been the most controversial issue in the drafting of the Basic Law. The special issue sub-group adopted the political model put forward by [[Louis Cha]]. This \"mainstream\" proposal was criticised for being too conservative.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\nAccording to Clauses 158 and 159 of the Basic Law, powers of interpretation and amendment of the Basic Law are vested in the [[Standing Committee of the National People's Congress]] and the National People's Congress, respectively. Hong Kong's people have limited influence.\n\n==Tide of migration==\nAfter the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]], the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Councillors]] and the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Councillors]] of Hong Kong unexpectedly held an urgent meeting, in which they agreed unanimously that the British Government should give the people of Hong Kong the [[Right of abode (United Kingdom)|right of abode]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>[http://www.taiwantoday.tw/ct.asp?xItem=103048&ctNode=2198&mp=9 A Rough Road ahead] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424062259/http://www.taiwantoday.tw/ct.asp?xItem=103048&ctNode=2198&mp=9 |date=24 April 2016 }}, ''[[Taiwan Review]]'', 1 March 1990</ref>\n\nMore than 10,000 Hong Kong residents rushed to [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]] in order to get an application form for residency in the United Kingdom. On the eve of the deadline, over 100,000 lined up overnight for a [[British National (Overseas)]] application form. While mass migration began well before 1989, the event led to the peak migration year in 1992 with 66,000 leaving.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=zyMeydaAu1kC&lpg=PP1&dq=Manion%2C%20Melanie.%20%5B2004%5D(2004).%20Corruption%20by%20Design%3A%20Building%20Clean%20Government%20in%20Mainland%20China%20and%20Hong%20Kong.%20Harvard%20University%20press.&pg=PA80#v=snippet&q=66000&f=false ''Corruption by Design: Building Clean Government in Mainland China and Hong Kong''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104312/https://books.google.com/books?id=zyMeydaAu1kC&lpg=PP1&dq=Manion%2C%20Melanie.%20%5B2004%5D(2004).%20Corruption%20by%20Design%3A%20Building%20Clean%20Government%20in%20Mainland%20China%20and%20Hong%20Kong.%20Harvard%20University%20press.&pg=PA80#v=snippet&q=66000&f=false |date=22 February 2017 }}, Melanie Manion, Harvard University Press, page 80</ref>\n\nMany citizens were pessimistic towards the future of Hong Kong and the transfer of the region's sovereignty. A tide of emigration, which was to last for no less than five years, broke out. At its peak, [[citizenship]] of small countries, such as [[Tonga]], was also in great demand.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/07/magazine/in-the-court-of-the-king-of-tonga.html?pagewanted=all In the Court of the King of Tonga] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160803/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/07/magazine/in-the-court-of-the-king-of-tonga.html?pagewanted=all |date=24 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times Company]]'', 1992</ref>\n\n[[Singapore]], which also had a [[Chinese Singaporeans|predominantly Chinese]] population, was another popular destination, with the country's Commission (now Consulate-General) being besieged by anxious Hong Kong residents.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-12/news/8902160755_1_singapore-commission-hong-kong-singapore-government Singapore Lure Stirs Crowds In Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002085238/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-12/news/8902160755_1_singapore-commission-hong-kong-singapore-government |date=2 October 2015 }}, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', 12 July 1989</ref> By September 1989, 6000 applications for residency in Singapore had been approved by the Commission.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/newpaper19890921-1.2.3.7.aspx 6,000 from HK given residency here] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420031256/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/newpaper19890921-1.2.3.7.aspx |date=20 April 2016 }}, ''[[The New Paper]]'', 21 September 1989, page 2</ref>\n\nSome [[consul (representative)|consul]] staff were suspended or arrested for their [[political corruption|corrupt behaviour]] in granting immigration visas. In April 1997, the acting [[Immigration and Naturalization Service|immigration officer]] at the [[Consulate General of the United States, Hong Kong and Macau|US Consulate-General]], James DeBates, was suspended after his wife was arrested for smuggling of Chinese migrants into the United States.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/06/world/us-immigration-officer-in-hong-kong-investigated-for-corruption.html U.S. Immigration Officer in Hong Kong Investigated for Corruption] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160810/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/06/world/us-immigration-officer-in-hong-kong-investigated-for-corruption.html |date=24 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 6 April 1997</ref> The previous year, his predecessor, Jerry Stuchiner, had been arrested for smuggling forged [[Honduran passport]]s into the territory before being sentenced to 40 months in prison.<ref>[http://europe.newsweek.com/smuggling-people-170802 Smuggling People], ''[[Newsweek]]'', 17 March 1997</ref>\n\nCanada ([[Greater Vancouver|Vancouver]] and [[Greater Toronto|Toronto]]), the United Kingdom (London, [[Glasgow]], and [[Manchester]]), Australia ([[Perth]], [[Greater Sydney|Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]]), and the United States ([[San Francisco Bay Area|San Francisco]] and [[New York metropolitan area|New York]]) were, and by large, the most popular destinations. The United Kingdom devised the [[British Nationality Selection Scheme]], granting 50,000 families British citizenship under the [[British nationality law and Hong Kong|British Nationality Act (Hong Kong) 1990]].<ref>{{UK-LEG|path=ukpga/1990/34/contents|title=British Nationality Act (Hong Kong) 1990}}</ref>\n\n[[Chinese Canadians in Greater Vancouver|Vancouver]] was among the most popular destinations, earning the nickname of  \"Hongcouver\".<ref>[http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/story.html?id=011b7438-172c-4126-ba42-2c85828bd6ce Chinese Vancouver: A decade of change] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116072007/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/story.html?id=011b7438-172c-4126-ba42-2c85828bd6ce |date=16 November 2014 }}, ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', 30 June 2007</ref> [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]], a suburb of Vancouver, was nicknamed \"Little Hong Kong\".<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/a-tale-of-two-solitudes-written-anew/article1034293/ A tale of two solitudes written anew] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418034355/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/a-tale-of-two-solitudes-written-anew/article1034293/ |date=18 April 2016 }}, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', 26 October 2001</ref> All in all, from the start of the settlement of the negotiation in 1984 to 1997, nearly 1 million people emigrated; consequently, Hong Kong suffered serious loss of human and financial capital.<ref>Fosh, Patricia. Chan, Andy. Chow, Wilson WS. Snape, Ed. Westwood, Robert. [2000] (2000) Hong Kong Management and Labour. United Kingdom: Routledge. {{ISBN|0-415-22269-9}}.</ref>\n\n==Last governor==\n{{main|1994 Hong Kong electoral reform}}\n[[Chris Patten]] became the last governor of Hong Kong. This was regarded as a turning point in Hong Kong's history. Unlike his predecessors, Patten was not a diplomat, but a career politician and former Member of Parliament. He introduced democratic reforms which pushed PRC\u2013British relations to a standstill and affected the negotiations for a smooth handover.\n\nPatten introduced a package of electoral reforms in the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]]. These reforms proposed to enlarge the electorate, thus making voting in the Legislative Council more democratic. This move posed significant changes because Hong Kong citizens would have the power to make decisions regarding their future.\n\n==Handover ceremony==\n{{Main|Hong Kong handover ceremony}}\nThe handover ceremony was held at the new wing of the [[Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre]] in [[Wan Chai]] on the night of 30 June 1997.\n\nThe principal British guest was [[Prince Charles]], who read a farewell speech on behalf of the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]]. The newly elected [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Prime Minister, [[Tony Blair]], the [[Foreign Secretary of the United Kingdom|Foreign Secretary]] [[Robin Cook]], the departing [[Governor of Hong Kong|Governor]] [[Chris Patten]] and [[Charles Guthrie, Baron Guthrie of Craigiebank|General Sir Charles Guthrie]], [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]], also attended.\n\nRepresenting the People's Republic of China were the President, [[Jiang Zemin]], the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]], [[Li Peng]], and the first chief executive [[Tung Chee-hwa]]. The event was broadcast around the world.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=YeiaOWcc17MC&lpg=PA395&ots=eEfHvoBqVr&dq=hong%20kong%20handover%201997%20cnn%20coverage&pg=PA395#v=onepage&q=hong%20kong%20handover%201997%20cnn%20coverage&f=true ''China Live: People Power and the Television Revolution''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222094506/https://books.google.com/books?id=YeiaOWcc17MC&lpg=PA395&ots=eEfHvoBqVr&dq=hong%20kong%20handover%201997%20cnn%20coverage&pg=PA395#v=onepage&q=hong%20kong%20handover%201997%20cnn%20coverage&f=true |date=22 December 2016 }}, Mike Chinoy, Rowman & Littlefield, 1999, page 395</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/bbc_parliament/6241974.stm Hong Kong Night \u2013 Sunday 1 July] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819202535/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/bbc_parliament/6241974.stm |date=19 August 2007 }}, [[BBC News]], 27 June 2007</ref>\n\n==Additional effects==\n\n===Before and after handover===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"clear:both; width:100%;\"\n! width=50% | Unchanged after 30 June 1997\n! width=50% | Changed after 30 June 1997\n|-valign=top\n|\n#English continued as an official language and is still taught in all schools. However, many schools teach in [[Cantonese]] in parallel with [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]] and English.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GbF8AgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA198&dq=However%2C%20many%20schools%20teach%20in%20Cantonese%20in%20parallel%20with%20Mandarin%20and%20English.&pg=PA198#v=onepage&q=However,%20many%20schools%20teach%20in%20Cantonese%20in%20parallel%20with%20Mandarin%20and%20English.&f=true Education and colonial transition in Singapore and Hong Kong: Comparisons and contrasts] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104051/https://books.google.com/books?id=GbF8AgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA198&dq=However%2C%20many%20schools%20teach%20in%20Cantonese%20in%20parallel%20with%20Mandarin%20and%20English.&pg=PA198#v=onepage&q=However,%20many%20schools%20teach%20in%20Cantonese%20in%20parallel%20with%20Mandarin%20and%20English.&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Jason Tan in '' Changing Educational Contexts, Issues and Identities: 40 Years of Comparative Education'', Michael Crossley, Patricia Broadfoot, Michele Schweisfurth, Routledge, 2007, page 198</ref>\n#The border with the mainland, while now known as the boundary, continued to be patrolled as before, with separate immigration and customs controls.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200301/08/0108224.htm Lok Ma Chau Control Point to provide 24-hour passenger clearance services] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051045/http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200301/08/0108224.htm |date=4 March 2016 }}, [[Government of Hong Kong|Government Information Centre]], 8 January 2003</ref>\n#Hong Kong citizens were still required to apply for a [[Mainland Travel Permit for Hong Kong and Macao Residents|Mainland Travel Permit]], in order to visit mainland China.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201202/15/P201202150334.htm LCQ1: Immigration clearance and entry visas to the Mainland for non-Chinese Hong Kong permanent residents with foreign passports] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109234739/http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201202/15/P201202150334.htm |date=9 January 2015 }}, [[Government of Hong Kong|Government Information Centre]], 15 February 2012</ref> \n#Citizens of mainland China still did not have the [[right of abode]] in Hong Kong.<ref>[http://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/services/roa/geninfor.html General Information on the Right of Abode in Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325022735/http://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/services/roa/geninfor.html |date=25 March 2016 }}, [[Hong Kong Immigration Department|Immigration Department]]</ref> Instead, they had to apply for a permit to [[Two-way Permit|visit]] or [[One-way Permit|settle]] in Hong Kong from the PRC government.<ref>[http://www.fmcoprc.gov.hk/eng/fwxx/wgrqz/t1055657.htm Exit and Entry Administration Law of the People's Republic of China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331061809/http://www.fmcoprc.gov.hk/eng/fwxx/wgrqz/t1055657.htm |date=31 March 2016 }}, [[Office of the Commissioner of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region]]</ref> \n#Hong Kong remained a [[common law jurisdiction]], with a separate legal system from that [[Law of the People's Republic of China|used in the mainland]], with previous laws remaining in force provided that they did not conflict with the [[Basic Law of Hong Kong|Basic Law]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PknF6cR7lQMC&lpg=PA245&ots=nnGw3418k-&dq=Hong%20Kong%20remained%20a%20common%20law%20jurisdiction%2C&pg=PA245#v=onepage&q=Hong%20Kong%20remained%20a%20common%20law%20jurisdiction,&f=true ''China Briefing's Business Guide to the Greater Pearl River Delta''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222111618/https://books.google.com/books?id=PknF6cR7lQMC&lpg=PA245&ots=nnGw3418k-&dq=Hong%20Kong%20remained%20a%20common%20law%20jurisdiction%2C&pg=PA245#v=onepage&q=Hong%20Kong%20remained%20a%20common%20law%20jurisdiction,&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, China Briefing Media, Ltd., 2004, page 245</ref>\n#The [[Hong Kong dollar]] continued to be used as its sole currency, and the responsibility of the [[Hong Kong Monetary Authority]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hkma.gov.hk/eng/index.shtml |title=Hong Kong Monetary Authority |access-date=30 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329231845/http://www.hkma.gov.hk/eng/index.shtml |archive-date=29 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The [[Bank of China (Hong Kong)|Bank of China]] had already started issuing banknotes in 1994.<ref>[http://www.boc.cn/en/aboutboc/ab7/200809/t20080926_1601846.html Bank of China Authorized to Issue HKD and MOP (1987\u20131992)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411141108/http://www.boc.cn/en/aboutboc/ab7/200809/t20080926_1601846.html |date=11 April 2016 }}, [[Bank of China]]</ref>\n#Hong Kong continued to operate as a separate customs territory from mainland China under Article 116 of the Basic Law.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200009/30/0929290.htm Hong Kong operates as a separate Customs territory] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040908113214/http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200009/30/0929290.htm |date=8 September 2004 }}, [[Government of Hong Kong|Government Information Centre]], 30 September 2000</ref>\n#Hong Kong remained an individual member of various international organisations, such as the [[World Trade Organization]] and [[APEC]].<ref>[https://www.wto.org/english/news_e/spmm_e/spmm03_e.htm Address Via Video-Conference \u2013 A challenge to APEC business] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912164957/http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/spmm_e/spmm03_e.htm |date=12 September 2014 }}, Address given by Rt Hon Mike Moore, Director-General, World Trade Organization, 12 September 1999</ref>\n#Hong Kong, which remained an individual member of the [[International Olympic Committee]], continued to send its own team to international sporting events such as the Olympics.<ref name=\"Olympic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.olympic.org/hong-kong-china |title=Sports Federation and Olympic Committee of Hong Kong China |access-date=27 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316171825/http://www.olympic.org/hong-kong-china |archive-date=16 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#Hong Kong maintained [[Hong Kong Economic and Trade Office]]s overseas, as well as in the Greater China Region. These include the offices in London, Washington D.C., [[Brussels]] and [[Geneva]], previously known as Hong Kong Government Offices.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr82-83/english/lc_sitg/hansard/h821111.pdf |title=Official report of proceedings, 11 November 1982, Legislative Council |access-date=27 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220507/http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr82-83/english/lc_sitg/hansard/h821111.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#Many countries' [[Consular missions in Hong Kong|consulates-general]] in Hong Kong remained outside the jurisdiction of their embassies in Beijing, such as the United States [[Consulate General of the United States, Hong Kong|Consulate General]], which reports directly to the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ait.org.tw/en/pressrelease-pr1224.html |title=Christopher J. Marut Appointed as Director of the Taipei Office of the American Institute in Taiwan |access-date=24 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002648/http://www.ait.org.tw/en/pressrelease-pr1224.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#The Chung Hwa Travel Service, which functioned as [[Taiwan]]'s [[de facto embassy|''de facto'' mission]] in Hong Kong, continued to function as before, issuing visas to visitors from Hong Kong, mainland China and other countries.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9X9QXYXGdJwC&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=chung+hwa+travel+service+hong+kong&source=bl&ots=t6fQurzJdF&sig=DTWZY5m5tTuyzK7hiJ5pjUxU5g8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi97p-_7uDLAhXBaRQKHblCC9UQ6AEIUTAJ#v=onepage&q=chung%20hwa%20travel%20service%20hong%20kong&f=true ''The First Decade: The Hong Kong SAR in Retrospective and Introspective Perspectives''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222103202/https://books.google.com/books?id=9X9QXYXGdJwC&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=chung+hwa+travel+service+hong+kong&source=bl&ots=t6fQurzJdF&sig=DTWZY5m5tTuyzK7hiJ5pjUxU5g8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi97p-_7uDLAhXBaRQKHblCC9UQ6AEIUTAJ#v=onepage&q=chung%20hwa%20travel%20service%20hong%20kong&f=true |date=22 December 2016 }}, Yue-man Yeung, Chinese University Press, 2007, page 87</ref> In 2011 it was renamed the [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Hong Kong]].<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2011/07/17/2003508415 Is name change a game changer?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222005/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2011/07/17/2003508415 |date=3 March 2016 }}, ''[[Taipei Times]]'', 17 July 2011</ref>     \n#Hong Kong continued to negotiate and maintain its own aviation bilateral treaties with foreign countries and territories.<ref>[http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/laws/table1ti.html List of Air Services Agreements and Air Services Transit Agreements] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411054743/http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/laws/table1ti.html |date=11 April 2016 }}, [[Department of Justice (Hong Kong)|Department of Justice]]</ref> Agreements with [[Taiwan]] signed in 1996 remained in force after the change of sovereignty, and were replaced by \"the air transportation agreement between Taiwan and Hong Kong\", which retained international regulations, such as regulations on customs.<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2002/07/01/0000146568 New air accord a result of compromise, analysts say] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409020634/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2002/07/01/0000146568 |date=9 April 2016 }}, ''[[Taipei Times]]'', 1 July 2002</ref> \n#Signs (and fonts), labels, and roadway construction standards on Hong Kong roads and expressways continue to follow the [[Transport in the European Union|European Union roadway standards]], particularly those of the UK.<ref>[http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/car-news/89974/celebrating-50-years-of-uk-road-signs Celebrating 50 years of UK road signs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706041738/http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/car-news/89974/celebrating-50-years-of-uk-road-signs |date=6 July 2016 }}, ''[[Auto Express]]'', 8 January 2015</ref>\n#Hong Kong continued to [[Left- and right-hand traffic|drive on the left]], unlike Mainland China, which drives on the right.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PgJTSYeEnNkC&lpg=PA279&dq=hong%20kong%20%22drive%20on%20the%20left%22&pg=PA279#v=onepage&q=hong%20kong%20%22drive%20on%20the%20left%22&f=false ''Hong Kong & Macau''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104114/https://books.google.com/books?id=PgJTSYeEnNkC&lpg=PA279&dq=hong%20kong%20%22drive%20on%20the%20left%22&pg=PA279#v=onepage&q=hong%20kong%20%22drive%20on%20the%20left%22&f=false |date=22 February 2017 }}, Andrew Stone, Chung Wah Chow, Reggie Ho,\n[[Lonely Planet]], 2008, page 278</ref> [[Vehicle registration plates of Hong Kong|Vehicle registration plates]] continued to be modelled on [[Vehicle registration plates of the United Kingdom|those of the United Kingdom]], white on the front and yellow on the back, with the vehicle registration mark in a similar font.<ref>[http://hub.hku.hk/bitstream/10722/46157/1/50044.pdf?accept=1 Recognition of vehicle registration mark on moving vehicles in an outdoor environment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412233817/http://hub.hku.hk/bitstream/10722/46157/1/50044.pdf?accept=1 |date=12 April 2016 }}, N. H. C. Yung*, K. H. Au & A. H. S. Lai, Laboratory for Intelligent Transportation Systems Research, [[University of Hong Kong]], IEEE Conference on Intelligent Transportation Systems, Proceedings, Itsc, 1999, p. 418-422</ref>\n#Hong Kong-registered vehicles still required special [[Vehicle registration plates of China#Cross-border with Hong Kong and Macau|cross-border]] plates to travel to and from mainland China, similar to those of [[Guangdong]].<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/article/1105206/cross-border-licence-plates-go-1-million-yuan-black-market Cross-border licence plates go for a million yuan on black market] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503102917/http://www.scmp.com/article/1105206/cross-border-licence-plates-go-1-million-yuan-black-market |date=3 May 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 14 December 2012</ref> Vehicles registered in the mainland can enter Hong Kong under the [[Hong Kong mainland China driving scheme]].<ref name=\"scmp1\">[http://topics.scmp.com/news/hk-news-watch/article/New-entry-plan-for-mainland-cars New entry plan for mainland cars] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223095104/http://topics.scmp.com/news/hk-news-watch/article/New-entry-plan-for-mainland-cars |date=23 February 2012 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 9 February 2012.</ref>\n#Hong Kong citizens continued to have easier access to many countries, including those in Europe and North America, with Hong Kong SAR passport holders having visa-free access to 154 other countries and territories.<ref>[http://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/service/travel_document/visa_free_access.html  Visa-free access for HKSAR Passport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331011103/http://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/service/travel_document/visa_free_access.html |date=31 March 2016 }}, [[Hong Kong Immigration Department]]</ref> \n#Many former colonial citizens could still use [[British National (Overseas)]] and [[British citizen]] passports after 1997. (''Main article: [[British nationality law and Hong Kong]]'')\n#It continued to have more political freedoms than [[mainland China]], with the holding of demonstrations and the [[Memorials for the Tiananmen Square protests of 1989#Hong Kong|annual memorial]] to commemorate the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]] continuing to be held in [[Victoria Park, Hong Kong|Victoria Park]].<ref>[http://time.com/3908678/tiananmen-massacre-26th-anniversary-hong-kong-china-vigil-victoria-park/ Tens of Thousands Gather in Hong Kong to Remember the 1989 Tiananmen Massacre] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419102504/http://time.com/3908678/tiananmen-massacre-26th-anniversary-hong-kong-china-vigil-victoria-park/ |date=19 April 2016 }}, ''[[Time Magazine]]'', 4 June 2015</ref>   \n#It continued to have a [[List of political parties in Hong Kong|multi-party]] political system.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=af_IAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA135&ots=nyGolV20hz&dq=Political%20parties%20of%20Hong%20Kong&pg=PA135#v=onepage&q=Political%20parties%20of%20Hong%20Kong&f=true ''Political Development in Hong Kong: State, Political Society, and Civil Society''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222224332/https://books.google.com/books?id=af_IAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA135&ots=nyGolV20hz&dq=Political%20parties%20of%20Hong%20Kong&pg=PA135#v=onepage&q=Political%20parties%20of%20Hong%20Kong&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Ngok Ma, Hong Kong University Press, 2007, page 135</ref> This is separate from the [[Chinese Communist Party|Communist]]-led [[United Front (People's Republic of China)|United Front]] on the mainland.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1864432/united-front-chief-sun-chunlan-tells-young-hongkongers-love United Front chief Sun Chunlan tells young Hongkongers to love their country and make the most of close ties with China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624035646/http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1864432/united-front-chief-sun-chunlan-tells-young-hongkongers-love |date=24 June 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 6 October 2015</ref> \n#It continued to have more [[freedom of the press]] than mainland China, under Article 27 of the Basic Law, despite the growing influence of Beijing.<ref>[https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2015/hong-kong Hong Kong * | Country report | Freedom of the Press | 2015] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328194946/https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2015/hong-kong |date=28 March 2016 }}, [[Freedom House]]</ref>\n#It also continued to have more religious freedoms, with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Hong Kong]] remaining under the jurisdiction of the [[Holy See]], instead of the [[Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association]] on the mainland.<ref>[http://en.radiovaticana.va/news/2016/01/16/pope_appoints_hong_kong_bishop_to_macau_%E2%80%8E/1201599 Pope appoints Hong Kong bishop to Macau] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420112918/http://en.radiovaticana.va/news/2016/01/16/pope_appoints_hong_kong_bishop_to_macau_%E2%80%8E/1201599 |date=20 April 2016 }}, ''[[Vatican Radio]]'', 16 January 2016</ref> The [[Falun Gong]] spiritual practice also remained legal in Hong Kong, despite encountering opposition from the SAR government.<ref name=dangerous>{{Cite book |first=Mickey |last=Spiegel |url=https://archive.org/details/fromhouseholdtof00huma |title=Dangerous Meditation: China's Campaign Against Falungong |publisher=Human Rights Watch |year=2002 |accessdate=28 September 2007 |isbn=1-56432-269-6 }}</ref>\n#Many other technical standards from the United Kingdom, such as [[Electrical wiring in Hong Kong|electrical plugs]] ([[BS 1363]]) are still used in Hong Kong.<ref>[http://www.frommers.com/destinations/china/702082 Fast Facts in China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409031813/http://www.frommers.com/destinations/china/702082 |date=9 April 2016 }}, ''[[Frommer's]]''</ref> However, telephone companies changed from installing [[British Standard|UK-style]] [[BS 6312]] telephone sockets to installing [[Registered jack|US-style]] [[Modular connector#6P2C|RJ11]] ones.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120211132642/http://www.ofta.gov.hk/en/consumer_interest/rj_system/index.html The RJ System of telephone plugs and sockets is gradually replacing the BT System in Hong Kong], [[Office of the Telecommunications Authority]] (OFTA), Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government</ref> Hong Kong also adopted the [[Digital Terrestrial Multimedia Broadcast|digital TV standard]] devised in mainland China for [[Television in Hong Kong|TV transmissions]], instead of [[DVB-T]], to replace [[PAL]]-I.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-KY9AQAAIAAJ&dq=DTMB+TdM+Macau&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=DTMB+ ''World Radio TV Handbook''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222170808/https://books.google.com/books?id=-KY9AQAAIAAJ&dq=DTMB+TdM+Macau&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=DTMB+ |date=22 February 2017 }}, WRTH Publications Ltd, 2008, page 642</ref> (''Main article: [[Technical standards in colonial Hong Kong]]'')\n#Hong Kong retained a separate [[country calling code|international dialling code]] (852) and [[Hong Kong telephone numbering plan|telephone numbering plan]] from that of the [[China telephone numbering plan|mainland]].<ref>[https://www.itu.int/oth/T0202000060/en Hong Kong, China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304064001/http://www.itu.int/oth/T0202000060/en |date=4 March 2016 }}, [[International Telecommunication Union]], 19 February 2013</ref> Calls between Hong Kong and the mainland still required international dialling.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GpqzAAAAIAAJ&q=%2200852%22+hong+kong+-ibp&dq=%2200852%22+hong+kong+-ibp&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi0r9rt0uDLAhVMchQKHfEiDUAQ6AEILzAE ''China International Business: The Monthly Publication of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, P.R.C''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104139/https://books.google.com/books?id=GpqzAAAAIAAJ&q=%2200852%22+hong+kong+-ibp&dq=%2200852%22+hong+kong+-ibp&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi0r9rt0uDLAhVMchQKHfEiDUAQ6AEILzAE |date=22 February 2017 }}, Issues 7\u201312, Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, 2002</ref> \n#Hong Kong retained a separate [[ISO 3166]] code, [[ISO 3166-2:HK|HK]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:HK |title=ISO Online Browsing Platform: HK |access-date=29 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617031837/https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:HK |archive-date=17 June 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> It also retained a [[Country code top-level domain|top-level domain]], [[.hk]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hkirc.hk/ |title=Hong Kong Internet Registration Corporation |access-date=29 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321090104/https://www.hkirc.hk/ |archive-date=21 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, the [[ISO 3166-2:CN|Chinese code]] CN-91 was also used.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:CN |title=ISO Online Browsing Platform: CN |access-date=29 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617031837/https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:CN |archive-date=17 June 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#Hong Kong retained its own separate [[postal service]]s, with [[Hongkong Post]] operating separately from [[China Post]]. Hong Kong was not made part of the [[List of postal codes in China|Chinese postcode system]], nor did it introduce a postcode system of its own.<ref>[http://www.upu.int/fileadmin/documentsFiles/activities/addressingUnit/hkgEn.pdf Hongkong, China], [[Universal Postal Union]]</ref>\n#The Hong Kong government continued to make a subvention to the [[English Schools Foundation]], responsible for English-medium schools, which would not be phased out until 2016.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/families/article/1359426/esfs-new-chief-executive-belinda-greer-looks-boost-efficiency ESF's new chief executive Belinda Greer looks to boost efficiency], ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 19 November 2013</ref>  \n#The former British military drill, marching and words of command in English continued in all disciplinary services including all civil organisations.<ref>[http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/11_useful_info/aux_police/training.html Training] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316201245/http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/11_useful_info/aux_police/training.html |date=16 March 2016 }}, Hong Kong Police Force</ref> The [[People's Liberation Army|PLA]] soldiers of the [[People's Liberation Army Hong Kong Garrison|Chinese Garrison in Hong Kong]] have their own drills and Mandarin words of command.\n#Statues of British monarchs remained. [[Queen Victoria]]'s statue remains in [[Victoria Park, Hong Kong|Victoria Park]].<ref>[http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/vp/index.html Victoria Park] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321182929/http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/vp/index.html |date=21 March 2016 }}, [[Leisure and Cultural Services Department]]</ref> [[King George VI]]'s statue similarly remained in [[Hong Kong Zoological and Botanical Gardens]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/hkzbg/ |title=Hong Kong Zoological and Botanical Gardens |access-date=31 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330204811/http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/hkzbg/ |archive-date=30 March 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#British-inspired road names remain unchanged.<ref name=\"SCMP1994\" />\n||\n#From 2012, secondary education moved away from the English model of five years secondary schooling plus two years of university matriculation to the Chinese model of three years of junior secondary plus another three years of senior secondary, while university education was extended from three years to four.<ref>[https://universitydesign.asu.edu/db/hong-kong-undergraduate-education-reform-under-201c3-3-4201d Hong Kong Undergraduate Education Reform Under \"3+3+4\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408045313/https://universitydesign.asu.edu/db/hong-kong-undergraduate-education-reform-under-201c3-3-4201d |date=8 April 2016 }}, University Design Consortium, [[Arizona State University]]</ref>\n#The [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|chief executive]] became the [[head of government]], [[Elections in Hong Kong|elected]] by a [[Selection Committee]], whose members were mainly elected from among professional sectors and business leaders.<ref>[http://www.basiclaw.gov.hk/en/basiclawtext/annex_1.html Annex I : Method for the Selection of the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408201047/http://www.basiclaw.gov.hk/en/basiclawtext/annex_1.html |date=8 April 2016 }}, [[Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]]</ref> The [[Governor of Hong Kong|Governor]] was appointed by the United Kingdom.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/politics97/hk/patten.shtml Chris Patten \u2013 Governor of Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402130913/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/politics97/hk/patten.shtml |date=2 April 2018 }}, [[BBC]], Politics 97</ref>\n#The [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]], [[1995 Hong Kong legislative election|elected in 1995]], was dissolved and replaced by a [[Provisional Legislative Council]], before elections were held to a new Council, in which only 20 out of 60 seats were directly elected.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elections.gov.hk/elections/legco1998/524-e.htm#gc524-e |title=Results of the 1998 Legislative Council Election |access-date=15 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231311/http://www.elections.gov.hk/elections/legco1998/524-e.htm#gc524-e |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The decision to dissolve the Legislative Council and replace it with a Provisional Legislative Council was criticised by representatives of the UK government.<ref>An interview with the former British Prime Minister Thatcher just before Britain's handover of Hong Kong back to China on 1 July 1997; Reporter/Producer: Susan Yu; Published on 1 July 1997 and viewable on YouTube.</ref>\n#Foreign nationals were not allowed to stand for directly elected seats in the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]], only for [[Functional constituency (Hong Kong)|indirectly elected]] seats.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/lau-in-passport-battle-1289087.html Lau in passport battle] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427221230/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/lau-in-passport-battle-1289087.html |date=27 April 2016 }}, ''[[The Independent]]'', 16 December 1997</ref>  \n#All public office buildings now flew the flags of the [[Flag of the People's Republic of China|PRC]] and the [[flag of Hong Kong|Hong Kong SAR]]. The [[Union Flag]] now flew only outside the [[British Consulate-General, Hong Kong|British Consulate-General]] and other British premises.\n#The British national anthem ''[[God Save the Queen]]'', was no longer played after closedown on [[Television in Hong Kong|television stations]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cV3QdfNOewk God Save the Queen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316195259/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cV3QdfNOewk |date=16 March 2014 }}, [[TVB Pearl]], 1987</ref> The Chinese national anthem, ''[[March of the Volunteers]]'' was now played instead.<ref>Vickers, Edward. [https://books.google.com/books?id=QwXgYeQRVHsC&pg=PA94#v=onepage&q=anthem&f=false \"Learning to Love the Motherland: 'National Education' in Post-Retrocession Hong Kong\" in ''Designing History in East Asian Textbooks: Identity Politics and Transnational Aspirations'', p.&nbsp;94] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104503/https://books.google.com/books?id=QwXgYeQRVHsC&pg=PA94#v=onepage&q=anthem&f=false |date=22 February 2017 }}. Routledge (Abingdon), 2011. {{ISBN|9780415602525}}.</ref> \n#At international sporting events such as the Olympics, Hong Kong was now known as [[Hong Kong at the Olympics|Hong Kong, China]].<ref name=\"Olympic\" /> Hong Kong athletes and teams compete under the Hong Kong SAR flag instead of the British flag of Hong Kong, and gold medallists were honoured with the Chinese national anthem, instead of the British national anthem.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-34918397 Fifa investigates Hong Kong over China match booing] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216001611/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-34918397 |date=16 February 2018 }}, [[BBC News]], 25 November 2015</ref>\n#The [[Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal|Court of Final Appeal]] replaced the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] as the highest court of appeal.<ref>[http://www.hkcfa.hk/en/about/overview/index.html A Brief Overview of the Court of Final Appeal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230185237/http://www.hkcfa.hk/en/about/overview/index.html |date=30 December 2015 }}, [[Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal]]</ref>\n#The [[Supreme Court (Hong Kong)|Supreme Court]] was replaced by the [[High Court (Hong Kong)|High Court]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4LAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA227&ots=0FlQLxX7k4&dq=high%20court%20hong%20kong%20supreme%20court&pg=PA227#v=onepage&q=high%20court%20hong%20kong%20supreme%20court&f=true ''Hong Kong's Court of Final Appeal: The Development of the Law in China's Hong Kong''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222094349/https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4LAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA227&ots=0FlQLxX7k4&dq=high%20court%20hong%20kong%20supreme%20court&pg=PA227#v=onepage&q=high%20court%20hong%20kong%20supreme%20court&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, Simon N. M. Young, Yash Ghai\nCambridge University Press, 2013, page 227</ref>\n#The [[Secretary for Justice (Hong Kong)#Attorneys General before 1997|Attorney General]] was replaced by the [[Secretary for Justice (Hong Kong)|Secretary for Justice]].<ref>[http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/about/soj.html Secretary for Justice, Mr Rimsky Yuen, SC, JP] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412145253/http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/about/soj.html |date=12 April 2016 }}, [[Department of Justice (Hong Kong)|Department of Justice]]</ref>\n#The [[Central People's Government]] was now formally represented in Hong Kong by a [[Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region|Liaison Office]], dealing with domestic matters.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/20/world/in-watching-hong-kong-china-loses-the-shades.html In Watching Hong Kong, China Loses The Shades] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160817/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/20/world/in-watching-hong-kong-china-loses-the-shades.html |date=24 July 2016 }}, ''[[New York Times]]'', 20 February 2000</ref> This had been established under British rule as the [[Xinhua News Agency#Xinhua in Hong Kong|Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch]], before it adopted its present name in 2000.<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/insight/archives/2000/01/21/0000020843 Renamed Xinhua becomes a new force in Hong Kong's politics] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819145347/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/insight/archives/2000/01/21/0000020843 |date=19 August 2017 }}, ''[[Taipei Times]]'', 21 January 2000</ref> \n#The Hong Kong SAR Government was now formally represented in Beijing by the [[Office of the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region in Beijing|Office of the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bjo.gov.hk/en/home/index.html |title=Welcome Message Office of the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) of the People's Republic of China in Beijing |access-date=1 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416173624/http://www.bjo.gov.hk/en/home/index.html |archive-date=16 April 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n#The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China]] was represented in Hong Kong by a [[Office of the Commissioner of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region|Commissioner]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070821153208/http://big5.fmprc.gov.cn/gate/big5/www.fmcoprc.gov.hk/eng/ Office of the Commissioner of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region]</ref>\n#The [[People's Liberation Army]] established a [[People's Liberation Army Hong Kong Garrison|Garrison]], taking over responsibility for defence from [[British Forces Overseas Hong Kong]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/hong-kong-forces-withdrawal-outlined-1485942.html Hong Kong forces withdrawal outlined] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410065018/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/hong-kong-forces-withdrawal-outlined-1485942.html |date=10 April 2016 }}, ''[[The Independent]]'', 19 July 1993</ref> The Prince of Wales Building was renamed the [[Chinese People's Liberation Army Forces Hong Kong Building]], while the Prince of Wales Barracks was similarly renamed the Central Barracks, with effect from January 2002.<ref>[http://en.people.cn/200112/30/eng20011230_87779.shtml PLA Hong Kong Garrison Head Office to Use New Name] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030627/http://en.people.cn/200112/30/eng20011230_87779.shtml |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''[[People's Daily]]'', 31 December 2001</ref>\n#Flags were no longer flown at the [[The Cenotaph (Hong Kong)|Cenotaph]] to remember the war dead; previously British troops raised flags representing the [[British Army]], [[Royal Navy]] and [[Royal Air Force]] every morning, lowering them again before sunset.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/article/204622/confusion-over-flags-leaves-cenotaph-bare Confusion over flags leaves Cenotaph bare], ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 21 July 1997</ref> \n#[[Government House, Hong Kong|Government House]] was not used as the residence of the first chief executive, [[Tung Chee-hwa]].<ref name=\"Slow but Sure\" /> However, his successor, [[Donald Tsang]], moved into the compound in 2006.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200601/12/P200601110210.htm CE moves into Government House today] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200906/http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200601/12/P200601110210.htm |date=3 March 2016 }}, [[Government of Hong Kong]], 12 January 2006</ref>   \n#[[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]]'s portrait was removed from public offices.<ref name=\"Battle Royal\" /> Coins issued since 1993 no longer had the Queen's head, instead having the [[Bauhinia \u00d7 blakeana#Usage as an emblem|Bauhinia]].<ref>[http://www.hkma.gov.hk/eng/publications-and-research/reference-materials/viewpoint/19991118.shtml Viewpoint: Bauhinia Coins] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031116/http://www.hkma.gov.hk/eng/publications-and-research/reference-materials/viewpoint/19991118.shtml |date=4 March 2016 }}, [[Hong Kong Monetary Authority]], 18 November 1999</ref>\n#Postage stamps now displayed the words \"Hong Kong, China\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QCAfAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22definitive+stamps%22+hong+kong+1997&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22definitive+stamps+issued%22+ ''Hong Kong''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222102958/https://books.google.com/books?id=QCAfAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22definitive+stamps%22+hong+kong+1997&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22definitive+stamps+issued%22+ |date=22 December 2016 }}, Government Press, 1999, page 354</ref> A set of definitive stamps, bearing the words \"Hong Kong\" with no connotation of sovereignty, was introduced in January 1997.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=8gNEAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22definitive+stamps%22+hong+kong+1997&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22+no+connotation+of+sovereignty%22 ''Hongkong Post Annual Report''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222111131/https://books.google.com/books?id=8gNEAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22definitive+stamps%22+hong+kong+1997&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22+no+connotation+of+sovereignty%22 |date=22 December 2016 }}, Hongkong Post, Government Press, 1996, page 30</ref> \n#The \"[[Royal Charter|Royal]]\" title was dropped from almost all [[Royal Charter#Hong Kong|organisations that had been granted it]], with the exception of the [[Royal Hong Kong Yacht Club]].<ref name=\"Battle Royal\">[http://www.csmonitor.com/1996/0610/061096.intl.intl.2.html A Battle Royal Rocks Imperial Yacht Club] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408180839/http://www.csmonitor.com/1996/0610/061096.intl.intl.2.html |date=8 April 2016 }}, ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', 10 June 1996</ref>\n#The [[St Edward's Crown|Crown]] was removed from the crest of the [[Hong Kong Police Force]], and replaced by the [[Bauhinia \u00d7 blakeana#Usage as an emblem|Bauhinia]].<ref name=\"Battle Royal\" />\n#Legal references to the \"[[The Crown|Crown]]\" were replaced by references to the \"State\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5ZtTFZBUG_oC&pg=PA39&lpg=PA39&dq=hong+kong+crown+state&source=bl&ots=yVx-PcG9vM&sig=CEfShX7Ja3O1YcyHYUDTaLYdG48&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjRzoSdwN3LAhWJuxQKHfUHDoUQ6AEIYzAO#v=onepage&q=hong%20kong%20crown%20state&f=false Continuity and Change in the Legal System], ''The Other Hong Kong Report 1998'', edited by Larry Chuen-ho Chow, Yiu-Kwan Fan, Chinese University Press, 1998, page 39</ref> [[Barrister]]s who had been appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] would now be known as [[Senior Counsel]].<ref>[http://hkba.org/the-bar/aboutus/index.html About Us] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305101411/http://www.hkba.org/the-bar/aboutus/index.html |date=5 March 2016 }}, [[Hong Kong Bar Association]]</ref>\n#The [[British honours system]] was replaced by a local system, in which the [[Grand Bauhinia Medal]] was the highest award.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jfpWAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22grand+bauhinia+medal%22+history+established&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22grand+bauhinia+medal%22++ Xinhua News Agency] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222115425/https://books.google.com/books?id=jfpWAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22grand+bauhinia+medal%22+history+established&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22grand+bauhinia+medal%22++ |date=22 December 2016 }}, 3 July 1997</ref>\n#[[Public holidays in Hong Kong|Public holidays]] changed, with British-inspired occasions, such as the [[Queen's Birthday|Queen's Official Birthday]], [[Victory over Japan Day#Hong Kong|Liberation Day]], and [[Remembrance Day]] being replaced by [[PRC National Day]] and [[Hong Kong SAR Establishment Day]].<ref name=\"SCMP1994\">[http://www.scmp.com/article/88137/17-holidays-stay-after-1997 17 holidays to stay after 1997] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503213839/http://www.scmp.com/article/88137/17-holidays-stay-after-1997 |date=3 May 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 12 September 1994</ref> [[Double Ten Day]], commemorating the establishment of the [[Republic of China (1912-49)|Republic of China]], was abolished as a public holiday in 1950.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4lJOAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22republic+of+china%22+%22national+day%22+hong+kong+%22public+holiday%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22cancellation+of+the+public+holiday%22 ''Far Eastern Economic Review''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222104059/https://books.google.com/books?id=4lJOAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22republic+of+china%22+%22national+day%22+hong+kong+%22public+holiday%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22cancellation+of+the+public+holiday%22 |date=22 February 2017 }}, 1968, page 450</ref>\n#Many of the red [[Royal Mail]] [[pillar box]]es were removed from the streets of Hong Kong and replaced by green [[Hongkong Post]] boxes.<ref name=\"Slow but Sure\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/09/world/change-in-hong-kong-is-slow-but-sure.html?pagewanted=all Change in Hong Kong Is Slow but Sure] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160822/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/09/world/change-in-hong-kong-is-slow-but-sure.html?pagewanted=all |date=24 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 9 October 1997</ref> All others were re-painted.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/07/hong-kong-to-cover-british-insignia-on-postboxes-to-avoid-confusion Hong Kong to cover British insignia on postboxes to 'avoid confusion'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215070035/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/07/hong-kong-to-cover-british-insignia-on-postboxes-to-avoid-confusion |date=15 December 2016 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 7 October 2015</ref>\n#British citizens (without right of abode in Hong Kong) were no longer able to work in Hong Kong without a visa; the policy was changed on 1 April 1997.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160826184845/http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/97/0411/nat3.html Warning: Deadline Ahead], ''[[Asiaweek]]'', 11 April 1997</ref><ref name=\"Offshore Investment\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20161221002053/http://www.offshoreinvestment.com/media/uploads/Hong%20Kong%20after%20the%20change%20of%20sovereignty.pdf Hong Kong after the change of sovereignty], Jane McNair and Professor Peter Willoughby,\nDeacons Graham & James, Hong Kong SAR, ''Offshore Investment'', January 1999, issue 92</ref>\n#The United Kingdom was now represented by the [[British Consulate-General, Hong Kong|British Consulate-General]], which reports directly to the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmfaff/649/64907.htm The UK's relations with Hong Kong: 30 years after the Joint Declaration] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525090559/https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmfaff/649/64907.htm |date=25 May 2017 }}, Tenth Report of Session 2014\u201315, [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]], [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], 6 March 2015, page 16 [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmfaff/649/649.pdf PDF] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719113821/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmfaff/649/649.pdf |date=19 July 2018 }}</ref> This has responsibility for British citizens, instead of the [[Hong Kong Immigration Department]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=veEZBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA167&dq=hong%20kong%20%22immigration%20department%22%20british&pg=PA167#v=onepage&q=%22immigration%20department%22%20british&f=false ''Hong Kong's New Constitutional Order: The Resumption of Chinese Sovereignty and the Basic Law''], Yash Ghai, Hong Kong University Press, 1997, page 167</ref> Previously, the country's commercial interests were represented by a British Trade Commission.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QhVWl7-NcY8C&lpg=PA417&ots=SnpcsYyo9K&dq=british%20%22senior%20trade%20commissioner%22%20to%20Hong%20Kong&pg=PA417#v=onepage&q=british%20%22senior%20trade%20commissioner%22%20to%20Hong%20Kong&f=false ''Hunting with the Tigers: Doing Business with Hong Kong, Indonesia, South Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Taiwan, Thailand, and Vietnam''], Claudia Cragg, Pfeiffer & Company, 1993, page 417</ref> It was headed by a Senior Trade Commissioner, who became the first Consul-General.<ref>[http://www.info.gov.hk/isd/news/oct97/1022pm.htm Chief Executive holds 'useful, cordial' talks with British Prime Minister] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613122434/http://www.info.gov.hk/isd/news/oct97/1022pm.htm |date=13 June 2018 }}, Government of Hong Kong, 22 October 1997</ref>\n#Hong Kong was no longer linked to the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] and no longer participated in related [[Commonwealth Family|organisations or events]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecgf.com/countries/intro.asp?loc=HKG# |title=Commonwealth Games Federation \u2013 Hong Kong |access-date=24 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819125702/http://www.thecgf.com/countries/intro.asp?loc=HKG |archive-date=19 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Consular missions in Hong Kong|Consular missions]] of Commonwealth member states in Hong Kong were no longer known as Commissions, but as Consulates-General.<ref>[http://www.mfa.gov.sg/content/mfa/overseasmission/hong_kong/about_the_consulate_general.html About the Consulate-General] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029161528/http://www.mfa.gov.sg/content/mfa/overseasmission/hong_kong/about_the_consulate_general.html |date=29 October 2015 }}, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Singapore)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]], Singapore</ref>\n#Countries which did not have diplomatic relations with the United Kingdom, but had diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of China, such as [[North Korea]] and [[Iran]], were allowed to establish or re-open Consulates-General.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QtHHi3B0peYC&lpg=PA80&dq=chung%20hwa%20travel%20service%20hong%20kong&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q=Iran&f=false ''Hong Kong's Transition to Chinese Rule: The Limits of Autonomy''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222105735/https://books.google.com/books?id=QtHHi3B0peYC&lpg=PA80&dq=chung%20hwa%20travel%20service%20hong%20kong&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q=Iran&f=false |date=22 February 2017 }}, Ralf Horlemann, Routledge, 2003, page 78</ref> \n#Consulates of countries which maintained diplomatic relations with [[Taiwan]] were closed.<ref name=\"SCMP Liberia\">[http://www.scmp.com/article/214706/liberian-consulate-forced-close Liberian consulate forced to close] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426075314/http://www.scmp.com/article/214706/liberian-consulate-forced-close |date=26 April 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 10 October 1997</ref> Only South Africa, which was to establish relations with the People's Republic of China from 1998, was allowed to keep its Consulate General open for an interim period.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140109234316/http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/1997/06130x66197.htm Statement on Future South Africa/Hong Kong Relations by the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs, Mr Aziz Pahad, 12 June 1997]</ref>   \n#Hong Kong's [[Aircraft registration#List of countries/regions and their registration prefixes and patterns|aircraft registration prefix]] changed from '''VR''' to '''B''', bringing it into line with mainland China and Taiwan.<ref>[http://www.yearbook.gov.hk/1997/ch15/e15v.htm Hong Kong&nbsp;\u2013 A New Era \u2013 Civil Aviation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060225/http://www.yearbook.gov.hk/1997/ch15/e15v.htm |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''Hong Kong Yearbook 1997'', [[Government of Hong Kong|Hong Kong SAR Government]]</ref>\n#Newspapers, such as the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', changed to heading their pages with \"National\", rather than \"Local\" and 'China', and began including Chinese names in Chinese characters. However, the online edition still uses \"China\" and only displays Chinese names in Roman script.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/news/china China News] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327135325/http://www.scmp.com/news/china |date=27 March 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]''</ref>  \n#A giant golden statue of a ''[[Bauhinia blakeana]]'' was erected in a public space outside the [[Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre]], named [[Golden Bauhinia Square]], along with a [[Monument in Commemoration of the Return of Hong Kong to China|Reunification Monument]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_RRXAAAAMAAJ&q=reunification+monument+hong+kong+bauhinia&dq=reunification+monument+hong+kong+bauhinia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDu-XU2evLAhVGtxQKHWq4C1wQ6AEIRzAE ''Summary of World Broadcasts: Asia, Pacific''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222130304/https://books.google.com/books?id=_RRXAAAAMAAJ&q=reunification+monument+hong+kong+bauhinia&dq=reunification+monument+hong+kong+bauhinia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDu-XU2evLAhVGtxQKHWq4C1wQ6AEIRzAE |date=22 December 2016 }}, Issues 3986\u20133998, page G-8</ref> \n|-\n|}\n\n===Rose Garden Project===\n{{Main|Port and Airport Development Strategy}}\n\nAfter the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]], the Hong Kong government proposed a grand \"Rose Garden Project\" to restore faith and solidarity among the residents.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=TDkZAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Rose+Garden+Project%22+Hong+Kong&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Rose+Garden+Project%22+ ''Before and After Suzie: Hong Kong in Western Film and Literature''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222170827/https://books.google.com/books?id=TDkZAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Rose+Garden+Project%22+Hong+Kong&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Rose+Garden+Project%22+ |date=22 February 2017 }}, Thomas Y. T. Luk, James P. Rice\nNew Asia College, The Chinese University of Hong Kong, 2002, page 88</ref> As the construction of the new [[Hong Kong International Airport]] would extend well after the handover, Governor Wilson met PRC Premier [[Li Peng]] in Beijing to ease the mind of the PRC government.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fQofAAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA195&ots=uNIpAfQ-bW&dq=Governor%20Wilson%20met%20PRC%20Premier%20Li%20Peng%20in%20Beijing&pg=PA195#v=onepage&q=Governor%20Wilson%20met%20PRC%20Premier%20Li%20Peng%20in%20Beijing&f=true ''A Concise History of Hong Kong''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222164350/https://books.google.com/books?id=fQofAAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA195&ots=uNIpAfQ-bW&dq=Governor%20Wilson%20met%20PRC%20Premier%20Li%20Peng%20in%20Beijing&pg=PA195#v=onepage&q=Governor%20Wilson%20met%20PRC%20Premier%20Li%20Peng%20in%20Beijing&f=true |date=22 February 2017 }}, John M. Carroll, Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, 7 June 2007, page 195</ref>\n\nThe communist press published stories that the project was an evil plan to bleed Hong Kong dry before the handover, leaving the territory in serious debt.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=v6ZszKvUkjAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bray,+Denis.+Hong+Kong+Metamorphosis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9OFcUoH7DZKihgeJjIDIAg&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=Rose%20Garden%20Project&f=false ''Hong Kong Metamorphisis''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222102850/https://books.google.com/books?id=v6ZszKvUkjAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bray,+Denis.+Hong+Kong+Metamorphosis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9OFcUoH7DZKihgeJjIDIAg&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=Rose%20Garden%20Project&f=false |date=22 December 2016 }} Denis Bray, Hong Kong University Press, 2001, page 232</ref> After three years of negotiations, Britain and the PRC finally reached an agreement over the construction of the new airport, and signed a Memorandum of Understanding.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=h7LtAAAAMAAJ&dq=Britain+and+the+PRC+finally+reached+an+agreement+over+the+construction+of+the+new+airport%2C+and+signed+a+Memorandum+of+Understanding&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Memorandum+of+Understanding%22 ''A Modern History of Hong Kong''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222224418/https://books.google.com/books?id=h7LtAAAAMAAJ&dq=Britain+and+the+PRC+finally+reached+an+agreement+over+the+construction+of+the+new+airport%2C+and+signed+a+Memorandum+of+Understanding&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Memorandum+of+Understanding%22 |date=22 February 2017 }}, Steve Yui-Sang Tsang, Palgrave Macmillan, 2004, page 253</ref> Removing hills and reclaiming land, it took only a few years to construct the new airport.\n\n===Views of the Kowloon Walled City===\n{{Main|Kowloon Walled City}}\n\nThe Walled City was originally a single fort built in the mid-19th century on the site of an earlier 17th century watch post on the [[Kowloon Peninsula]] of Hong Kong.<ref>Lim, Patricia. [2002] (2002). Discovering Hong Hong's Cultural Heritage. Central, Hong Kong: Oxford University Press. ISBN Volume One 0-19-592723-0</ref> After the ceding of [[Hong Kong Island]] to Britain in 1842 ([[Treaty of Nanjing]]), [[Manchu]] [[Qing]] Dynasty authorities of China felt it necessary for them to establish a military and administrative post to rule the area and to check further British influence in the area.\n\nThe 1898 Convention which handed additional parts of Hong Kong (the [[New Territories]]) to Britain for 99 years excluded the Walled City, with a population of roughly 700. It stated that China could continue to keep troops there, so long as they did not interfere with Britain's temporary rule.\n\nBritain quickly went back on this unofficial part of the agreement, attacking Kowloon Walled City in 1899, only to find it deserted. They did nothing with it, or the outpost, and thus posed the question of Kowloon Walled City's ownership squarely up in the air. The outpost consisted of a [[yamen]], as well as buildings which grew into low-lying, densely packed neighbourhoods from the 1890s to 1940s.\n\nThe [[enclave]] remained part of Chinese territory despite the turbulent events of the early 20th century that saw the fall of the Qing government, the establishment of the [[Republic of China (1912\u201349)|Republic of China]] and later, a [[People's Republic of China|Communist Chinese government]] (PRC).\n\nSquatters began to occupy the Walled City, resisting several attempts by Britain in 1948 to drive them out. The Walled City became a haven for criminals and drug addicts, as the [[Hong Kong Police]] had no right to enter the City and China refused maintainability. The 1949 foundation of the People's Republic of China added thousands of refugees to the population, many from [[Guangdong]]; by this time, Britain had had enough, and simply adopted a \"hands-off\" policy.\n\nA murder that occurred in Kowloon Walled City in 1959 set off a small diplomatic crisis, as the two nations each tried to get the other to accept responsibility for a vast tract of land now virtually ruled by anti-[[Qing dynasty|Manchurian]] [[Triad society|Triads]].\n\nAfter the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration|Joint Declaration in 1984]], the PRC allowed British authorities to demolish the City and resettle its inhabitants. The mutual decision to tear down the walled city was made in 1987.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9NYyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kO8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1193%2C4443534 Hong Kong's infamous Walled City to be converted into park area], Michael Browning, [[Knight Ridder]], ''Ottawa Citizen'', 29 January 1987, page c9</ref> The government spent up to [[HKD|HK$]] 3&nbsp;billion to resettle the residents and shops.\n\nSome residents were not satisfied with the compensation, and some even obstructed the demolition in every possible way.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YsExAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3YwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6688%2C969556 Riot police evict Hong Kong residents from Walled City] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630155905/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YsExAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3YwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6688%2C969556 |date=30 June 2016 }}, [[Associated Press]], ''[[Boca Raton News|The News]]'', 3 July 1992</ref> Ultimately, everything was settled, and the Walled City became a park.<ref>[http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/kwcp/index.html Kowloon Walled City Park \u2013 History/Background] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323040215/http://www.lcsd.gov.hk/en/parks/kwcp/index.html |date=23 March 2016 }}, [[Leisure and Cultural Services Department]]</ref>\n\n==International reaction==\nThe [[Republic of China on Taiwan]] promulgated the ''Laws and Regulations Regarding Hong Kong & Macao Affairs'' on 2 April 1997 by [[President of the Republic of China|Presidential]] Order, and the [[Executive Yuan]] on 19 June 1997 ordered the provisions pertaining to Hong Kong to take effect on 1 July 1997.<ref>[[Ministry of Justice (Republic of China)]]: [http://law.moj.gov.tw/Eng/LawClass/LawHistory.aspx?PCode=Q0010003 Laws and Regulations Regarding Hong Kong & Macao Affairs: Legislative History]</ref>\n\nThe [[United States\u2013Hong Kong Policy Act]] or more commonly known as the Hong Kong Policy Act ([[Public law|PL]] no. 102-383m 106 Stat. 1448) is a 1992 act enacted by the [[United States Congress]].  It allows the United States to continue to treat Hong Kong separately from China for matters concerning trade export and economics control after the handover.<ref name=\"HKrev\">Hong Kong's reversion to China: effective monitoring critical to assess U.S. DIANE Publishing. {{ISBN|1-4289-7837-2}}</ref>\n\nThe United States was represented by then Secretary of State [[Madeleine Albright]] at the [[Hong Kong handover ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Albright To Attend Hong Kong Transfer Ceremony |url=http://edition.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1997/04/16/albright.hongkong/ |publisher=CNN |date=16 April 1997 |accessdate=27 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128152038/http://edition.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1997/04/16/albright.hongkong/ |archive-date=28 January 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, she partially boycotted it in protest of China's dissolution of the democratically elected Hong Kong legislature.<ref>{{cite news |title=Smooth Hong Kong handover lifts China's image |url=http://articles.cnn.com/1997-07-15/world/9707_15_hongkong_1_handover-beijings-china-policy?_s=PM:WORLD |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119115910/http://articles.cnn.com/1997-07-15/world/9707_15_hongkong_1_handover-beijings-china-policy?_s=PM:WORLD |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 January 2013 |publisher=CNN |date=15 July 1997 |accessdate=27 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==End of the British Empire==\n{{Seealso|Decolonization|List of countries that have gained independence from the United Kingdom}}\n[[File:HK 71 Match BHKG1.jpg|thumb|Hong Kong 1 July march with [[Flag of Hong Kong (1959\u20131997)|British Hong Kong flag]]]]\nThe handover marked the end of British rule in Hong Kong, which was Britain's last substantial overseas territory.  Although in statute law set down by [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], British Hong Kong had no status of pre-eminence vis-a-vis the other [[British Dependent Territories]] (as they were then classified before the term British Overseas Territory was [[British Overseas Territories Act 2002|introduced in 2002]]), Hong Kong was by far the most populous and economically potent.  In 1997 the colony had a population of approximately 6.5 million, which represented roughly 97% of the population of the British Dependent Territories as a whole at that time (the next largest, [[Bermuda]], having a 1997 population of approximately only 62,000).  With a [[gross domestic product]] of approximately US$180 billion in the last year of British rule,<ref>{{cite web |title=Hong Kong SAR, China  |url=https://data.worldbank.org/country/hong-kong-sar-china?view=chart |website=World Bank |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> Hong Kong's economy was roughly 11% the size of Britain's.<ref>{{cite web |title=United Kingdom |url=https://data.worldbank.org/country/united-kingdom |website=World Bank |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>  Therefore, although the economies of the [[Economy of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] and [[Economy of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] were measured separately, the Handover did mean the British economy in its very broadest sense became substantially smaller (by comparison, the acquisition of Hong Kong boosted the size of the [[Economy of the People's Republic of China|Chinese economy]], which was then smaller than the United Kingdom's, by 18.4%).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bland and Pong |first1=Ben and Jane |title=Hong Kong since the handover in charts |url=https://www.ft.com/content/7e2422b8-5bb1-11e7-9bc8-8055f264aa8b |accessdate=21 September 2018 |agency=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> As a comparator to Hong Kong, in 2017 Bermuda (as with population, the economically largest of Britain's remaining territories) had a GDP of only US$4.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gross Domestic Product \u2013 2017 highlights |url=https://www.gov.bm/sites/default/files/GDP%202017%20annual%20publication.pdf |publisher=Government of Bermuda, Department of Statistics |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe cession of Hong Kong meant that Britain's remaining territories (excepting the United Kingdom itself) henceforth consisted either of uninhabited lands (for instance the [[British Antarctic Territory]]), small islands or micro land masses (such as [[Montserrat]]), territories used as military bases (for example [[Akrotiri and Dhekelia]] on the island of [[Cyprus]], itself a former [[crown colony]] granted independence in 1960), or a combination of the latter two (like [[Gibraltar]]). And while many of Britain's remaining territories are significant to the global economy by virtue of being [[offshore financial centre]]s (Bermuda, the [[British Virgin Islands]], and the [[Cayman Islands]] being the most prominent of these), their economies are insubstantial.  Demographically, they are also tiny compared to Britain, with a collective population of less than 0.4% of Britain's 2017 population of 66 millions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Population estimates |url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/populationestimates |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> As of 2018 the combined population of Britain's remaining fourteen Overseas Territories is only approximately 250,000, which is less than all but three [[districts of Hong Kong]], and roughly equal to that of the [[City of Westminster]]\n\nConsequently, because ceding Hong Kong came at the end of half a century of decolonisation, and because the handover meant that the United Kingdom became without significant overseas territories, [[dominions]], or [[colonies]] for the first time in its history ([[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]], having been bequeathed the incipient domains of its later empire by inheriting the [[English overseas possessions|colonial possessions]] of the [[Kingdom of England]] upon the passing of the [[Acts of Union 1707]], always having been an imperial power, [[ab initio]]) the handover of Hong Kong to China is regarded by some as marking the conclusion of the [[British Empire]], with 1 July 1997 being its end date and the handover ceremony being its last diplomatic act.\n\n==In popular culture==\nScholars have begun to study the complexities of the transfer as shown in the popular media, such as films, television and video and online games.  For example, Hong Kong director [[Fruit Chan]] made a sci-fi thriller ''[[The Midnight After]]'' (2014) that stressed the sense of loss and alienation represented by survivors in an apocalyptic Hong Kong. Chan infuses a political agenda in the film by playing on Hong Kongers' collective anxiety towards communist China.<ref>Chia-rong Wu, \"Hong Kong Identity in Question: Fruit Chan's Uncanny Narrative and (Post-)97 Complex.\" ''American Journal of Chinese Studies'' (April 2017), Vol. 24 Issue 1, pp 43\u201356.</ref>  Yiman Wang has argued that America has viewed China through the prisms of films from Shanghai and Hong Kong, with a recent emphasis on futuristic disaster films set in Hong Kong after the transfer goes awry.<ref>Yiman Wang, ''Remaking Chinese Cinema: Through the Prism of Shanghai, Hong Kong, and Hollywood'' (2014) pp 114, 131</ref> \n*The handover is central to the plot of the 1998 action film ''[[Rush Hour (1998 film)|Rush Hour]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=YOWdAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=Rush+Hour+(1998+film)+hong+kong+british&source=bl&ots=qbKm3Xei9j&sig=q5F1cjpS9sjyik_Yx5Q77vfqOow&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2y87t9O3LAhWMPBQKHYvcBQAQ6AEIRTAH#v=onepage&q=Rush%20Hour%20(1998%20film)%20hong%20kong%20british&f=false China on Screen: Cinema and Nation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222111113/https://books.google.com/books?id=YOWdAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=Rush+Hour+(1998+film)+hong+kong+british&source=bl&ots=qbKm3Xei9j&sig=q5F1cjpS9sjyik_Yx5Q77vfqOow&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2y87t9O3LAhWMPBQKHYvcBQAQ6AEIRTAH#v=onepage&q=Rush%20Hour%20(1998%20film)%20hong%20kong%20british&f=false |date=22 December 2016 }}, Chris Berry, Mary Ann Farquhar, Columbia University Press, 2006, page 2</ref><ref name=\"Singh 2016\">{{cite web|first1=Harminder|last1=Singh|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education-community/article/1983718/everything-you-need-know-about-hong-kongs-return|title=Everything you need to know about Hong Kong's return to Chinese sovereignty|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|publisher=[[Alibaba Group]]|date=1 July 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018010140/http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education-community/article/1983718/everything-you-need-know-about-hong-kongs-return|archive-date=18 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*It is also mentioned in another 1998 film\u2014''[[Knock Off (film)|Knock Off]]''.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Knock-Off-Rob-Schneider/dp/B000I9YUY0 ''Knock Off'' 1998] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508072910/http://www.amazon.com/Knock-Off-Rob-Schneider/dp/B000I9YUY0 |date=8 May 2016 }}, [[Amazon.com]]</ref>\n*The handover is the backdrop for \"A Death in Hong Kong\", the first episode the [[Murder, She Wrote (season 10)|tenth series]] of ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007h8j3 A Death in Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312123725/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007h8j3 |date=12 March 2017 }}, [[BBC Two]], 27 February 2009</ref><ref name=\"Singh 2016\" />\n*Hong Kong Cantopop artist [[Samuel Hui|Sam Hui]] has made numerous references to 1997 including the song \"Could Not Care Less About 1997\" (\u8a71\u77e5\u4f6097).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MLT4fstT_Tc |title=Sam Hui \u8a31\u51a0\u5091 \u2013 \u8a71\u77e5\u4f6097 (\u96fb\u5f71\u300e\u65b0\u534a\u65a4\u516b\u4e24\u300f\u4e3b\u984c\u66f2) |access-date=1 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423031249/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MLT4fstT_Tc |archive-date=23 April 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n*Chinese American rapper [[Jin Auyeung]] has a song called \"1997\" in his Cantonese album ''ABC'', which he makes references to the handover, ten years since Hong Kong's return to China.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hqfSgxw--38 |title=Artist : Jin Title : 1997 Album : ABC Track No : 9  |access-date=1 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170416150844/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hqfSgxw--38 |archive-date=16 April 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n*''[[Zero Minus Ten]]'', a [[James Bond]] novel by [[Raymond Benson]], is set largely in Hong Kong during the days leading up to the Handover.<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Zero-Minus-Ten-James-Bond/dp/0340684496 ''Zero Minus Ten'' (James Bond 007)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414143231/http://www.amazon.co.uk/Zero-Minus-Ten-James-Bond/dp/0340684496 |date=14 April 2016 }}, [[Amazon.com]]</ref><ref name=\"Singh 2016\" />\n*The 2012 James Bond film ''[[Skyfall]]'' features [[Raoul Silva|a villain]] who had been an [[MI6]] agent in Hong Kong until the Handover, when he was handed over to the Chinese for his unauthorised [[Hacker (computer security)|hacking]] of their security networks.<ref>[http://www.scmp.com/business/article/1080685/will-james-bond-bow-beijings-censorship Will James Bond bow to Beijing's censorship?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503213927/http://www.scmp.com/business/article/1080685/will-james-bond-bow-beijings-censorship |date=3 May 2016 }}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', 12 November 2012</ref>\n* The ''[[Doctor Who Unbound]]'' audio drama ''[[Sympathy for the Devil (audio drama)|Sympathy for the Devil]]'' by [[Jonathan Clements]] is set on the eve of the Handover and involves an attempted defection by a war criminal, only hours before China takes control.<ref name=\"Singh 2016\" />\n*''[[Hong Kong 97 (film)|Hong Kong 97]]'', a 1994 [[American films|American]] movie starring [[Robert Patrick]], is set in Hong Kong during the 24 hours before the end of British rule.<ref>[https://ew.com/article/1994/11/04/video-review-hong-kong-97 Hong Kong '97] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120080102/http://www.ew.com/article/1994/11/04/video-review-hong-kong-97 |date=20 November 2015 }}, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', 4 November 1994</ref>\n*''[[Hong Kong 97 (video game)|Hong Kong 97]]'', a 1995 Japanese [[homebrew (video games)|homebrew]] [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]] game, is set in Hong Kong around the time of the transition. The player controls Chin ([[Jackie Chan]]), who was called by the Hong Kong government to kill the invading Chinese, including [[Tong Shau Ping]]. The game gained a [[cult following]] due to its [[kuso|very poor quality]] and absurd plot.<ref>[http://kotaku.com/5936454/racism-violence--madness-make-this-awful-hong-kong-game-one-to-remember Racism, Violence & Madness Make This Awful Hong Kong Game One to Remember] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416131853/http://kotaku.com/5936454/racism-violence--madness-make-this-awful-hong-kong-game-one-to-remember |date=16 April 2016 }}, [[Kotaku]], 21 August 2012</ref>\n*The handover of Hong Kong is referenced multiple times and witnessed in the 1997 film ''[[Chinese Box]]'', starring [[Jeremy Irons]] and [[Gong Li]].  The film itself was filmed leading up to and during the handover.<ref name=NYT>[https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A02E7D8143CF934A25757C0A96E958260 Chinese Box (1997) FILM REVIEW; A Meditation on the Meaning of Hong Kong] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724160827/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A02E7D8143CF934A25757C0A96E958260 |date=24 July 2016 }}, Stephen Holden, ''[[The New York Times]]'' 17 April 1998</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Hong Kong}}\n*[[History of Chinese immigration to Canada#Heading into the new millennium|History of Chinese immigration to Canada]]\n*[[Hong Kong people in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Monument in Commemoration of the Return of Hong Kong to China]]\n*[[Transfer of sovereignty over Macau]]\n*[[Hong Kong 1 July marches]]\n*[[Hong Kong\u2013Mainland conflict]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |year=2008 |title=''[[Dicey Morris & Collins|Dicey, Morris and Collins on the Conflict of Laws]]'' |isbn=978-0-421-88360-4 |edition=14th |publisher=Sweet & Maxwell |first1=Lawrence |last1=Collins |author1-link=Lawrence Collins, Baron Collins of Mapesbury |first2=C.G.J. |last2=Morse |first3=David |last3=McClean |first4=Adrian |last4=Briggs |first5=Jonathan |last5=Harris |first6=Campbell |last6=McLachlan |first7=Jonathan |last7=Hill}}\n* {{cite book |year=2008 |first1=J.J. |last1=Fawcett |first2=J.M. |last2=Carruthers |first3=Peter |last3=North |title=Cheshire, North & Fawcett: Private International Law |isbn=978-0-19-928438-2}}\n* Flowerdew, John. ''The final years of British Hong Kong: The discourse of colonial withdrawal'' (Springer, 1998).\n* Lane, Kevin. ''Sovereignty and the status quo: the historical roots of China's Hong Kong policy'' (Westview Press, 1990).\n* Mark, Chi-kwan. \"To \u2018educate\u2019 Deng Xiaoping in capitalism: Thatcher's visit to China and the future of Hong Kong in 1982.\" ''Cold War History'' (2015): 1\u201320.\n* Tang, James TH. \"From empire defence to imperial retreat: Britain's postwar China policy and the decolonization of Hong Kong.\" ''Modern Asian Studies'' 28.02 (1994): 317\u2013337.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://gohongkong.about.com/od/travelplanner/a/hongkongcountry.htm|title=What Country Is Hong Kong in? China or Not?|first=Rory|last=Boland|work=About.com Travel}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/big/0630.html|title=China Resumes Control of Hong Kong, Concluding 156 Years of British Rule|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"auto2\">\"1898 and all that\u2014a Brief History of Hong Kong.\" ''The Economist'', 28 June 1997</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970616070035/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/hongkong/index.htm|date=16 June 1997|title=The Hong Kong handover}} \u2013 [[BBC World Service]]\n* [http://www.hksar20.gov.hk/ Hong Kong SAR's 20th Anniversary]{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} \n{{HKafter1997}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Transfer Of Sovereignty Of Hong Kong}}\n[[Category:History of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:British Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:1997 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:1997 in China]]\n[[Category:1997 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1997 in international relations]]\n[[Category:1990s in Hong Kong]]<!--for lead up in decade--->\n[[Category:China\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Sovereignty]]\n[[Category:July 1997 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Decolonisation]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "link maintenance, refine ref details (not necessary to archive Google content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handover_of_Hong_Kong"}
{"title_page": "Rodrigo de la Serna", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rodrigo de la Serna\n| image              = Rodrigo de la Serna-F\u00e9nix 2017 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize          = 200px\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Rodrigo De la Serna\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|4|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| othername          = \n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1995 - present\n| known_for          = [[The Motorcycle Diaries (film)|The Motorcycle Diaries]], [[Money Heist]]\n| awards             = \n}}\n\n'''Rodrigo de la Serna''' ({{IPA-es|ro\u02c8\u00f0\u027ei\u0263o \u00f0e la \u02c8se\u027ena}}; born April 18, 1976 in [[Buenos Aires]]) is an Argentine actor.\n\nHe is most known for starring in the 2004 [[biopic]] [[The Motorcycle Diaries (film)|''The Motorcycle Diaries'']] as [[Alberto Granado]], a companion of [[Che Guevara]], and in the Spanish [[Netflix]] series ''[[Money Heist]]'' as Palermo.\n\n== Career ==\nDe la Serna started his career in several smaller productions like ''[[Same Love, Same Rain]]'' and ''[[Nuts for Love]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Nueces para el amor (2000) - Ficha t\u00e9cnica, Sinopsis, Im\u00e1genes, Trailer, Actores, Cast {{!}} cinenacional.com|url=https://cinenacional.com/pelicula/nueces-para-el-amor|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 he had his breakthrough in the [[Biographical film|biopic]] [[The Motorcycle Diaries (film)|''The Motorcycle Diaries'']] for which he won a [[Silver Condor]] award for best actor, a [[Independent Spirit Award]] for \"Best Debut Performance\" and earned him a nomination for a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award for Best Supporting Actor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmindependent.org/spirit-awards/history/|title=History|website=Film Independent|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2005/film/actor-in-a-supporting-role|title=2005 Film Actor in a Supporting Role {{!}} BAFTA Awards|website=awards.bafta.org|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He played the role of [[Alberto Granado]], the travelling companion of [[Che Guevara]] during their 8-month long journey through [[South America]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.focusfeatures.com/motorcycle_diaries|title=Motorcycle Diaries Movie {{!}} Official Website {{!}} Buy Now {{!}} Focus Features|website=Motorcycle Diaries Movie {{!}} Official Website {{!}} Buy Now {{!}} Focus Features|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOver the years he has starred in several Argentine [[Television show|television series]] such as [[El puntero|''El Puntero'']], [[Tiempos compulsivos|''Tiempos Compulsivos'']], ''[[Sol Negro]]'' and ''[[Contra las cuerdas]]'', for which he was nominated and received several [[Mart\u00edn Fierro Awards]], an Argentine radio and television award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pol-ka.com/productions/compulsive-times|title=Compulsive Times - Polka|website=www.pol-ka.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pol-ka.com/productions/the-social-leader|title=The Social Leader - Polka|website=www.pol-ka.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jorgegalli.com.ar/rodrigo-de-la-serna.php|title=Rodrigo de la Serna representante: JORGE GALLI|website=www.jorgegalli.com.ar|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years he played a leading role in the historical film [[Revoluci\u00f3n: El cruce de los Andes|''Revoluci\u00f3n: El Cruce de los Andes'']] focusing on [[Jos\u00e9 de San Mart\u00edn|Jos\u00e9 de San Martin]] and the [[Crossing of the Andes]], ''[[Chiamatemi Francesco]]'' (''Call Me Francis''), an Italian biographical film about [[Pope Francis]], and the 2018 [[Netflix]] comedy film ''[[Yucat\u00e1n (film)|Yucat\u00e1n]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/cine/revolucion-el-cruce-de-los-andes-nid1363359|title=Revoluci\u00f3n, el cruce de los Andes|date=2011-04-07|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cineuropa.org/en/newsdetail/302341/|title=Call Me Francesco, the story behind the People\u2019s Pope|website=Cineuropa - the best of european cinema|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-capsule-reviews-20190214-story.html|title=Reviews: \u2018Yucat\u00e1n\u2019 sets sail on Netflix; Alex Reid powers \u2018The Bellwether\u2019 and more|date=2019-02-14|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> He also starred in [[Path to Peace|''Camino a la paz'']] (''Path to Peace'') and ''[[Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n]]'', which were both released internationally and de la Serna reveiving a nomination for [[Goya Award for Best New Actor|Best New Actor]] at the [[31st Goya Awards]] for ''Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiosgoya.com/31-edicion/nominaciones/por-categoria/|title=Pel\u00edculas \u00bb Premios Goya 2020|website=www.premiosgoya.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he gained prominence by joining the cast of the successful Spanish television show [[Money Heist]] for its third part as the character Palermo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1155871/Money-Heist-season-3-Who-is-Rodrigo-de-la-Serna-Who-plays-Palermo-La-Casa-de-Papel-netflix|title=Money Heist season 3: Who is Rodrigo de la Serna? Who plays Palermo in La Casa de Papel?|last=Watson|first=Fay|date=2019-07-20|website=Express.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He resumed his role in part 4 which was released on [[Netflix]] in April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2020-04-02/money-heist-netflix-season-4-cast/|title=Meet the cast of Money Heist season 4 on Netflix|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nDe la Serna also starred in a few theatre productions in Argentina including [[Lluvia Constante]] for which he won a [[Premio Florencio]] and most recently ''[[El Farmer]]'' in the [[Teatro La Comedia]] in Buenos Aires in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.garaytalent.com/actores/rodrigo-de-la-serna|title=Rodrigo de la Serna - Garay Talent - Representante de actores y directores|website=www.garaytalent.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/teatro/lluvia-constante-nid1382418|title=Lluvia constante|date=2011-06-18|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/cultura/2019/10/11/el-farmer-o-el-comienzo-del-mito-de-juan-manuel-de-rosas/|title=\"El Farmer\" o el comienzo del mito de Juan Manuel de Rosas|last=de 2019|first=Por Pompeyo Audivert 11 de octubre|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nHe is part of the music group ''[[El Yotivenco]]'', which formed in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glamourpath.com/rodrigo-de-la-serna|title=Meet Rodrigo de la Serna - BAFTA Award Winning Argentine Actor|date=2019-12-24|website=glamourpath.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cck.gob.ar/eventos/rodrigo-de-la-serna-y-el-yotivenco_2206|title=CCK|website=www.cck.gob.ar|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDe la Serna is in a relationship with the journalist Ludmila Romero with whom he has two children, born in 2019 and 2020. He also has a daughter from a previous relationship with actress [[\u00c9rica Rivas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/personajes/rodrigo-serna-fue-papa-tercera-vez-nid2330057|title=Rodrigo de la Serna y Ludmila Romero fueron padres por segunda vez|date=2020-02-03|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography (selection)==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Filmography<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.garaytalent.com/actores/rodrigo-de-la-serna|title=Rodrigo de la Serna - Garay Talent - Representante de actores y directores|website=www.garaytalent.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n!Year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jorgegalli.com.ar/rodrigo-de-la-serna.php|title=Rodrigo de la Serna representante: JORGE GALLI|website=www.jorgegalli.com.ar|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cybersix]]\n|1995 \u2013 1996\n|-\n|[[Son o se hacen]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Son o se hacen? (Serie de TV) (1997)|url=https://www.filmaffinity.com/es/film954946.html|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|1997 \u2013 1998\n|-\n|[[Campeones de la vida]]\n|1999\n|-\n|[[Same Love, Same Rain|El mismo amor, la misma lluvia]]\n|1999\n|-\n|[[Nuts for Love|Nueces para el amor]]\n|2000\n|-\n|[[Gallito Ciego]]\n|2001\n|-\n|[[Sol negro]]\n|2003\n|-\n|[[The Motorcycle Diaries (film)|The Motorcycle Diaries]]\n|2004\n|-\n|[[Botines]]\n|2005\n|-\n|[[Hermanos y detectives]]\n|2006\n|-\n|[[El Torc\u00e1n]]\n|2009\n|-\n|[[Lo que el tiempo nos dej\u00f3]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/television/lo-que-el-tiempo-nos-dejo-vive-la-historia-argentina-nid1300028|title=Lo que el tiempo nos dej\u00f3 vive la historia argentina|date=2010-09-01|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|2010\n|-\n|[[Revoluci\u00f3n: El cruce de los Andes|San Mart\u00edn: El Cruce de los Andes]]\n|2010\n|-\n|[[Contra las cuerdas]]\n|2010 - 2011\n|-\n|[[M\u00eda (film)|M\u00eda]]\n|2011\n|-\n|[[El puntero|El Puntero]]\n|2011\n|-\n|[[Tiempos compulsivos]]\n|2012 - 2013\n|-\n|[[Path to Peace|Camino a la paz]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gemafilms.com/en/portfolio/camino-a-la-paz-en/|title=CAMINO A LA PAZ \u2013 Gema Films|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n|2015\n|-\n|[[Chiamatemi Francesco]]\n|2015\n|-\n|[[Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telecinco.es/t5cinema/cine-2016/cien-anos-de-perdon/primeras-imagenes-Cien-anos-perdon_0_2070075396.html|title=Primeras im\u00e1genes: 'Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n', el nuevo thriller de Daniel Calparsoro|date=2015-10-19|website=telecinco|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|2016\n|-\n|[[The Intouchables|Inseparables]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Inseparables (2016) - Ficha t\u00e9cnica, Sinopsis, Im\u00e1genes, Trailer, Actores, Cast {{!}} cinenacional.com|url=https://cinenacional.com/pelicula/inseparables|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|2016\n|-\n|[[El Lobista]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pol-ka.com/productions/the-lobbyst|title=The Lobbyst - Polka|website=www.pol-ka.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|2018\n|-\n|[[Yucat\u00e1n (film)|Yucat\u00e1n]]\n|2018\n|-\n|[[Money Heist]]\n|2019\u2013present\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cinenacional name|id=rodrigo-de-la-serna|old_id=11551|name=Rodrigo de la Serna}}\n* {{IMDb name}}{{External links|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serna, Rodrigo De La}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Argentine male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:20th-century Argentine male actors]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rodrigo de la Serna\n| image              = Rodrigo de la Serna-F\u00e9nix 2017 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize          = 200px\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Rodrigo De la Serna\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|4|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| othername          = \n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1995 - present\n| known_for          = [[The Motorcycle Diaries (film)|The Motorcycle Diaries]], [[Money Heist]]\n| awards             = \n}}\n\n'''Rodrigo de la Serna''' ({{IPA-es|ro\u02c8\u00f0\u027ei\u0263o \u00f0e la \u02c8se\u027ena}}; born April 18, 1976 in [[Buenos Aires]]) is an Argentine actor.\n\nHe is most known for starring in the 2004 [[biopic]] [[The Motorcycle Diaries (film)|''The Motorcycle Diaries'']] as [[Alberto Granado]], a companion of [[Che Guevara]], and in the Spanish [[Netflix]] series ''[[Money Heist]]'' as Palermo.\n\n== Career ==\nDe la Serna started his career in several smaller productions like [[Same Love, Same Rain|''Same Love, Same Rain'']] and [[Nuts for Love|''Nuts for Love'']].<ref>{{Citation|title=Nueces para el amor (2000) - Ficha t\u00e9cnica, Sinopsis, Im\u00e1genes, Trailer, Actores, Cast {{!}} cinenacional.com|url=https://cinenacional.com/pelicula/nueces-para-el-amor|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 he had his breakthrough in the [[Biographical film|biopic]] [[The Motorcycle Diaries (film)|''The Motorcycle Diaries'']] for which he won a [[Silver Condor]] award for best actor, a [[Independent Spirit Award]] for \"Best Debut Performance\" and earned him a nomination for a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award for Best Supporting Actor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmindependent.org/spirit-awards/history/|title=History|website=Film Independent|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2005/film/actor-in-a-supporting-role|title=2005 Film Actor in a Supporting Role {{!}} BAFTA Awards|website=awards.bafta.org|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He played the role of [[Alberto Granado]], the travelling companion of [[Che Guevara]] during their 8-month long journey through [[South America]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.focusfeatures.com/motorcycle_diaries|title=Motorcycle Diaries Movie {{!}} Official Website {{!}} Buy Now {{!}} Focus Features|website=Motorcycle Diaries Movie {{!}} Official Website {{!}} Buy Now {{!}} Focus Features|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOver the years he has starred in several Argentine [[Television show|television series]] such as [[El puntero|''El Puntero'']], [[Tiempos compulsivos|''Tiempos Compulsivos'']], ''[[Sol Negro]]'' and ''[[Contra las cuerdas]]'', for which he was nominated and received several [[Mart\u00edn Fierro Awards]], an Argentine radio and television award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pol-ka.com/productions/compulsive-times|title=Compulsive Times - Polka|website=www.pol-ka.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pol-ka.com/productions/the-social-leader|title=The Social Leader - Polka|website=www.pol-ka.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jorgegalli.com.ar/rodrigo-de-la-serna.php|title=Rodrigo de la Serna representante: JORGE GALLI|website=www.jorgegalli.com.ar|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years he played a leading role in the historical film [[Revoluci\u00f3n: El cruce de los Andes|''Revoluci\u00f3n: El Cruce de los Andes'']] focusing on [[Jos\u00e9 de San Mart\u00edn|Jos\u00e9 de San Martin]] and the [[Crossing of the Andes]], [[Chiamatemi Francesco|''Chiamatemi Francesco'']] (''Call Me Francis''), an Italian biographical film about [[Pope Francis]], and the 2018 [[Netflix]] comedy film ''[[Yucat\u00e1n (film)|Yucat\u00e1n]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/cine/revolucion-el-cruce-de-los-andes-nid1363359|title=Revoluci\u00f3n, el cruce de los Andes|date=2011-04-07|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cineuropa.org/en/newsdetail/302341/|title=Call Me Francesco, the story behind the People\u2019s Pope|website=Cineuropa - the best of european cinema|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-capsule-reviews-20190214-story.html|title=Reviews: \u2018Yucat\u00e1n\u2019 sets sail on Netflix; Alex Reid powers \u2018The Bellwether\u2019 and more|date=2019-02-14|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> He also starred in [[Path to Peace|''Camino a la paz'']] (''Path to Peace'') and [[Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n|''Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n'']], which were both released internationally and de la Serna reveiving a nomination for [[Goya Award for Best New Actor|Best New Actor]] at the [[31st Goya Awards]] for ''Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiosgoya.com/31-edicion/nominaciones/por-categoria/|title=Pel\u00edculas \u00bb Premios Goya 2020|website=www.premiosgoya.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he gained prominence by joining the cast of the successful Spanish television show [[Money Heist]] for its third part as the character Palermo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1155871/Money-Heist-season-3-Who-is-Rodrigo-de-la-Serna-Who-plays-Palermo-La-Casa-de-Papel-netflix|title=Money Heist season 3: Who is Rodrigo de la Serna? Who plays Palermo in La Casa de Papel?|last=Watson|first=Fay|date=2019-07-20|website=Express.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He resumed his role in part 4 which was released on [[Netflix]] in April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2020-04-02/money-heist-netflix-season-4-cast/|title=Meet the cast of Money Heist season 4 on Netflix|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nDe la Serna also starred in a few theatre productions in Argentina including [[Lluvia Constante]] for which he won a [[Premio Florencio]] and most recently [[El Farmer|''El Farmer'']] in the [[Teatro La Comedia]] in Buenos Aires in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.garaytalent.com/actores/rodrigo-de-la-serna|title=Rodrigo de la Serna - Garay Talent - Representante de actores y directores|website=www.garaytalent.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/teatro/lluvia-constante-nid1382418|title=Lluvia constante|date=2011-06-18|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/cultura/2019/10/11/el-farmer-o-el-comienzo-del-mito-de-juan-manuel-de-rosas/|title=\u201cEl Farmer\u201d o el comienzo del mito de Juan Manuel de Rosas|last=de 2019|first=Por Pompeyo Audivert 11 de octubre|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nHe is part of the music group ''[[El Yotivenco]]'', which formed in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glamourpath.com/rodrigo-de-la-serna|title=Meet Rodrigo de la Serna - BAFTA Award Winning Argentine Actor|date=2019-12-24|website=glamourpath.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cck.gob.ar/eventos/rodrigo-de-la-serna-y-el-yotivenco_2206|title=CCK|website=www.cck.gob.ar|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nDe la Serna is in a relationship with the journalist Ludmila Romero with whom he has two children, born in 2019 and 2020. He also has a daughter from a previous relationship with actress [[\u00c9rica Rivas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/personajes/rodrigo-serna-fue-papa-tercera-vez-nid2330057|title=Rodrigo de la Serna y Ludmila Romero fueron padres por segunda vez|date=2020-02-03|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography (selection)==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Filmography<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.garaytalent.com/actores/rodrigo-de-la-serna|title=Rodrigo de la Serna - Garay Talent - Representante de actores y directores|website=www.garaytalent.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n!Year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jorgegalli.com.ar/rodrigo-de-la-serna.php|title=Rodrigo de la Serna representante: JORGE GALLI|website=www.jorgegalli.com.ar|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cybersix]]\n|1995 \u2013 1996\n|-\n|[[Son o se hacen]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Son o se hacen? (Serie de TV) (1997)|url=https://www.filmaffinity.com/es/film954946.html|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|1997 \u2013 1998\n|-\n|[[Campeones de la vida]]\n|1999\n|-\n|[[Same Love, Same Rain|El mismo amor, la misma lluvia]]\n|1999\n|-\n|[[Nuts for Love|Nueces para el amor]]\n|2000\n|-\n|[[Gallito Ciego]]\n|2001\n|-\n|[[Sol negro]]\n|2003\n|-\n|[[The Motorcycle Diaries (film)|The Motorcycle Diaries]]\n|2004\n|-\n|[[Botines]]\n|2005\n|-\n|[[Hermanos y detectives]]\n|2006\n|-\n|[[El Torc\u00e1n]]\n|2009\n|-\n|[[Lo que el tiempo nos dej\u00f3]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/television/lo-que-el-tiempo-nos-dejo-vive-la-historia-argentina-nid1300028|title=Lo que el tiempo nos dej\u00f3 vive la historia argentina|date=2010-09-01|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|2010\n|-\n|[[Revoluci\u00f3n: El cruce de los Andes|San Mart\u00edn: El Cruce de los Andes]]\n|2010\n|-\n|[[Contra las cuerdas]]\n|2010 - 2011\n|-\n|[[M\u00eda (film)|M\u00eda]]\n|2011\n|-\n|[[El puntero|El Puntero]]\n|2011\n|-\n|[[Tiempos compulsivos]]\n|2012 - 2013\n|-\n|[[Path to Peace|Camino a la paz]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gemafilms.com/en/portfolio/camino-a-la-paz-en/|title=CAMINO A LA PAZ \u2013 Gema Films|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n|2015\n|-\n|[[Chiamatemi Francesco]]\n|2015\n|-\n|[[Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telecinco.es/t5cinema/cine-2016/cien-anos-de-perdon/primeras-imagenes-Cien-anos-perdon_0_2070075396.html|title=Primeras im\u00e1genes: 'Cien a\u00f1os de perd\u00f3n', el nuevo thriller de Daniel Calparsoro|date=2015-10-19|website=telecinco|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|2016\n|-\n|[[The Intouchables|Inseparables]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Inseparables (2016) - Ficha t\u00e9cnica, Sinopsis, Im\u00e1genes, Trailer, Actores, Cast {{!}} cinenacional.com|url=https://cinenacional.com/pelicula/inseparables|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|2016\n|-\n|[[El Lobista]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pol-ka.com/productions/the-lobbyst|title=The Lobbyst - Polka|website=www.pol-ka.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}