mmer Solstice (1981 film)|Summer Solstice]]'' || Joshua Turner ||\n|-\n|}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Henry Fonda}}\n* {{IBDB name|40805}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000020}}\n* {{tcmdb name|63585}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fonda, Henry}}\n[[Category:Male actor filmographies|Fonda, Henry]]\n[[Category:American filmographies|Fonda, Henry]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Henry Fonda and Jane - 1943.jpg|right|thumb|[[Henry Fonda]] and daughter [[Jane Fonda]] in 1943]]\nThis is the filmography of American actor [[Henry Fonda]] (May 16, 1905 \u2013 August 12, 1982). From the beginning of Fonda's career in 1935 through to his last projects in 1981, Fonda appeared in 106 films, television programs, and shorts.\n\nThrough the course of his career he appeared in many critically acclaimed films, including ''[[12 Angry Men (1957 film)|12 Angry Men]]'' and ''[[The Ox-Bow Incident]]''. His roles in [[1940 in film|1940]]'s ''[[The Grapes of Wrath (film)|The Grapes of Wrath]]'' and 1981's ''[[On Golden Pond (1981 film)|On Golden Pond]]'' earned him [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominations he won for the latter).  Fonda made his mark in [[Western (genre)|Westerns]], appearing as [[Frank James]] in ''[[Jesse James (1939 film)|Jesse James]]'' and ''[[The Return of Frank James]]'', and war films such as ''[[The Longest Day (film)|The Longest Day]]'' and ''[[In Harm's Way]]'', and made frequent appearances in both television and foreign productions late in his career. He was [[Bette Davis]]' [[leading man]] in the romantic period piece ''[[Jezebel (1938 film)|Jezebel]]'' and portrayed historical figures [[Abraham Lincoln]] in ''[[Young Mr. Lincoln]]'' and [[Wyatt Earp]] in ''[[My Darling Clementine]]''.  Fonda made four movies with his close friend [[James Stewart]]; ''[[On Our Merry Way]]'', ''[[How the West Was Won (film)|How the West Was Won]]'', ''[[Firecreek]]'', and ''[[The Cheyenne Social Club]]''.  Henry Fonda made no major film appearances between 1948's ''[[Fort Apache (film)|Fort Apache]]'' with [[John Wayne]] and ''[[Mister Roberts (1955 film)|Mister Roberts]]'' with [[James Cagney]] in 1955, seven years later, concentrating instead on the stage; both films were directed by [[John Ford]].\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Feature films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1935 || ''[[The Farmer Takes a Wife (1935 film)|The Farmer Takes a Wife]]'' || Dan Harrow || \n|-\n|  ''[[Way Down East (1935 film)|Way Down East]]'' || David Bartlett || \n|-\n| ''[[I Dream Too Much (1935 film)|I Dream Too Much]]'' || Jonathan \"Johnny\" Street || \n|-\n| rowspan=3|1936 || ''[[The Trail of the Lonesome Pine (1936 film)|The Trail of the Lonesome Pine]]'' || Dave Tolliver || \n|-\n| ''[[The Moon's Our Home]]'' || Anthony Amberton / John Smith || \n|-\n| ''[[Spendthrift (film)|Spendthrift]]'' || Townsend Middleton || \n|-\n| rowspan=4|1937 || ''[[Wings of the Morning (1937 film)|Wings of the Morning]]'' || Kerry Gilfallen ||\n|-\n|  ''[[You Only Live Once (1937 film)|You Only Live Once]]'' || Eddie Taylor || \n|-\n| ''[[Slim (film)|Slim]]'' || Slim Kincaid ||\n|-\n|  ''[[That Certain Woman]]'' || Jack V. Merrick, Jr. || \n|-\n| rowspan=5|1938 || ''[[I Met My Love Again]]'' || Ives Towner || \n|-\n| ''[[Jezebel (1938 film)|Jezebel]]'' || Preston Dillard || \n|-\n| ''[[Blockade (1938 film)|Blockade]]'' || Marco || \n|-\n| ''[[Spawn of the North]]'' || Jim Kimmerlee || \n|-\n| ''[[The Mad Miss Manton]]'' || Peter Ames || \n|-\n| rowspan=5|1939 || ''[[Jesse James (1939 film)|Jesse James]]'' || [[Frank James]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Let Us Live]]'' || Brick Tennant || \n|-\n| ''[[The Story of Alexander Graham Bell]]'' || [[Thomas A. Watson|Thomas Watson]] || \n|-\n| ''[[Young Mr. Lincoln]]'' || [[Abraham Lincoln]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Drums Along the Mohawk]]'' || Gilbert Martin || \n|-\n|rowspan=4| 1940 || ''[[The Grapes of Wrath (film)|The Grapes of Wrath]]'' || Tom Joad || \n|-\n|  ''[[Lillian Russell (film)|Lillian Russell]]'' || [[Alexander Pollo